<FIRST>u a AM-TeacherContract 1stLd-Writethru a0781 02-03 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Contract, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0781,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Refuse To Report Official Grades To Protest Contract Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-6, `United Teachers-Los ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with number of teachers joining union action. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Carey
also ... .'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers pressing stalled contract demands
defied threats of withheld paychecks and gave out students' midyear
grades on union report cards Friday rather than report them to the
school district as required.
   The action came after weeks of student demonstrations supporting
the teachers and amid talk of a possible teacher strike. Meanwhile,
a state mediator organized a weekend meeting between the union and
the Los Angeles Unified School District.
   A union spokeswoman said the ``vast majority'' of teachers at
junior and senior high schools refused to report grades to the
school district, as required by school regulations.
   District spokeswoman Tammy Sims said 69 percent of the high
school teachers did not turn in grades. The school system's tally
for junior high teachers was not completed by Friday night, she said.
   United Teachers-Los Angeles printed up 400,000 report cards to
give to students, said spokeswoman Catherine M. Carey.
   ``Both members and non-members are participating,'' Carey said.
   Carey also said the union agreed to a state mediator's urging
that both sides in the long-running dispute meet Sunday.
   On Thursday, union President Wayne Johnson called for a
negotiating session between just the seven school board members and
seven union officers. But the meeting Sunday will include the
district superintendent and the district's chief negotiator.
   The union action on grades involved the 117,477 students in
junior highs, the 119,904 students in senior highs, and secondary
students among the 27,000 students at so-called magnet schools and
centers, Carey said.
   High school seniors have been concerned that the action would
affect their university applications, but Carey said those students
have been told to take the union report cards to their counselors
for forwarding to universities.
   The spokeswoman said both California university systems and the
Ivy League schools have said the grades will be recognized.
   The contract covers 26,000 classroom teachers and about 6,000
librarians, nurses, counselors and other certificated employees,
Carey said. Of that 32,000, about 22,000 are union members.
   The teachers have been without a contract since June. The union
has been seeking a 12 percent pay hike while the district offered
about 17 percent over three years.
   Current salaries range from starting pay of $23,440 to a maximum
of $43,319. The average salary is $36,600.
   Total district enrollment from the elementary level through high
school is more than 594,000.
</TEXT>
