<FIRST>u a AM-TampaDisturbance 3rdLd-Writethru a0829 02-03 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tampa Disturbance, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0829,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Disturbance Erupts After Drug Suspect Dies in Custody</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with nine arrests, quotes from
mayor, officer treated and released from hospital. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Price, a...'. Deletes 18th graf pvs `The size...' to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SPB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rioters threw rocks and bottles and set trash
bins on fire Thursday in the second night of violence after a
suspected drug dealer died in police custody.
   Police cordoned off the same predominantly black neighborhood
where about 100 officers in riot gear quelled the first outbreak
Wednesday night by about 75 young people, many ages 12 to 14.
   The melee erupted after the arrest of Edgar Allen Price, 40, in
an undercover bust. It took eight police officers to subdue Price.
   Police attempted to ward off further trouble in the College Hill
section Thursday by releasing details of the arrest. Price, who is
black, was not beaten or choked but died of cardiac arrest of
undetermined cause, Deputy Chief Thomas DePolis said at a news
conference.
   At sundown, however, more violence erupted, and 70 officers
responded. Police reported making nine arrests for inciting to riot,
including two juveniles and four members of the African People's
Socialist Party from St. Petersburg. There was no official estimate
of the number of people involved in the unrest.
   ``Many of these people that were arrested tonight were
outsiders,'' said Tampa Mayor Sandy Freedman, who added the
situation was under control late Thursday.
   ``The message is very clear. You come over here and incite riots,
you're going to get arrested,'' she said, vowing to stay in the area
as long as necessary.
   An officer hit by a brick, Sgt. B.J. Curry, was treated and
released at Tampa General Hospital.
   A couple of trash bins were set ablaze and there was sporadic
rock and bottle throwing over a three-hour period, said Sgt. Walter
Sluga.
   On Wednesday night, a grocery store was looted and torched and
two shotgun blasts were fired at a news van. One man was arrested,
and at least four officers injured in the disturbance.
   Price, a 6-foot-3, 300-pound man, struggled with two undercover
officers after an informant made a drug buy in the housing complex,
said police spokesman Steve Cole.
   DePolis gave this account of events:
   When the two plainclothes officers tried to arrest Price, he
picked one up off the ground with one hand and punched the other
repeatedly in the face. Price suffered a 2-inch gash from a blow to
the head, then wrestled free and tried to flee to his girlfriend's
apartment as two backup officers arrived.
   The four officers struck Price with their nightsticks on his arm
and leg, but he again pulled free.
   ``Two more officers arrived and all six officers go tumbling into
the living room fighting with this man,'' DePolis said. The officers
finally managed to slap handcuffs and leg manacles on Price.
   The girlfriend's mother, who uses a pacemaker and a walker, ended
up under the pileup. Paramedics arrived to treat the woman, who was
not identified, the officer with the broken nose and to dress
Price's head wound.
   When the rock- and bottle-throwing began, police put Price in a
cruiser and drove around the block for safety, which took about 45
seconds.
   ``Medical personnel looked in the car and realized he was
suffering cardiac arrest,'' said DePolis. Paramedics treated Price
and rushed him to St. Joseph's Hospital, where he was pronounced
dead less than 90 minutes after the arrest.
   The suspect was carrying 25 pieces of crack cocaine and a loaded
25-caliber derringer in his pockets, Cole said.
   Price, of Houston, was sentenced in 1974 to 50 years on a Texas
robbery conviction and also had a 1967 robbery arrest on his record,
said Cole, adding he did not know the disposition of that case.
   Officials cordoned off four intersections in the 22-block housing
development and summoned 100 police officers and 30 firefighters to
quell the disturbance.
   Gene Bexley, owner of Bexley's Bar-B-Q in the neighborhood, said
some of the young people looted a grocery store before it was set on
fire.
   ``Once they broke it, it took 10 to 15 minutes and they cleared
it out,'' he said. ``Some went in, then things come flying out
windows and doors.''
   The fire forced choir members at the Deliverance Tabernacle
Church to move an organ and other valuables into a truck as a
precaution.
   A young man with a 10-gauge shotgun fired on a WFLA-TV van, said
cameraman Rugene Moore, who was not injured.
   The College Hill neighborhood and housing development have been
the site of frequent confrontations between residents and police in
recent years, including an incident last April when a crowd 400
threw rocks and bottles after the arrest of a robbery suspect, and a
violent outbreak in February 1987 after a 23-year-old black man died
in police custody. A white police officer who used a neck hold to
subdue him eventually was cleared of wrongdoing and the neck hold
was banned.
   ``People feel trapped and they're ready to explode when something
even looks like brutality,'' said Eliott Johnson, pastor of Blessed
Hope Ministries two blocks from the looted grocery store. ``...
We're still sitting on a keg of dynamite down here.'
   Last month, blacks in Miami rioted for several days after a
police officer fatally shot a speeding black motorcyclist.
</TEXT>
