<FIRST>u i AM-Burma-Crash 1stLd-Writethru   02-03 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0842,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Airliner Crashes On Takeoff, 26 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 26 dead, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A domestic airliner taking off from Rangoon
airport crashed Friday after striking a tree, killing 26 people and
injuring the three other people aboard, the state radio said.
   Four more people were injured on the ground when the Burma
Airways Fokker Friendship 27 crashed near housing for families of
air force personnel at Mingaladon Airport, Radio Rangoon said.
   The radio gave engine failure as the cause of the crash, Burma's
fourth since mid-1987. It said the turboprop failed to gain altitude
and hit the tree shortly after takeoff on a flight to Kengtung, 380
miles northeast of Rangoon.
   The aircraft carried 25 passengers, a pilot, co-pilot and two
stewards. The report did not identify the three survivors and
described victims on the ground as family members of air force
personnel.
   All on board were presumed to be Burmese nationals, since
Kengtung is normally off limits to foreigners due to security
problems in the area.
   Burma Airways has lost four Fokker 27s, a Dutch-manufactured
aircraft, since June 21, 1987, when 45 people were killed after a
takeoff from Heho airport in the Shan States.
   All 49 persons on board were killed near Pagan in central Burma
in a crash on Oct. 11, 1987.
   On June 16, a chartered aircraft crashed on a flight from
Myitkyina to Putao in northern Burma and all four persons aboard
were killed.
   Several others crashes occurred in earlier years.
   Burma's tiny fleet of eight aircraft is plagued by a shortage of
spare parts and poor maintenance. After Friday's crash, the airline
has only five Fokker 27s for domestic service and three Fokker 28
jets for international flights.
</TEXT>
