<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     02-03 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producers Reduce Flocks to Raise Egg Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's egg producers are shipping lazy
hens off to the soup factory in an effort to reduce flock sizes, but
even those stern measures are unlikely to return quick profits to
the battered industry.
   Department economists say that losses to egg producers in 1988
were the highest since USDA began keeping those financial records 17
years ago.
   As of Jan. 1, the hen flock that produces table eggs _ the kind
in cartons _ was estimated by USDA at 233.4 million birds, 6 percent
fewer than a year earlier. Overall hen flocks, including hens
producing eggs to hatch new chicks, declined 5 percent to 271.3
million birds.
   ``This was the largest liquidation of layers since the avian
influenza outbreak in 1983,'' says economist Robert V. Bishop.
   Egg consumption is expected to continue its decline to around 235
eggs per person this year from an average of about 243 in 1988 and
259 in 1984. according to the department's Economic Research Service.
   ``Health concerns relating to cholesterol content may be
affecting egg consumption,'' the agency said in a recent report.
``At the same time, egg producers have spent little money on
changing the image of eggs or convincing consumers that eggs are not
just for breakfast.''
   Meanwhile, egg prices at the farm were erratic at times in 1988
but wound up the year averaging 62.1 cents per dozen, about the same
as in 1987.
   But production costs have risen in recent years, and in 1988
producers nationally lost an average of 5.2 cents per dozen.
   Lawrence A. Witucki, another USDA economist, said Thursday in a
telephone interview that the 1988 loss of 5.2 cents per dozen eggs
was the second poor year in a row for egg producers, who barely
broke even nationally with an average net return of 0.2 cents in
1987.
   According to agency records, he said, producers averaged a net
profit of 6.9 cents in 1986 before rising feed costs and other
expenses cut margins. Last year was the first real loss since 1980,
when producers had a negative average of 3.5 cents per dozen, he
said.
   Further, Witucki said, last year's 5.2 cents was the largest
annual loss since the agency began keeping track in 1972, a year
when egg producers lost an average of 2.8 cents per dozen.
   As with any national figures, he said, some egg producers have
made money and others have lost. The yearly averages are general
indicators of how the industry is faring.
   ``We expect more negatives in the first half (of 1989), with feed
prices playing a role,'' Witucki said. ``Hopefully, with normal
crops, feed prices should decline in the second half. But I'm afraid
it doesn't look real bright.''
   All states have some commercial egg production, even Alaska with
an output of about 700,000 eggs last year. The top 10 and their 1988
output in millions of eggs:
   California, 7,718.
   Indiana, 5,644.
   Pennsylvania, 5,302.
   Ohio, 4,477.
   Georgia, 4,294.
   Arkansas, 3,784.
   North Carolina, 3,396.
   Texas, 3,363.
   Florida, 2,758.
   Alabama, 2,596.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is a growing consumer of nuts, but an
Agriculture Department report says American exporters are finding
the market a bit hard to crack.
   The department's Foreign Agricultural Service said that Japanese
imports of tree nuts increased more than 40 percent in five years to
almost 64,000 metric tons worth $220 million in 1987.
   Although U.S. almonds and walnuts are on the upswing in Japan,
some other foreign suppliers are much bigger for certain kinds of
nuts.
   Japan has no quotas on the import of tree nuts, the report said.
But import duties have ranged from 4 percent for almonds to 9
percent for pistachios and macadamia nuts, 10 percent for hazelnuts
and 16 percent for chestnuts and walnuts.
   However, under the U.S-Japan beef and citrus agreement signed
last July, Japan agreed to eliminate the duty on pistachios, lower
it for macadamias and pecans to 5 percent, and reduce the walnut
duty to 10 percent, the report said.
   ``Although the U.S. share of the market for pistachios, hazelnuts
and macadamia nuts are relatively small, sales have increased
notably in the past few years and the future appears bright,'' the
report said.
   Iran is the main supplier of pistachios to Japan, Turkey is the
largest provider of hazelnuts, and Kenya has more than half of the
market for macadamia nuts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has proposed to
sharply increase inspection user fees on imported flue-cured and
burley tobacco.
   J. Patrick Boyle, administrator of the department's Agricultural
Marketing Service, said Thursday that all flue-cured and burley that
is affirmed by importers to be free of prohibited pesticides is
currently assessed fees of 0.1 cents per pound for USDA verification.
   The proposal would raise the fee to 0.35 cents per pound and
establish a minimum fee of $162 per shipment for sampling and
testing.
   Boyle said that tobacco not affirmed by importers to be free of
banned chemicals is currently charged an additional fee of 0.3 cents
per pound to cover USDA's more extensive testing. The proposal would
raise this fee to 0.35 cents.
   The 1985 farm law required USDA to revise its fees to reflect
changing costs in the inspection and testing of imported tobacco, he
said.
   Public comments on the proposed rule changes can be sent by March
6 to: Director, Tobacco Division, Room 502 Annex Building, AMS,
USDA, P.O. Box 96456, Washington, D.C. 20090-6456.
</TEXT>
