<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RecruitingBan     02-03 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Recruiting Ban,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Barred From Recruiting at Law School After Partner Makes Racist
Remarks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in grafs 8-10.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Chicago law school has barred a
prestigious law firm from on-campus recruiting for one year because
a partner made racist, sexist and anti-Semitic remarks during an
interview with a student.
   Geoffrey R. Stone, dean of the law school, commended the
Chicago-based law firm of Baker &amp; McKenzie on Thursday for
displaying ``sensitivity, professionalism and ... integrity'' after
the incident became public.
   But, he added in a statement, ``just as Baker &amp; McKenzie has
assured us it will take strong steps to condemn this behavior and to
prevent its repetition, so too must we take strong steps to protect
our students against insulting and degrading conduct in the
interview process.''
   The ban, which covers the 1989-90 academic year and had been
recommended by the university's Law Students Association, Black Law
Students Association and the Law School Placement Committee, came
nearly a week after initial reports of the job interview.
   ``This is especially painful because we've always taken great
pride in being part of the solution rather than part of the
problem,'' said Robert Cox, chairman of the executive committee at
Baker &amp; McKenzie, one of the world's largest law firms. ``But
obviously, when something like this happens, you must take a look at
yourself again.''
   According to last Friday's edition of the law school student
newspaper, the Phoenix, a partner from Baker &amp; McKenzie later
identified as Harry O'Kane conducted the interview with a black
female law student.
   Neither the law school nor the firm has disputed the account. The
student has not been identified.
   Among other things, O'Kane asked the student during a discussion
about the practice of law how she would react to being called a
``black bitch'' or ``nigger'' by adversaries or colleagues.
   When the student remarked at another juncture that she played
golf, the partner responded: ``Why don't blacks have their own
country clubs?'' He then answered his own question, saying, ``There
aren't too many golf courses in the ghetto.''
   The newspaper also paraphrased O'Kane as remarking he wouldn't
want to belong to a Jewish country club, ``but at least they had
their own.''
   O'Kane declined to comment when reached by telephone Thursday
night at his suburban Arlington Heights home, and referred all
questions to Cox.
   Cox said O'Kane, a partner for 20 years, has taken an
``indefinite leave.'' He said that O'Kane is ``not a racist,'' and
suggested his commments may have been a kind of ``stress test'' for
the applicant.
   ``But let me reiterate there is no attempt to excuse what he did.
We'll deal with what (disciplinary action) is appropriate in the
days ahead,'' he said.
   Baker &amp; McKenzie operates 44 offices in 26 countries and has
approximately 1,300 lawyers worldwide.
   Of the estimated 400 lawyers working in the United States, Cox
said there would be 10 blacks after the current round of hiring.
   Of the firms' 432 partners, Cox said about 30 were women and none
are black; 23, however, are graduates of the University of Chicago
law school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
