<DOCNO> AP890203-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast Bjt   02-03 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Ponders Arab Arms But Has No Peace Plan
Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has begun to weigh a new package of
potential U.S. arms sales to the Arab world even as prospects for
Mideast peace talks remain cloudy.
   The possible purchases under discussion with Bush administration
officials are bound to touch off a row with Israel's supporters.
Saudi Arabia, for instance, might get 315 Abrams tanks, probably the
best in the world, and the United Arab Emirates 40 jet fighters.
   The list is far from final. It's only a wish list _ what the
oil-rich Arab countries and other potential customers would like to
buy. Reaction to the soundings that began last Friday on Capitol
Hill could force changes before the White House makes formal
requests for approval.
   In the meantime, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has
unveiled a proposal to extend autonomy _ but not statehood _ to
Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   The plan was rejected outright by the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which is gaining diplomatic support in Western Europe
and apparently sees no reason to compromise on its demand for a
state carved out of Israeli-held territory.
   Shamir also has not engendered any enthusiasm from the Bush
administration despite his offer to withdraw troops from some of the
population centers on the West Bank and in Gaza once Palestinians
there accept autonomy. The State Department simply has had nothing
to say about the offer.
   In the Camp David agreements 10 years ago, the United States,
Israel and Egypt called for autonomy for the Palestinians. After
five years of managing their own local affairs, negotiations would
be opened for a permanent arrangement. All options, including
statehood, would be on the table.
   The idea was to see how living together would work, but Egypt was
ostracized for approving something less than immediate statehood for
the Palestinians and the plan never got off the ground.
   If the Bush administration has another approach in mind it has
not tipped its hand, although Secretary of State James A. Baker III
ruled out U.S. support for an independent Palestinian state at his
Senate confirmation hearing.
   The classified arms list under discussion in Capitol Hill
corridors and over lunches reflects a traditional U.S. approach of
trying to lubricate Middle East diplomacy with weapons.
   A copy obtained Thursday by The Associated Press showed Israel
under consideration for 200 shoulder-fired Stinger missiles, four
helicopters and some new radar and equipment for its jet fighters.
   The potential Arab purchases have far more punch.
   Kuwait, a wealthy Arab state, could receive 200 Abrams tanks,
known also as the M1A1 and considered by experts to be the best in
the world.
   Other key items include 40 Maverick air-to-ground missiles with
an infrared guidance system and electronic warfare gear for Bahrain
and 24 F-16 jet fighters and 100 Mavericks and 100 Sidewinder
air-to-air missiles for Morocco.
   If Bush follows through with specific requests he will have a
battle on his hand. Israel's supporters are concerned that Arab
weapons could be turned against the Jewish state in a Middle East
conflict.
   Congress has the power to block a purchase, but only if a
majority of both the Senate and the House reject a White House
proposal.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, declined to
identify any of the weapons under consideration. He stressed it was
not a ``sale plan,'' but rather the administration's ``best
estimate'' of other countries' weapons needs.
   ``Each item has to be reviewed by this administration,'' Redman
said.
   Israel's supporters were successful during the Carter and Reagan
administration in blocking some U.S. sales to both Jordan and Saudi
Arabia.
   But the skillful management of Baker, then the White House chief
of staff, and other Reagan administration operatives overcame
stubborn resistance in 1981 to the sale of Awacs radar planes to
Saudi Arabia which the Senate approved 52-48.
   The White House, in a cover letter, informed Congress the Saudis
were in the process of deciding whether to request U.S. or European
fighter planes to replace their F-5s in the next decade, the sources
said.
   The letter said the Saudis were considering jet fighters to be
jointly produced by Britain and West Germany and the French Mirage
4000, as well as U.S.-built F-16s and F-18s.
   Besides the Abrams tanks, on the list for the Saudis were seven
multiple-launch artillery rocket systems, for battlefield use, and
seven of the box-type rockets for Kuwait along with 1,500 Tow
anti-tank missiles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid heads the AP's State Department
staff.
</TEXT>
