<FIRST>d a PM-BacktotheFuture     02-03 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Back to the Future,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Universal to Make Two `Back to Future' Sequels Back-to-Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Universal Pictures plans to produce
two ``Back to the Future'' sequels this spring and summer starring
Michael J. Fox, who had the role of the young time traveler in the
original 1985 hit.
   Robert Zemeckis, who directed the first ``Back to the Future,''
will return behind the cameras for both follow-ups, the studio
announced Thursday.
   Most of the original co-stars, including Lea Thompson,
Christopher Lloyd and Tom Wilson, also will be reunited. Filming of
the first sequel will begin on Feb. 20. The two sequels are
scheduled for release in the winter of 1989 and the summer of 1990,
respectively.
   The consecutive filming schedule will keep production costs down
and take advantage of an extended opening in Fox's busy schedule,
said Tom Pollock, chairman of the MCA Motion Picture Group.
   Fox stars as Alex Keaton the NBC situation comedy ``Family Ties.''
   The original ``Back to the Future,'' in which Fox journeyed back
to the 1950s and had to make sure his parents fell in love, has
grossed $350 million in its domestic and international theatrical
release.
   Zemeckis' last film, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' was last year's
No. 1 movie at the box office.
</TEXT>
