<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-Measles Bjt   02-03 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Measles, Bjt,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Outbreak Blamed On `Toddler Immunization Gap'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-sixth of America's 1988 measles patients
came from Los Angeles County, where an ongoing outbreak among mostly
Hispanic toddlers demonstrates a nationwide need to vaccinate 1- to
4-year-olds, experts say.
   ``We seem to have a toddler immunization gap,'' said Dr. Stephen
Waterman, chief of acute communicable disease control for the county
Department of Health Services. ``A lot of those kids don't get
vaccinated until they go to school,'' where measles shots are
mandatory.
   The extent of the outbreak of the virus-caused respiratory
disease in Los Angeles County was reported by the national Centers
for Disease Control in today's issue of the agency's Morbidity and
Mortality Weekly Report.
   The county last year reported 513 measles cases, 17.5 percent _
or more than one-sixth _ of the nation's total of 2,933, the
Atlanta-based CDC said. Two of the patients, ages 8 months and 23
months, died.
   Waterman, a co-author of the CDC report, said he didn't know how
many measles cases occurred in the county so far this year, but said
the outbreak is continuing at a slower pace.
   Eight unvaccinated children of Samoan descent were brought this
week to two Long Beach hospitals, where two of them died, said Ron
Yukelson, spokesman for Long Beach Memorial Medical Center. Waterman
said he understood they belonged to a religious group opposed to
vaccinations.
   Of the 1988 cases, an ethnic group was identified for 331 of the
Los Angeles County measles patients, and 77.6 percent of them were
Hispanic. Age was known for 353, and of those, 25 percent were
younger than 1, while 40 percent were ages 1 to 4, the CDC report
said.
   The CDC considers 15 months to be the minimum age for
vaccination, and 26 percent fell in the 16-month-old to 4-year-old
age group. But the outbreak prompted Waterman's department last July
to lower the minimum age for vaccination in Los Angeles County to 1
year.
   Infants exposed to the measles in areas where the virus is
endemic, such as Los Angeles, should be vaccinated at 6 months, even
though the vaccine's effectiveness is questionable for children
younger than 1 year, Waterman said.
   Officials in some counties recommend dual vaccinations at 9
months and 15 months, he added.
   The CDC said lowering the minimum vaccination age is an important
way to help control measles in infants.
   ``The routine age for vaccination is 15 months, but in most
states where vaccinations are required for school, you've got that
4{-year period where they are not ... required to have measles
immunization,'' said Dr. Paul Stehr-Green, a CDC measles specialist.
   Waterman said this immunization gap is worst among ``the lower
socioeconomic status population and Hispanics. They just have
variable access to health care. Some of them may be afraid to go to
institutions because they're undocumented (aliens). They may not be
aware they can get the vaccinations for free with no questions
asked.''
   The CDC recommended programs aimed at reaching parents and
children in poor areas and use of churches, schools and mobile vans
as temporary vaccination sites.
   In the late 1970s, CDC measles specialists believed the childhood
disease could be eradicated in the United States by fall 1982. That
goal wasn't met. In the past six years, between 1,497 and 6,282
cases have been reported nationally each year.
   Part of the problem is what researchers call ``non-preventable''
cases _ patients too young for vaccinations to be effective and
those who were vaccinated but still got measles, since at best one
in 20 vaccinations does not provide full immunity. In Los Angeles
County, 58 percent of cases overall were considered non-preventable,
the CDC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearPlants     02-03 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Plants,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longer Delay Seen in Resumption of Nuclear Materials Output</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said restarting the
crippled Savannah River nuclear reactors probably will take longer
than previously forecast, raising new concerns about supplies of a
gas used in making atomic weapons.
   Richard Starostecki, the department's top safety official, told a
Senate Armed Services subcommittee Thursday it was ``not likely''
that even one of the three reactors would be restarted this year as
planned. All three have been shut down since last spring because of
structural, safety and managerial problems.
   The subcommittee was reconvening today for a closed session on
how long the reactors could remain shut down without harming
national security. Among the scheduled witnesses were Gen. Robert T.
Herres, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and Robert C.
Duncan, chairman of the Pentagon's Nuclear Weapons Council.
   ``I expect we're going to get some unpleasant news,'' Sen. Jim
Exon, D-Neb., told Thursday's session.
   Savannah River is the nation's only source of tritium, a
perishable gas used in the production of most U.S. nuclear weapons.
For weeks the Energy Department has said it expected to restart one
reactor by the end of the year, but Starostecki indicated he could
not be sure it would be operating even by January 1991.
   ``A lot of things would have to happen very quickly, and they are
not happening,'' Starostecki said of preparations to meet the
year-end 1989 target.
   Troy E. Wade III, the Energy Department's acting assistant
secretary for defense programs, told the subcommittee at least one
of the reactors would have to be restarted by the end of the year to
avoid a squeeze on supplies of tritium.
   The exact level of current tritium supplies is classified.
   ``It is our goal to resume operations this calendar year,'' Wade
said, adding, ``I'm an optimist.'' He later said a restart could be
accomplished by October at best and that if new problems were
encountered, the target date could slip.
   Wade said in a written statement to the subcommittee that the
effort to resume production of tritium ``is becoming critical''
because of the weapons requirements.
   ``If a reactor is not restarted this year, then the supply of
tritium could be reduced to such an extent that the nuclear
stockpile may be affected,'' Wade said.
   Asked how much confidence he held in the official goal of getting
Savannah River in shape to produce adequate supplies of tritium
until a proposed new generation of reactors comes on line late in
the 1990s, Wade said, ``I wish my confidence were higher.''
   Wade said that by March the department should be able to set a
target date for restarting the K reactor. By then, a department
safety advisory panel is expected to have completed its assessment
of the criteria for restarting the reactor.
   James S. Moore, president of Westinghouse Savannah River Co., a
subsidiary of Westinghouse Electric Corp., told the subcommittee
that his company's own assessment of the safety, technical and
management problems at the plant will be done by March.
   Westinghouse is due to take over April 1 from E.I. du Pont de
Nemours &amp; Co. as operator of the plant, which is owned by the Energy
Department and has been a key link in the nationwide network of
nuclear weapons plants since the late 1940s.
   Some officials voiced doubts about Westinghouse's claim that it
will improve safety and efficiency at Savannah River by bringing in
its own core management team while retaining more than 90 percent of
the 11,000-strong Du Pont workforce there.
   ``It's going to be very difficult to make the level of changes
necessary'' even if Westinghouse expands its core Savannah River
management group to as many as 150 people, said John Ahearne,
chairman of an Energy Department advisory panel on safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
