<DOCNO> AP890203-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceShootings     02-03 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Shootings,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Jose Police Sue City To Beef Up Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Jose Police Officers Association
has filed a lawsuit demanding that 500 officers be added to the
police force in response to the recent deaths of two patrolmen in a
shootout with a transient.
   The association, which represents 970 of San Jose's 1,014-member
police force, said the current level of 1.36 officers per 1,000
residents in San Jose is inadequate to assure reasonable police and
public safety and is far below the national average of 2.58 officers
per 1,000.
   Mayor Tom McEnery called the association's demand for a 50
percent increase, spelled out in a lawsuit filed Thursday,
``fiscally impossible and unrealistic.''
   In making the demand, which is estimated to cost $25 million
annually, the association is relying on a state labor code provision
requiring employers to adopt reasonable safety standards for
workers. It may be the first such use of the provision.
   With a total of 1,500 officers, the force would have about two
officers per 1,000 population. More than 742,000 people live in San
Jose.
   The City Council on Thursday approved McEnery's request for 15
more officers this spring as part of the mid-year budget review. The
mayor said he plans to ask the council for an addition 40 to 50
officers.
   Carm Grande, president of the association, conceded the hiring of
500 officers at one time is ``an impossible project'' and said the
association was willing to negotiate a time period when that many
officers could be added.
   The lawsuit filed in Superior Court, which names as defendants
the city, McEnery, the city manager and the city council, added fuel
to a heated debate over police staffing and procedures since the
Jan. 20 gun battle in which Officers Gene Simpson and Gordon Silva
were killed along with gunman Dale Randell Connors. Simpson was shot
with his own gun when Connors, a transient, grabbed the weapon
during a struggle.
   In its suit, the association also asked for two officers per
patrol car, but Grande said he would drop that demand if the city
agreed to hire 500 more officers.
   McEnery dismissed the need for so many more police, arguing that
despite the recent shootings San Jose is ``the safest big city in
America.''
   An FBI report last July showed that San Jose has only six violent
crimes per 1,000 population, far below Detroit's 25.4 per thousand,
Portland's 22.4, New York's 20.4, Chicago's 19.6 and Los Angeles'
19.1.
   San Jose also had the lowest homicide rate of California's 10
largest cities in 1987, when it had 26 killings. The city had 30
killings in 1988, but already has 13 so far this year, Grande said.
   Grande said the officers chose to fight the city in court after
getting nowhere in negotiations.
   ``The mayor has indicated over the past years that he supports
the police department but we see nothing forthcoming from his
office,'' Grande said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoysShot     02-03 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boys Shot,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Boy Shoots Another, Wounds Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two boys aged 4 and 5 were wounded
with a .38-caliber revolver they found while searching for chewing
gum in a purse belonging to the younger boy's mother, authorities
said.
   Jeremiah Curtis, 4, of Lake George was in serious condition
Thursday in the intensive care unit at St. Francis Hospital after he
was accidentally shot by his companion. The boy's lung collapsed,
and he lost part of his liver and much blood, officials said.
   Benjamin Mabrey, 5, of Florissant was in satisfactory condition
at St. Francis with a hand injury, authorities said.
   The shooting occurred Wednesday when Deborah Curtis and her son,
Jeremiah, stopped at the Mabrey residence in Florissant, 40 miles
west of here, said David Pierson, a Teller County sheriff's deputy.
   When Curtis got ready to leave, Jeremiah and Benjamin jumped into
the back seat of her car while the two mothers stood in the
driveway, Pierson said.
   Jeremiah was looking for chewing gum in his mother's purse when
Benjamin saw the .38-caliber revolver and pulled it out, the deputy
said.
   ``The 5-year-old held the gun up to his hands, like kids do when
they are shooting a water pistol, and the bullet went through his
hand, and then it hit the 4-year-old in the chest,'' Pierson said.
   Deborah Curtis, a real estate agent, said she was carrying the
loaded gun in her purse because she had to show property that
morning with people she didn't know and usually carries the gun
under such circumstances, Pierson said.
   The district attorney's office will investigate the case, said
Jeanne Smith, assistant district attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
