<FIRST>r i PM-Ortega     02-03 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ortega,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Promises To Hand Over Power If Opposition Wins 1990 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA TEJERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government will hand
over power if the opposition wins elections next year, visiting
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega promised.
   Ortega also announced a Central American summit would be held
Feb. 13-14 in El Salvador.
   The president said Thursday night that his Sandinista Liberation
Front was still the largest party in Nicaragua, but said ``whoever
wins the elections will assume power'' _ and cope with the most
battered economy in the region.
   ``If the opposition wins, they will have to assume power and
shoulder the responsibility of fixing the Nicaraguan economy, which
won't be easy,'' he told reporters at the end of a 2{-hour meeting
with President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica.
   Earlier this week, Ortega announced a series of measures to try
to remedy the ravaged Nicaraguan economy, which is reeling from
inflation that reached 20,000 percent in 1988.
   Under the Nicaraguan Constitution, general elections must be held
in November 1990, and Ortega said he has already ``summoned
political parties to present their candidates.''
   Until now, the Sandinistas had refused to speak of handing over
the power they have held since they led a popular uprising that
toppled President Anastasio Somoza in 1979.
   Ortega conducted intense talks on the Central American conflict
with Arias following the swearing-in ceremony for Venezuela's new
president, Carlos Andres Perez.
   Arias called the meeting with Ortega ``very frank'' and said that
he was convinced that ``without a doubt we can reach satisfactory
agreements'' about the thousands of Nicaraugan rebels in Honduras,
one of the main points of contention between Nicaragua and Honduras.
   Each Central American president attended the inauguration except
El Salvador's Jose Napoleon Duarte, who has terminal cancer and sent
his wife in his place.
   Ortega, who said he spoke by telephone Thursday with Duarte,
announced the summit of five Central American nations would be held
Feb. 13-14 in San Salvador.
   The presidents of the five nations _ Costa Rica, El Salvador,
Guatemala, Honduras and Panama _ are expected to follow up on an
August 1987 plan to end warfare in the region.
   On Wednesday, Nicaragua presented new proposals, which include an
amnesty program for the U.S.-backed Contra rebels, reviewing the
cases of political prisoners and turning over some sectors of the
economy to private enterprise.
</TEXT>
