<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-03 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Stocks Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined today against the Japanese
yen, while stock prices firmed to set a record-high close in Tokyo.
   The dollar, after opening lower at 129.50 yen, the day's high,
dipped to 128.85 yen at one point before rebounding and closing the
week at 129.27 yen, down 0.48 yen from Thursday's close.
   Volume was estimated at an active $7.5 billion, compared to an
average daily volume of $5 billion.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 137.62-point winner the previous day, garnered another
178.48 points to close the week at a record 31,685.48. The previous
high of 31,646.13 points was set on Jan. 27.
   Volume was estimated at 2.0 billion shares, a three-month high.
   ``The gradual recovery of the yen, we believe, stems from the
market's expectations that the dollar would somewhat soften after
reaching a peak at a time when major monetary countries in the Group
of Seven are meeting in Washington,'' said Takamasa Yamasaki of the
Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   The dealer said market participants were expecting the seven
countries to reach agreement on the need to maintain currencies at a
stable level as the dollar inched down in value against the yen and
the German mark.
   ``The dollar's overnight retreat in London and New York also
tempted selling of the dollar,'' Yamasaki said.
   Bolstered by active stock purchases by foreign investors, trading
was brisk with construction and related issues showing continued
vigor, said Toshiyuki Nishiguchi of Daiwa Securities.
   Stocks also rallied following news reports that Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, in a meeting in Washington with President
Bush, pledged to further stimulate Japan's domestic demand,
Nishiguchi said.
</TEXT>
