<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-Rebels     02-03 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Rebels,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Predict Rapid Fall of Kabul Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla leader says
President Najib's regime will fold shortly after the Soviet army's
departure, and guerrillas are making plans to secure the major
cities without large-scale attacks.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of the guerrilla group Hezb-i-Islami,
said the government ``will fall in weeks, not months.'' He addressed
a news conference in Peshawar, a frontier city where a seven-party
guerrilla alliance has its headquarters.
   Neighboring Pakistan and Iran, meanwhile, urged the factions to
end their squabbles and form a broad-based government in Kabul when
the Soviet withdrawal is completed. Pakistan and Iran support the
guerrillas.
   The Soviet army is due to complete its withdrawal from
Afghanistan by Feb. 15 under a U.N.-brokered accord signed last
April.
   Hekmatyar said the insurgents were determined to avoid attacks on
Kabul, the Afghan capital, and other cities that would endanger
civilian lives. More than 2 million people, including many refugees,
have crammed into Kabul.
   ``The whole world will be witness to the fact that Kabul will
fall without any major onslaught on the city,'' Hekmatyar said.
   Abdul Haq, a senior military leader, said field commanders will
need plans for the administration of towns and cities that fall to
them, for bringing in food, and keeping water and power systems
operating.
   ``Before we knew only to attack the Russians,'' he said in an
interview. ``Now we must secure the nation, establish law and order,
feed the people, stop looting or killing. It is very difficult.''
   He said the Kabul regime was preparing to defend itself and about
5,000 special troopers had returned from training in the Soviet
Union in house-to-house fighting. The government also is
strengthening such elite formations as the presidential guard and
secret police militia, Haq said.
   Afghanistan's conscript army shows signs of collapse and is of
little use for major operations, he said, adding that government
forces generally are confined to cities and large towns, leaving the
countryside to the guerrillas.
   Haq said the guerrillas must find a way army units can surrender
safely and without fear of reprisal so they will not be compelled to
fight. ``We should not make them fight for survival,'' he said.
   Hekmatyar told the news conference there were arrangements for
securing the fall of major cities without large-scale attacks, but
gave no details. Other guerrilla groups said they were unaware of
such plans.
   Most of the nation's industry, agriculture and public facilities
have been destroyed by the civil war, which began after a communist
coup in April 1978. Soviet soldiers intervened in December 1979 and
an estimated 115,000 were in Afghanistan when the withdrawal began
in May under a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   Members of the seven-party alliance are trying to reach agreement
on a provisional government, but are deeply divided on sharing power
and other important issues.
   Syed Ahmed Gailani, head of the National Islamic Front of
Afghanistan, told reporters Thursday in Islamabad efforts were under
way to form an interim government. He indicated there were problems,
but did not elaborate.
   Ali Akbar Velayati and Sahabzada Yaqub Khan, foreign ministers of
Iran and Pakistan, appealed for guerrilla unity after two days of
meetings in Islamabad that ended Thursday, Pakistani diplomats said.
   A coalition of eight resistance groups is based in Iran. Most of
the guerrillas in Iran are Shiite Moslems, and those in Pakistan
largely follow the predominant Sunni branch of Islam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
