<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Legislation Co-Author Ousted As Head of Subcommittee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman who co-authored the 1986
immigration reform law has been ousted from his post as chairman of
the House Judiciary immigration subcommittee.
   Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli, D-Ky., on Thursday lost the post he held
for eight years on a secret 16-5 vote of committee Democrats. The
10-term congressman from Louisville wrote, with Sen. Alan K.
Simpson, R-Wyo., the Simpson-Mazzoli immigration reform of 1986.
   Mazzoli was replaced in a subsequent 20-1 vote for Rep. Bruce A.
Morrison, an aggressive and ambitious former legal aid attorney from
Connecticut who was elected to his fourth term in November.
   Committee Democrats said after the behind-the-scenes coup that
issues including policy and politics contributed to Mazzoli's
defeat.
</TEXT>
