<HEAD>Prince Charles Coming to White House, Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second member of the British royal family
will visit the United States this month.
   Britain's Prince Charles, heir to the throne whose wife Diana
completed a two-day visit to New York, will visit Washington and
meet with President Bush at the White House on Feb. 17, it was
announced Thursday.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the main purpose of
the prince's visit is to launch the Association of Marshall Scholars
which is marking the 35th anniversary of the first U.S. scholars
going to Britain under a program named for the late Secretary of
State George C. Marshall.
   The prince will make a stopover in the Big Apple for a brief
private visit before coming here to meet with Bush. He will then
travel to Vero Beach and Palm Beach in Florida to play in two
benefit polo matches.
