<HEAD>Kimmitt Selected for Top State Department Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS lede to restore dropped word</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided to fill a top-level
State Department post with the man who oversaw background checks on
Republican vice-presidential hopefuls, the process that ended with
selection of Dan Quayle.
   Robert M. Kimmitt, a 41-year-old Washington lawyer, is Bush's
choice for undersecretary for political affairs. The job is now held
by Michael H. Armacost, who is expected to be named ambassador to
Japan. Bush announced his choice of Kimmitt on Thursday.
   Last summer Kimmitt oversaw background checks on the dozen-plus
Republicans under consideration by Bush as vice presidential
contenders.
   Kimmitt held several posts in the Reagan administration,
including executive secretary to the National Security Council from
1983-1985 and was general counsel of the Treasury Department from
1985-87.
   Bush also picked Morris Berthold Abram, the chairman of the
National Conference on Soviet Jewry, to be U.S. representative to
the European Office of the United Nations, a post that has
ambassadorial rank.
   Abram, 70, a lawyer, is also a former vice chairman of the U.S.
Commission on Civil Rights and was president of Brandeis University
in Waltham, Mass., in the late 1960s. He would succeed Joseph C.
Petrone.
   Other appointments announced Thursday by the White House included:
   _Richard R. Burt, U.S. ambassador to West Germany since 1985, to
be U.S. negotiator for strategic nuclear arms. The post carries an
ambassador's rank.
   _Richard T. McCormack, the U.S. representative to the
Organization of American States since 1985, to be undersecretary of
state for economic and agricultural affairs.
   _Reginald Bartholomew, U.S. ambassador to Spain since 1986, to be
undersecretary of state for coordinating security assistance
programs.
   _Ivan Selin, a computer and management consultant, to be
undersecretary of state for management.
   _Edith E. Holiday, financial operations director for the 1988
Bush campaign, to be general counsel for the Treasury Department.
