<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay 7thLd-Writethru   02-03 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay, 7th Ld-Writethru,a0456,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Revolts, President Stroessner Reported Under Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with infantry, air unit joining rebels. Picks
up graf 5 pvs, `There was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, the
Western Hemisphere's longest ruling leader, was placed under arrest
early Friday by the First Army Corps after it staged a rebellion, a
spokesman for the opposition claimed.
   Infantry divisions in three interior cities and an air force unit
sided with rebels after shooting broke out late Thursday and lasted
more than six hours.
   Stroessner, 76, ``is a prisoner ... and Gen. (Andres) Rodriguez
is in complete control of the situation,'' said the opposition
political leader, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The report on the detention of Stroessner, who has ruled since
1954, could not immediately be confirmed.
   The government issued no statement from the time gunfire began at
a military base and tanks rumbled through this semitropical capital
of 900,000, firing on the headquarters of the police and
presidential guard. Two planes flew low over the capital early
Friday but did not participate in the fighting.
   There was no immediate word on casualties.
   Rodriguez, commander of the powerful First Army Corps, issued a
statement, but it did not mention specific goals or motivations, nor
did it specify whether he was acting against Stroessner personally.
   ``Dear countrymen, appreciated comrades of the armed forces, we
have left our barracks in defense of the dignity and the honor of
the armed forces, for the full and total unification of the ruling
Colorado Party, for the initiation of democratization in Paraguay,
for the respect of human rights, and for the defense of our Roman
Catholic religion.''
   Rodriguez, Paraguay's No. 2 military commander, is identified
with a faction within the ruling party that favors limited
democratic reforms.
   Diplomats and political sources said earlier Thursday that
Rodriguez for undetermined reasons apparently was ordered to give up
his command and retire or accept the post of defense minister. He
refused.
   His statement was broadcast repeatedly by Radio Primera de Marzo,
one of two stations that stayed on the air.
   Residents quickly deserted downtown streets on a steamy summer
night when firefights involving cannon, recoilless rifles and heavy
machine guns broke out in the most serious incident against
Stroessner since he took power.
   The revolt by the army's largest and best-armed corps appeared to
catch Stroessner, the army commander, by surprise.
   Rodriguez, in his statement, asked citizens to remain calm.
   Shooting was first heard at 9:45 p.m. (7:45 p.m. EST) in front of
the First Army Corps' base in Loma Pyta, four miles to the north,
and continued early today.
   Some residents fled their homes, and witnesses reported seeing 40
to 50 tanks leave the base and rumble downtown, where exchanges of
gunfire continued past midnight.
   ``We're all keeping our heads down. We can hear mortar rounds
landing'' at the presidential escort battalion, said a U.S.
diplomat. The embassy and escort battalion are near one another on
Avenida Mariscal Lopez, lined with fine homes and old mango trees.
   The Roman Catholic station Radio Caritas reported early Friday
that heavy smoke could be seen from the quarters of the presidential
guard. Later, the station reported electricity was cut in its sector
of town.
   ``Return home and pray ... that nothing worse happens,'' the Rev.
Pastor Cuquejo, auxiliary archbishop of Asuncion, urged Paraguayans
in a radio address. Later, the bells of the National Cathedral
tolled briefly in the traditional call for prayer.
   The rebellion comes as Stroessner is in ill health following
surgery for a prostate operation five months ago.
   The stocky, vigorous general in recent months has worked fewer
hours, seen fewer people, delegated more work to subordinates and
looked pale and weak.
   The revolt follows a festering dispute within the Colorado Party
between a militant pro-Stroessner faction and traditionalists who
wanted to distance the 100-year-old party from the unpopular,
authoritarian general.
   Domingo Laino, leader of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, the
biggest opposition group, said the fighting ``has something to do
with Rodriguez and (Sabino) Montonaro,'' who is interior minister
and president of the Colorado Party.
   Montonaro leads the party's militant faction, which took over
party leadership in a divisive national congress in August 1987 and
since has purged its opponents from positions of power.
   Rodriguez is considered close to the traditionalist faction.
   The military and the Colorado Party control nearly all facets of
life in the California-sized nation of nearly 4 million between
Brazil, Bolivia and Argentina.
   Stroessner toppled Federico Chaves in 1954. The last unrest in
the military occurred in 1962, when a cadet was slain outside the
capital.
</TEXT>
