<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Explosion     02-03 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Explosion,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Rips Through Shrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong explosion ripped through a shrine in
central Tokyo today, shattering windows and causing part of the
ceiling to collapse, police said. No injuries were reported.
   The pre-dawn blast shattered more than a dozen windows and burned
a covered passageway at the Togo Shrine, said a police official who
spoke on condiiton of anonymity.
   Parts of a fire extinguisher, electrical wires and welding
materials, which could have been used in making a bomb, were found
near the shrine's main building, the official said.
   However, he refused to confirm if police suspect radicals bombed
the Togo Shrine, a Shinto shrine, because of its close association
with militarism and loyalty to the emperor. Ultraleftist groups have
been linked by police to at least seven incidents since the death
last month of Emperor Hirohito.
   The Togo Shrine was founded in memory of Heihachiro Togo, an
admiral during the Russo-Japanese War who commanded the interception
and destruction of the Russian Baltic Fleet in the Battle of
Tsushima in 1905.
   Togo was in charge of educating Hirohito from 1914 until 1924,
and was known for his loyalty to the monarchy. He died in 1934.
   The shrine is located less than a mile from the site where
Hirohito's state funeral will be held Feb. 24.
   Teruo Matsuhashi, a priest at the shrine, said two priests were
staying at the shrine when the explosion occured and 20 more
employees were asleep in an annex, which was undamaged. ``I don't
know why they would want to attack us,'' Matsuhashi said.
</TEXT>
