<DOCNO> AP890203-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BopperMemorial     02-03 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bopper Memorial,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families of Holly, Valens and Big Bopper Gather For Sculpture Unveiling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty years after the music died, the
memories of rock 'n' roll stars Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens and J.P.
``Big Bopper'' Richardson are being revived here in sculptures as
big as life.
   Relatives of Holly and Valens arrived in Port Arthur on Thursday
for a private showing of the sculptures, to be followed by a public
unveiling and concert in Beaumont today on the 30th anniversary of
their deaths.
   ``This is really an honor,'' said Maria Elena Holly, Holly's
widow. ``I have no words to express. It is very touching. He would
be so proud. He would be crying to be in such good company.''
   ``There's no way I can express,'' said Bob Morales of
Watsonville, Calif., Valens' brother. ``He'd love it. It's the most
beautiful thing he could see.''
   The musicians were killed on Feb. 3, 1959, when their small plane
crashed in bad weather near Clear Lake, Iowa, en route to a concert
date in Fargo, N.D.
   At the time, Holly was a giant on the fledgling rock'n'roll scene
and his death became known as ``the day the music died.'' Valens was
a budding star famous for his hit ``La Bamba.''
   Richardson, who was from Beaumont, was known as ``The Big
Bopper'' and recently had earned a gold record for his hit song
``Chantilly Lace.''
   ``He was my hero,'' said John Palmer, a Port Arthur businessman
credited with being the force behind the memorials. ``These guys
were budding stars and then they were gone _ whammo! It's
frightening and it can happen to anybody. To think the only memorial
to these guys is here, it shakes me. I'm so happy.''
   The life-size sculptures were made by Port Arthur artist Doug
Clark for the city's historical society, which began its sculpture
collection last year with Clark's portait of rock queen Janis
Joplin, a Port Arthur native who died in 1970.
   Clark said he worked from videotapes of Richardson and Holly and
from photos of Valens. His pose of the three _ with the Bopper's
arms around Valens and Holly _ is intended to show the trio as if
they were standing for a picture just before boarding the fateful
flight to Fargo.
   ``I don't know that there really is such a picture,'' Clark said.
``But I could just imagine someone getting one last shot before they
got on the airplane.''
   A second sculpture of Richardson alone shows the wide-eyed
grinning singer with a guitar at his waist and his arms wide open.
   Proceeds from today's event will go toward the purchase of a
$50,000 building for a Port Arthur museum that would include rock
'n' roll memorabilia.
   Until the museum is built, the sculptures will stand in a local
library.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-03 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEL AIR, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Principal Matthew Plevyak promised pupils at
Bel Air Middle School he'd put on a chicken suit if they read four
books each in a month. Now he's flapping down Main Street.
   The 935 students, challenged to read four books apiece last
month, tackled 5,527 or nearly six each.
   ``It's worth it,'' seventh-grader Susan Hoopergardner said as she
waited for the feathered Plevyak to walk through the center of this
northern Maryland town Wednesday.
   Teachers decorated the principal's office like a chicken coop,
and a local newspaper delivered five roosters to the school.
   Plevyak, in costume, arrived at the school in the back of a
pickup truck, read to classes and ate lunches with the classes that
read most of the books.
   He said his day as a chicken was a lot of fun.
   ``In nine years, the students have not seen me wear anything but
a suit and tie to school,'' Plevyak said, adding, ``We hope that
some of them found out that reading books is fun.
   ``Everybody is wondering what we're going to do next year,'' he
said. ``Maybe we'll make the science teachers dress up like
ballerinas or something.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Mexico has a state bird, tree, animal,
vegetable and mineral. Now it wants a cookie.
   House Bill 406 would correct that glaring deficiency, giving
state cookie honors to the bischochito, a rich sugar and anise
cookie relished by residents of northern New Mexico, especially
during the Christmas season.
   Three Albuquerque-area Democratic representatives sponsored the
cookie bill, and a bipartisan group of 16 lawmakers co-signed it
recently.
   If the bill passes, it would add the bischochito to the ranks of
the yucca, the official state flower; the roadrunner, the official
bird; the pinon, the official tree; the native trout, the official
fish; the black bear, the official animal; the chili and pinto bean,
official vegetables; the turquoise, the official gem; blue gramma
grass, the official grass; and the coelophysis, the official fossil.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bovine version of the
peanut-butter-and-jelly sandwich may help keep hay from spoiling and
make it more nutritious and delicious for cattle.
   Researchers at Southern Illinois University in Carbondale are
spreading a substance that resembles peanut butter onto bales of hay
to see if it shields the hay from rain and snow and reduces spoiling.
   They also may add flavorings to the protective paste to make it
more appealing to livestock and nutrients to make it more healthful,
said Robert Wolff, a professor of agricultural mechanization at the
school.
   The product, called ``balebutter'' because it resembles peanut
butter, consists of soybean oil and minerals.
   ``Not only does it have the capacity to cut down on hay loss, but
it also utilizes agricultural products,'' Wolff said recently. ``We
need to find new uses for soybeans.''
   Wolff said a farmer, Dale Halford, developed balebutter and
brought it to the university for evaluation.
   ``We're still investigating,'' said Wolff. ``We don't know yet if
it has fantastic potential or it doesn't.''
</TEXT>
