<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-Shooting     02-03 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Shooting,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Soldier Shoots, Wounds French Journalist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet soldier shot at three French
journalists today in a yard where departing Red Army troops gather,
slightly wounding one of the correspondents, a witness said.
   Jean Francois Leven, a correspondent for the weekly magazine
L'Express, was taken to the Red Cross hospital in Kabul with a
slight bullet wound to his right buttock, said Laurent Zecchini, a
fellow correspondent who was at the scene.
   Leven arrived in Afghanistan on Sunday and is one of 35 foreign
journalists covering the pullout of the Soviet army.
   Leven, Zecchini and Patrick Robert, a photographer for the Sygma
photo agency, where at a yard where Soviet troops assemble before
starting their journey home. The yard is at the base of the Salang
Highway, the strategic 260-mile road linking the capital to the
Soviet border.
   Zecchini said about 15 Soviet solders were talking to some Afghan
boys selling leather bags.
   ``I think they were about to make a deal. I think that's why one
of them started shooting,'' he said.
   He said one soldier fired four or five shots at the ground and
the three journalists raced back to their taxi. He said the soldier
fired one more shot, but Zecchini did not know if the bullet was
fired directly at the car or ricocheted and then pierced the door,
striking Leven.
   The French Embassy was notified about the incident.
   Under a U.N.-mediated agreement, the Soviets have said they would
withdraw their troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
