<DOCNO> AP890203-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0611EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Alaska'sImage     02-03 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska's Image,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather News Cools Efforts to Change Alaska's `Ice Box' Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First there were the whales, trapped in an
ice-bound sea as red-nosed reporters from around the world shivered
in wait. Then things really got cold, again chilling Alaska's
efforts to warm its frosty image.
   Mark Rhoads, a public relations consultant in Washington, D.C.,
said he was watching television this week when he noticed some
startling mixed messages about Alaska.
   ``The weather report had just been on and they were reporting
these ghastly temperatures in Alaska,'' Rhoads recalled Thursday.
``The very next thing after the weather report was a commercial to
promote tourism in Alaska.''
   The commercial Rhoads saw features a southern governor enjoying a
sunny barbecue along a scenic Alaska bay. There's blue sky, lush
forest and not a hint of snow or ice. The governor has been away
from his home state a bit too long, and when his parka-clad aides
track him down he jokes that they're ``a little bit overdressed.''
   ``They're clever commercials, but they were just out of sync that
particular day,'' Rhoads said.
   That's the attitude state officials hope potential tourists adopt
as they plan their summer vacations. They say they don't believe the
publicity will lead to fewer tourists visiting the nation's largest
state, which bills itself as ``The Last Frontier.''
   ``Weather stories come along all the time. They have a passing
effect on people's thinking,'' said Hugh Gellert, director of the
state Tourism Division.
   But the past several months have focused an unusual amount of
national attention on Alaska, all of it having to do with ice.
   Before the record cold wave, there was the effort last fall to
save the trapped whales near Barrow. Telecasts of shivering
reporters on the windy and frozen Arctic tundra did nothing to warm
the hearts of Alaska's tourism officials.
   Rod Bradley, president of the Anchorage advertising firm that
handles the state's tourism ad campaign, said those scenes reinforce
a negative image of Alaska among residents in the lower 48 states.
   ``They still think we live in igloos and drive dog teams. There's
an ingrained bias there,'' Bradley said. ``We're the most
misunderstood state in the union, there's no doubt about it.''
   Alaska will spend about $7.6 million on tourism promotion this
year. Of that, $2.5 million is being spent on the television ads in
major urban markets and on cable.
   The ad campaign is part of a long-term effort to change Alaska's
image. It is based on extensive research showing many potential
tourists don't come to Alaska because they think it's too cold.
   ``The intent of those ads is not to say it's not cold ever in
Alaska, but to say this is not a year-round land of ice and snow. We
have some parts of the year when its warm, sunny, and all the nice
colors come out,'' Gellert said.
   Bob Miller, director of the Alaska Tourism Marketing Council,
says the commercials are under review and the ``weather strategy''
may be replaced next year. He says the icy publicity may actually
draw tourists.
   ``In many cases in enhances people's interest in coming in the
summer,'' Miller said.
   He may be right. Seattle-based Holland America Lines Westours,
the largest cruise ship company serving Alaska, reports heavy
bookings in recent weeks for summer cruises to Alaska.
   Company spokesman Rick Skinner said that's because those buying
Alaska cruises know what to expect.
   ``They've looked at the literature to make sure they know what to
wear and that sort of thing,'' Skinner said. ``They tend to be
well-educated and much more erudite than the typical Caribbean
cruiser would be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0616EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSCoach     02-03 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Coach,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Victim Reinstated As Coach _ Temporarily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDERSONVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man dismissed as coach of his
daughter's basketball team after officials discovered he has AIDS
won a reprieve while the school board decides whether he poses a
public health threat.
   Allen Ward, who works as the volunteer coach of his daughter's
intramural team at Laurel Elementary School, was dismissed last week
after only one game. He was reinstated temporarily Thursday.
   In firing Ward, administrators cited a new AIDS policy requiring
school employees suspected of carrying the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome virus to be tested and their cases reviewed by a
committee of health and school officials.
   Don Jobe, superintendent of Franklin County Community Schools,
said at a news conference Thursday that Ward would be allowed to
continue coaching pending a decision by the school board whether his
condition is a public health threat.
   But Jobe said he doesn't think Ward's condition ``constitutes an
immediate health threat.''
   He said he made the decision to reinstate Ward after speaking
with the coach's physician, the Franklin County health officer and
officials at the State Board of Health.
   The school board was awaiting written confirmation of Ward's
condition from his physician in Indianapolis, Jobe said. A final
decision on whether Ward can stay on indefinitely is expected in
about two weeks, he said.
   Ward was diagnosed as having AIDS last June while undergoing a
blood test in Indianapolis. He contracted the deadly disease from
tainted blood products used during open heart surgery in 1984.
   The parents of some of Ward's players were upset he was suspended.
   ``Everybody is afraid of AIDS, but I don't think breeding
stupidity into our children will make it go away,'' said Dora Cable
of Metamora, whose 10-year-old son is on Ward's team.
   ``It's been blown out of proportion,'' added Pam Gerrain, whose
sixth-grade child is on the team. ``I don't see anything wrong with
him coaching the team. I'm not worried about it, but there's always
a chance I guess.''
   Ward, who launched a petition drive to be reinstated, said he was
happy to go back to work. ``I really feel good about it. I believe
their decision will come out in my favor.''
   He said he was concerned that school officials _ fearing he would
transmit AIDS to others _ would bar him from the school and would
insist on testing his children, Dande, 10, and Christopher, 14, for
the AIDS virus.
   The disease, which attacks the body's immune system, is
transmitted primarily through bodily fluids, such as during sexual
contact, intravenous drug use and blood transfusions, but not
through casual contact.
   Ward had volunteered to coach the team of fourth-, fifth- and
sixth-graders when his daughter decided to play at the school, 60
miles southeast of Indianapolis.
   His wife, Theresa, offered to substitute as coach while her
husband's case was pending but was told that she, too, would have to
undergo an AIDS test.
   ``I have no physical contact with them (team members) at all,''
Ward said. ``I might throw a basketball to them, but if they're
going to get it that way, we're all in trouble.''
   A similar argument was made after school authorities in Howard
County barred Ryan White from his classes in 1985 because he has
AIDS. Ryan eventually won the legal right to return to classes, but
his family soon moved to Cicero in Hamilton County.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
