<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-03 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Big Chill Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An arctic air mass maintained its icy grip on the northern and
central sections of the nation today, generating dangerous wind
chills of 80 below, as freezing rain made roads treacherous from
Texas to Vermont.
   Snow fell in Oregon, California, Nevada, Utah and Wyoming.
   Temperatures fell below minus-20 degrees in Montana, Wyoming,
North Dakota and Minnesota, making for a 100-degree difference
between North Dakota and Texas.
   At midnight, it was 36 degrees below zero in Cody, Wyo., and 34
below in Broadus, Mont. The mercury plunged to a record low of
minus-14 in Goodland, Kan., where the old record of minus-7 was last
tied in 1981. It was the second consecutive record low for that city.
   Winds combined with the cold to produce dangerous wind chills
across the central and northern Plains. Wind chills between 60
degrees below and 80 degrees below zero were common in Montana and
the Dakotas.
   Freezing rain, freezing drizzle and sleet fell from north central
Texas to Vermont, with snow in extreme northern Ohio and northern
Vermont, making driving dangerous.
   Showers and thunderstorms dumped heavy rain and small hail on
sections of Texas and Arkansas, with some places getting more than 2
inches of rain. A flash flood watch was in effect for southwest
Arkansas. Rainfall also was heavy in western Kentucky and southern
Indiana.
   In the West, snowstorms accompanied by wind buffeted Wyoming and
Colorado. Up to 8 inches of snow was predicted for Colorado mountain
passes. Snow also was heavy in a small section of Utah south of the
Salt Lake area. Up to 8 inches of snow fell in the state.
   More than 5 inches of snow fell Thursday in Salem, Ore., and
heavy snow continued to fall over the state's western valleys today.
   Winds up to 75 mph blasted through mountain ridges around Lake
Tahoe and California's Sierra Nevada. Up to 6 inches of snow fell in
24 hours in the northern Sierra Nevada.
   Today's forecast called for snow from Oregon to Idaho and the
central Rockies, from Nebraska to the middle Mississippi Valley and
over the Great Lakes and central New England; freezing rain and
sleet from southeast Missouri to central Illinois and from western
and central New York to Connecticut; rain from the lower Mississippi
Valley to the Ohio Valley and the Middle Atlantic States; scattered
rain showers along the California coast and dangerous wind chills
from the northern and central Rockies to the northern and central
Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were predicted from 25 degrees below zero to
minus 10 from the northern Rockies and northern Plains to western
Nebraska and northwest Kansas; from minus 10 to zero from northern
Idaho to the Colorado Rockies, the central High Plains, the lower
Missouri Valley and the upper Mississippi Valley; the single digits
and teens from much of the Pacific Northwest to northwest Colorado,
from the southern Plains to central Missouri and in northeast
Wisconsin and northern New England; the 20s and 30s from the
northern Pacific Coast to Nevada, western and northern Texas, the
middle Mississippi Valley, the lower Great Lakes and central New
England; the 40s, 50s and 60s from the California coast to southern
Texas, the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys and the Middle
Atlantic States; and the 70s and 80s from the central Gulf Coast to
the southern Atlantic Coast and Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 35
degrees below zero at Cody, Wyo., to 74 degrees at Fort Lauderdale
and Key West Naval Air Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 61 cloudy; Boston 30 freezing drizzle; Buffalo 18
freezing drizzle; Charleston, S.C. 60 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 33
rain; Cleveland 26 snow; Detroit 24 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York
36 rain; Philadelphia 41 foggy; Pittsburgh 32 drizzle; Portland,
Maine 19 freezing drizzle; Washington 46 fog.
   _Central: Bismarck -24 fair; Chicago 23 snow; Dallas-Fort Worth
21 windy; Denver -15 fair; Des Moines -10 snow; Indianapolis 30
freezing rain; Kansas City -4 snow; Minneapolis-St. Paul -21 fair;
Nashville 48 cloudy; New Orleans 67 foggy; St. Louis 19 snow.
   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 4 fair; Las Vegas 50 windy;
Los Angeles 51 cloudy; Phoenix 53 fair; Salt Lake City 23 snow; San
Diego 53 cloudy; San Francisco 45 rain; Seattle 11 windy.
   _Canada: Montreal 7 freezing drizzle; Toronto 14 cloudy.
</TEXT>
