<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-03 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mainly Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in light, nervous trading in
Europe today as market players awaited fresh news from the
Washington meeting of the group of finance ministers from leading
industrialized countries.
   Gold prices moved down.
   ``The dollar is just bouncing around right now without any new
factors in the market,'' said one Frankfurt dealer. ``People are a
little nervous about the G-7 meeting and trading is very light.''
   The Group of Seven is made up of the United States, Japan, West
Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.48 yen to a closing 129.27 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 129.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8779 West German marks, up from 1.8700
   _1.5952 Swiss francs, up from 1.5923
   _6.3885 French francs, up from 6.3735
   _2.1180 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1135
   _1,370.75 Italian lire, up from 1,368.50
   _1.1885 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1882.
   In London, the dollar also rose against the British pound, which
cost $1.7475, cheaper than $1.7515 on Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $391.35 a troy ounce, up
from $392.25 bid late Thursday, but fell back in later trading. At
midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $390.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price at noon was $390.40, down from $391.50
bid late Thursday.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.81 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $5.86.
</TEXT>
