<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-Politics     02-03 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Politics,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Approves Bill To Retire Elderly Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui today signed a law
that will give large bonuses to lawmakers elected in China 42 years
ago who voluntarily retire, but officials said many of the aging
politicians refuse to step down.
   A statement said the bill, part of the ruling Nationalist Party's
plan to increase the clout of native Taiwanese in the government,
will take effect Monday.
   The Nationalist government, which fled to Taiwan in 1949 after
losing a civil war to Communist forces on the mainland, still claims
to be the rightful ruler of all China.
   The elderly lawmakers, most of them Nationalists, have been
frozen in office until they can return to their mainland
constituencies for new elections.
   Chang Chun, a 100-year-old presidential adviser, signed up today
to retire from the 880-seat National Assembly ``to support the
government reform,'' Assembly Secretary Gen. Irwine Ho said.
   Chang, the oldest assemblyman, will receive a one-time payment of
about $143,000, or more than five times his annual salary, for
stepping down.
   Ho told reporters only about 100 elderly members of the assembly
_ an electoral college that meets every six years to choose the
president _ are expected to retire this year. Approximately 700 more
aging assemblymen will wait to consider retirement until after the
next presidential election in May 1990, he said.
   Meanwhile, officials of the 297-seat Legislative Yuan said about
70 of the body's 200 elderly members are expected to retire this
year. Many others refuse to step down because they believe they
still represent their mainland constituents, the officials said.
   The opposition party Democratic Progressive Party has attacked
the retirement bill for failing to restrict pension payments to
lawmakers who resign this year. But the Nationalist Party rejected
the demand to avoid outraging the elderly legislators.
   Lawmakers elected on Taiwan now account for 73 seats in the
297-seat Legislative Yuan and 106 seats in the 880-seat National
Assembly. Most other members were elected on the Chinese mainland.
   Legislation has yet to be introduced to increase the number of
Taiwan's elected members in the two parliamentary bodies.
   The Nationalist Party proposed last week to increase the number
of elected Legislative Yuan lawmakers to 130 for the December
election. Under the plan, Taiwan-elected lawmakers would rise to 150
by 1992, when all elderly lawmakers are expected to have retired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
