<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Crash     02-03 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Crash,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Death Toll Rises To 15 in Train Derailment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSMAN GHANI MANSOOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHITTAGONG, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mechanical problems may have caused
the derailment that killed at least 15 people on a crowded passenger
train, officials said today.
   Three cars of the 10-car, Dhaka-bound express train derailed
Thursday at Kumira, 14 miles north of this port city.
   The official death toll rose to 15 today after two people died of
their injuries in a Chittagong hospital. However, the independent
newspaper Inquilab said at least 25 people were killed and more than
100 injured. Officials say about 70 people were injured.
   Inquilab said some bodies were reportedly removed from the scene
either by their relatives or rescuers, and therefore remained
unaccounted for.
   The government news agency Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha said the
train was carrying at least 2,100 passengers, three times its
authorized capacity, including many travelers riding on top of the
train or clinging outside the doors.
   A railroad official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
generator under a first-class coach may have broken and gotten
caught in the track, throwing the coach and two adjoining cars off
the track.
   Chittagong's police superintendent, Mohammad Talukder, blamed
defects in the train's frame and mechanical system.
   On Thursday night, Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha quoted an
unidentified railroad official who was traveling on the train as
saying the derailment was caused by a defect in a dining car.
   The wreck happened less than three weeks after two trains
collided head on near Dhaka, killing 114 people in Bangladesh's
worst-known rail disaster.
   The Jan. 15 crash also happened on the line linking Dhaka with
Chittagong, 135 miles southeast of the capital.
</TEXT>
