<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     02-03 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Warns Ban On Public Meetings Will Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government today said it would
keep its ban on public assembly as long as anti-government
protesters continue their activities.
   ``There are elements who are bent to incite trouble at any given
opportunity,'' government spokesman Kyaw Sann told a news
conference. He said some people had shouted anti-government slogans
at the recent funeral of Yan Naing, a hero of Burma's 1940s struggle
for independence from Britain.
   Kyaw Sann announced the ban on public assembly would continue.
The spokesman also said political parties and other groups could be
prosecuted if they continue distributing pamphlets and videotapes in
violation of existing registration laws.
   Some opposition party leaders have complained of government
harassment.
   The military seized power on Sept. 18 and brutally put down
nationwide pro-democracy demonstrations, killing 500 people, by
government count. Diplomats estimated 1,000 people were killed.
   The new leaders have allowed the formation of more than 180
political parties and promised general elections but have not fixed
a date.
   Kyaw Sann said some political parties, insurgents and ``hostile
foreign organizations'' were probably behind the spread of rumors
that rebel commandos had infiltrated the Rangoon area and that
Soviet advisers were fighting with the Burmese army against the
Karens.
   The Karens are one of about a dozen ethnic minority groups
fighting the central government for greater autonomy.
