<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     02-03 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Palestinian Minors Jailed For Weeks Without Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian teen-agers from Arab east Jerusalem
are routinely held for weeks without bail on charges of throwing
stones or erecting roadblocks, an Israeli lawyer said today.
   In other cases, Palestinian children under 13, whom the law does
not consider legally responsible for their acts, are held for days
because their parents can't pay bail, said attorney Shlomo Lecker.
   Lecker said an 11-year-old and two 13-year-olds were detained for
five days each in a cell at Jerusalem police headquarters because
their parents could not come up with $415 bail.
   ``They are held eight to a cell, and it's dark,'' Lecker said,
adding that his young clients have complained of being slapped in
the face and kicked in the legs during interrogation.
   Dorit Beinish, a state attorney in the Justice Ministry, defended
the practice as legal.
   ``We have many cases of stone-throwing by minors. This is a new
crime, part of the uprising, and punishments are more severe,'' she
said in an interview.
   Ms. Beinish said she did not recall a case in which a youth was
held without bail and later acquitted.
   Ms. Beinish also said she did not know of Palestinians under 13
being held. ``If this happened, it was a mistake,'' she said.
   Police spokeswoman Nurit Buton said she would investigate
Lecker's allegations that children under 13 have been held.
   Asked about the charges of mistreatment during interrogation, she
said each complaint was investigated by a special police unit. ``We
have many complaints that have no basis at all, while in some cases
there may be something to it,'' she said.
   Nine left-wing Israeli legislators have written a letter to
Justice Minister Dan Meridor asking that the practice of holding
minors be stopped.
   ``Standards from the West Bank are coming to Israel,'' said Dedi
Zucker, a legislator from the Citizens Rights Movement. He spoke in
an interview Thursday.
   Lecker said the practice began a year ago after the Supreme Court
ruled that minors _ those between the ages of 14 and 18 _ can be
held without bail until the start of trial if they are charged with
throwing stones.
   On Thursday, Israeli troops shot and killed a 16-year-old
Palestinian in clashes near the West Bank villages of Fahme and Kfar
Rai, the army said. Hospital officials identified the youth as Ahmed
Jamil Saabneh, and gave his age as 22.
   The death brought to 371 the number of Palestinians killed in the
uprising. Fifteen Israelis also have been killed.
</TEXT>
