<FIRST>r i PM-KALBombing     02-03 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KAL Bombing,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged KAL Plane Bomber Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors indicted a North Korean
agent today for her alleged role in the bombing of a South Korean
jetliner in 1987.
   Prosecutors said formal charges had been filed against Kim
Hyon-hui, 27, who confessed to bombing a Korean Airlines Boeing 707
that disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, near Burma with 115 people on board.
   Miss Kim has said she received direct orders from Kim Jong Il,
North Korean President Kim Il Sung's son and heir apparent, to plant
a time bomb on the KAL plane and commit suicide before she was
arrested.
   She said the purpose of her mission was to disrupt the Olympic
Games, which were held in Seoul in September and October.
   Miss Kim has been in the custody of South Korea's main
intelligence organization, the Agency for National Security
Planning, since she was extradited from Bahrain, where she was
arrested at the airport.
   Prosecutors said Miss Kim would face legal measures but not be
jailed. Although international aviation rules require South Korea to
put Miss Kim on trial, officials here want to spare her punishment
because she has shifted her allegiance and fully cooperated with the
government inquiry into the bombing.
   Miss Kim and a male companion, traveling on forged Japanese
passports, were among passengers on an early leg of the KAL flight
from Baghdad, Iraq to Seoul but disembarked before the jet
disappeared near Burma. They took poison when police tried to
question them at Bahrain Airport. The man died but Miss Kim survived.
</TEXT>
