<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     02-03 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Crash Linked to Fuel Tank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRBY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Air Force crewmen reported a faulty fuel
tank before they ejected from an FB-111 fighter-bomber that crashed
and exploded in northeastern Vermont on a training mission, a
congressman's aide said.
   The pilot, Capt. Randall F. Voorhees, 31, and the radar
navigator, Capt. Len J. Esterly Jr., 30, parachuted to safety
seconds before the plane hit the ground shortly before noon Thursday.
   The crew lost control of the aircraft after they noticed problems
with the fuel tank, Air Force officials told J.P. Dowd, an aide to
U.S. Sen. Patrick Leahy, who was briefed on the accident.
   ``They radioed they were having problems, aborted the mission and
then ejected when they lost control of the plane,'' Dowd said.
   Air Force officials declined to comment on the cause of the
crash. Officials said a military board has been established to
investigate the crash.
   The pilot and navigator ejected together in a single capsule,
called a pod. The two landed safely, although a tree branch broke
through the pod on impact, bruising the pilot's knee.
   ``Everything turned out well,'' said David Eastman, 34, a former
Air Force sergeant who found the pilot and navigator a short
distance from his home. ``They walked away with just some bruises
and some hurt pride.''
   The plane, a medium-range fighter-bomber, was based at the U.S.
Air Force base in Plattsburgh, N.Y., which is about 80 miles west of
the crash site.
</TEXT>
