<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MysteryMan     02-03 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mystery Man,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cult Figure Of Hughes Aircraft Unmasked In Houston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fast track at Hughes Aircraft was too much
for Ed Greer, but life in the slow lane did not hold the appeal
fantasized by his former colleagues when the young executive left
without a trace in 1981.
   The man who had become a cult figure to corporate daydreamers was
tracked down by FBI agents last October in Houston, masquerading
under the name of Kenneth Roy Hearn and working quietly at a small
oil exploration firm.
   ``I hurt a lot of people _ my parents, my ex-wife and my kids,''
Greer, 40, said in an interview with the Los Angeles Times this
week. ``I really regret doing this. If I had to do it over again, I
would do it differently.''
   He vanished on Sept. 10, 1981, leaving behind his engineering
job, his parents, his wife and two kids and taking a flight to Ft.
Lauderdale, Fla. Before he left, he told a co-worker, ``Never become
too good at something you hate. They'll make you do it the rest of
your life.''
   After he left, his former colleagues, some of whom said they
wished they had the courage to do the same, began throwing annual
parties, often showing up at them wearing Ed Greer masks.
   No one from his past saw or heard from him again until FBI
agents, trying to learn why someone in Texas was using the name of
Kenneth Roy Hearn of Alabama, tracked him to his office at
Input-Output Inc. of Houston.
   Greer first lived in Florida for a time, fixing boat engines and
hanging out at the beach.
   ``There are a lot of pretty girls on the beach,'' he explained.
   But he eventually decided to go back to a regular job.
   ``After a while, I got tired of never having enough money and
never having an ID,'' he said. As for the pretty girls,
``Unfortunately, about the time you get to know them, they've gone
back to Muncie, (Ind.),'' Greer said.
   He got Hearn's name and Social Security number by placing a
newspaper ad for an engineering job that the man answered.
   He said the FBI agents who caught him lost interest in the case
after discovering he was not a drug dealer or money launderer.
   ``The federal charge that he was investigated on was possession
of a false Social Security card number,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Don De Gabrielle, who handled the case in Houston.
   Under an agreement with the government, Greer must stay out of
trouble for a year or face charges in the case. He also faces
$78,000 in back taxes.
   And he must face the past.
   ``Anyone with any attachment to the human race couldn't do what
he did,'' said his ex-wife, Kit Clark, who divorced him after he
disappeared. ``I will never forgive him for what he did to the
boys.''
   She said she told him he could contact his sons, now 9 and 16, if
he wanted, however.
   As for why he left, Greer said, ``I felt trapped. I really hated
management. ... I didn't like my life.''
   Greer plans to remain at his job in Houston.
</TEXT>
