<FIRST>r w PM-PayRaise-Protest     02-03 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise-Protest,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Jeer Democrats En Route to Luxury Resort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pay Raise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About three dozen pay-raise protesters gathered
at Union Station this morning to greet House Democrats as they
departed by train for a weekend legislative retreat at a luxurious
West Virginia resort.
   ``Money for the needy, not for the greedy,'' the group chanted.
However, the lawmakers arrived by bus under police guard and slipped
in through a side door of the station to avoid the protesters.
   Groups represented ranged from the conservative Students for
America to followers of Mitch Snyder, an advocate for the homeless.
   ``Maybe we would be less inclined to be here if they were rushing
through a rise in the minimum wage'' or other measures to help
low-income Americans, Snyder said.
   The Democrats are spending the weekend at the Greenbrier, a
resort hotel in West Virginia. The annual retreat is subsidized by
corporate and union interests.
   The Senate voted 95-5 Thursday to reject the 51 percent pay raise
recommended by a presidential commission, placing the spotlight on a
House leadership plan to legalize the increase next week but scale
it back to 30 percent a day later.
   The Senate resolution included language to roll back the raise if
it becomes law and end the system allowing congressional increases,
along with those for top federal executives and judges, to become
law automatically unless rejected by both houses.
   Rank-and-file lawmakers would see their salaries rise from
$89,500 to $135,000 under the full raise. But the pay would be
$116,350 under House Speaker Jim Wright's plan.
