<FIRST>r a PM-Phone-InPlea     02-03 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone-In Plea,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overweight Man Phones in Guilty Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 500-pound man unable to appear in court
because he was too obese and too ill was allowed to plead guilty by
telephone to assault and battery charges.
   David Streefkerk, 39, of Hazel Park made the call from his bed
Thursday to Oakland County Circuit Judge Gene Schnelz. In addition
to the severe obesity, Streefkerk has congestive heart failure,
advanced diabetes and lung disease, according to his doctors.
   He could face up to 90 days in jail and a $100 fine at his Feb.
27 sentencing. Schnelz said he may grant a suspended sentence
because Streefkerk is penniless and terminally ill.
   Streefkerk initially was charged with felonious assault for
allegedly pointing a loaded gun at a man last June during an
argument, county Assistant Prosecutor Steven Meads said. The charge
was reduced to assault and battery.
   Robert Cleland, president of the Michigan Prosecuting Attorneys
Association, said he was unaware of any other case in which a guilty
plea was made by phone.
