<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-AborigineDeaths     02-03 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aborigine Deaths,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aborigines Angered at Findings into Blacks' Deaths in Custody</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families of four aborigines who died in
police custody today denounced a government report on the deaths
that criticized police but stopped short of recommending criminal
charges.
   The report, issued Thursday, found no evidence of foul play in
the four deaths but said they probably could have been avoided.
   Judge James Muirhead was ordered by the government of Prime
Minister Bob Hawke in 1987 to investigate 44 aboriginal deaths
nationwide since 1980. Since the inquiry began, the number of deaths
has jumped to 107.
   Most of the offenders were arrested on minor charges such as
being drunk and disorderly.
   Alice Dixon, whose son, Kingsley, was found hanging in his cell
in Adelaide jail in 1987, wept when she heard the report.
   ``I expected some retribution. They're murdering our people, our
boys, and they're getting away with it,'' she said. ``My son is
dead, other sons are dead and other mothers are grieving and this is
the result we are going to get.''
   Leila Murray, whose 21-year-old son Eddie was found hanged in
1981, said: ``I've never believed police.'' She said the finding her
son took his own life ``shatters my faith in white justice.''
   Muirhead said police fabricated evidence and withheld evidence
during the inquiry's investigation of Murray's death.
   The judge concluded that proper custodial care and observance of
prison regulations could have prevented Dixon's death, and that the
death by heart attack of Charles Sidney Michael, 31, in 1984 might
have been avoided.
   Muirhead said the fourth death, that of John Clarence Highfold,
37, at Adelaide Jail in 1983 was from natural causes.
   Muirhead didn't say when another report on more deaths would be
released.
   The National Aboriginal and Islander Legal Service, which helped
pressure the government to investigate, criticized the inquiry.
   ``There is no message in there that says to police, `Stop if you
are killing people or if you all allowing aboriginals to die,'''
said service director Peter Coe.
   Australia's indigenous aborigines number about 160,000, or about
1 percent of the 16 million population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru a0479 02-03 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestants, Catholics Says Secret Talks Yielded No Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new comments from political leaders.
CORRECTS name of Hume's party. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protestant and Catholic politicians in Northern
Ireland confirmed today that party members met secretly in West
Germany but said they found no way to end the province's sectarian
violence.
   ``Sadly, there's no agreement, there's no new dawn, there's no
new era. We are not on the eve of a breakthrough,'' said Peter
Robinson, deputy leader of the hard-line Protestant Democratic
Unionist Party.
   His assessment differed from that of the British Broadcasting
Corp., which said the talks last year produced unanimous agreement
on power sharing at all levels of government, including the police,
in the British-ruled province.
   The BBC said the secret four-party talks could produce the most
important political breakthrough since sectarian violence in the
Protestant-dominated province flared in 1969. The BBC said Robinson
participated in the talks.
   Meetings have continued in Northern Ireland since October, it
said.
   The BBC said the West German talks included representatives of
Northern Ireland's two main Protestant parties, the largest Roman
Catholic party and the middle-of-the-road Alliance Party. It said
they took place Oct. 14-15 at the Angerhof Hotel between Duesseldorf
and Duisburg.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, was not included, the report said.
   The mostly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the 60 percent Protestant province with
the 95 percent Catholic Irish Republic. About 2,700 people have been
killed in sectarian violence since 1969.
   Reacting to the BBC report, John Hume, who leads the moderate
Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party, said the BBC's version
of what had happened was ``wildly exaggerated'' and ``completely off
the wall.''
   Hume said in a BBC radio interview today that the political
leaders were invited to a meeting in West Germany to put forward
their views on Northern Ireland. He said there had been previous
similar meetings in West Germany and others in England that brought
together Protestant and Catholic politicians from Northern Ireland.
   ``But we did not exaggerate and say that suddenly there's a great
breakthrough because there has not been .... I am not aware the four
parties reached agreement.''
   James Molyneaux, leader of the Protestant Official Unionist
Party, said Thursday night it was ``crackers'' to suggest his or the
Rev. Ian Paisley's Democratic Unionists had been involved in any
formal talks.
   He said the meeting in West Germany was merely the kind of
conference frequently attended by senior Protestant leaders. ``There
has never been any negotiation about the future government of
Northern Ireland,'' Molyneaux said.
   Gordon Mawhinney, deputy leader of the Alliance Party, which
draws support from both Catholics and Protestants, said a German
Lutheran churchmen organized the West German meeting for a different
purpose, which he did not specify, and the talks about political
differences took place ``somewhat by accident.''
   ``There was a regular line of communication opened between the
Northern Ireland political parties and ... great willingness to look
at the problems of the other community,'' he said.
   In addition to Mawhinney and Robinson, the BBC said, the other
two politicians who worked out the agreement in West Germany were
Jack Allen, chairman of the Official Unionists, the largest
Protestant party; and Austin Currie of Hume's party, the largest
Catholic political group.
   Catholic and Protestant party leaders who were not at the talks
divorced themselves from the report. The BBC said the talks were
supported by the government of Britain and the neighboring Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
