<FIRST>u w PM-Bennett-Confirmation 1stLd-Writethru a0419 02-03 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Confirmation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0419,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says He Can Handle Job Without Being Cabinet Member</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Bennett interview this morning on Cabinet
status, delay in confirmation hearings, smoking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, President Bush's choice to
direct the federal war on drugs, said today he has ``the confidence
of the president'' and will be able to handle the job despite not
being a member of the Cabinet.
   In an interview this morning, Bennett said he appreciated the
concern of Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr.
and others who have criticized Bush's decision to leave him out of
the Cabinet.
   On Thursday, Biden said, ``I'm worried that the president has
made a crucial mistake, maybe in part by oversight, by not having
the drug coordinator at the table.''
   The director of National Drug Control Policy ``has to do what
none of the others (in the Cabinet) has to do,'' said Biden. ``He
has to take them on, as a practical matter. He is entering the most
dangerous world in Washington, and that is the world of fiefdoms.''
   The director will be called upon to develop a strategy covering
more than 30 agencies spread throughout the federal government that
are under the more direct control of individual department
secretaries.
   ``I have the confidence of the president,'' said Bennett. ``I
know that. He said it. I heard it. He said it to my colleagues.''
   In a preliminary meeting of the top Cabinet-level appointments,
Bush told everyone that Bennett would be in charge of drug control
programs and said, ``You are to work with him,'' Bennett recalled.
   ``He has since reiterated that,'' he said. ``He's told me, `I
want you to be able to do it (the new job) in a way that's
unencumbered'.''
   Bennett said he's been assured by Bush that he will be invited to
Cabinet meetings when they pertain to the drug effort.
   Asked if he felt he wasted a lot of time attending Cabinet
meetings on subjects he didn't care about during his 3{ years as
education secretary under President Reagan, Bennett said only, ``I
went to three years of Cabinet meetings, and some were more
interesting than others.''
   Bennett, who met with Biden last week, planned to make courtesy
calls this afternoon with Sens. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., and Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, all members of the
Judiciary Committee that will begin hearings on his nomination
starting March 1.
   Biden said Thursday that he had wanted to start the hearings a
month earlier, but agreed to the later date at the administration's
request to give Bennett time to prepare.
   Once Bennett is confirmed, he ``must begin work immediately on
developing a plan that has never been developed in the history of
the United States of America, and that is a comprehensive drug
plan,'' which is due 180 days after the nominee is confirmed, said
Biden, D-Del.
   ``The clock is running the day I'm confirmed,'' Bennett said
today. ``Senator Biden and I discussed this and we decided to put
off the hearings a bit to give us time to set up our staff, figure
out how the office is going to run.''
   He said his vow to quit smoking by the time he was confirmed was
not the reason for the delay in the hearings.
   ``I will be done by the time I take office,'' Bennett said.
``I've set a date for that, but I'm not going to preach until I've
succeeded.''
   Biden noted that the job of director of National Drug Control
Policy is bound to be extremely difficult. ``Dr. Bennett or whoever
will take that post will be a sitting duck. There is no way someone
can succeed in the first year,'' he said.
   The senator said he considered the administration's request for a
delay until March 1 ``reasonable.''
   ``We have created a completely new Cabinet post, and this is an
infrequent occurrence which requires time and great effort to
implement,'' he said. ``Dr. Bennett has no office, no place to
reside, physically, and he has no staff.''
   Bennett aide John Walters has said Bennett has other obligations
to take care of before he starts his new job. Those include some
speaking engagements and completion of a book on education.
</TEXT>
