<HEAD>Archdiocese to Close Three District High Schools Because of Low Enrollment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, D.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Catholic Archdiocese of Washington
has announced that it will permanently close three of its four city
high schools in June because of a decade-long decrease in enrollment
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The archdiocese announced Thursday that it will close Mackin
Catholic High School, a boys school, and All Saints and Holy Spirit,
two girls high schools.
   Only Archbishop John Carroll High School will open for classes in
the fall, drawing students from the other three schools and for the
first time admittng girls as students.
   Cardinal James A. Hickey, Washington's archbishop, said the
archdiocese was not abandoning the nation's capital. ``Our
committment remains unshaken and enhanced,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, two independent Catholic girls high schools in the
area also have announced plans to close. They are the Academy of
Notre Dame, in Washington, and Regina High School in suburban
Hyattsville, Md.
   The closings follow a nationwide trend among Catholic schools
caused by the continuing exodus of middle-class black families from
the inner city to the suburbs.
   About 1,300 students will be affected by the closings.
   On Thursday, the students grappled with the news that their
schools were closing.
   ``We're Mackin men and that means something,'' said Aaron Young
III, Mackin student body president. ``It is unfair for the cardinal
to just close us down. He never even asked our opinion.''
