<FIRST>r a PM-Homeless-Tower     02-03 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless-Tower,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Declines Offer of Abandoned, Unheated Tower as Homeless Shelter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK HALL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has offered to lease
an abandoned 80-foot observation tower to house homeless people in a
rural county, but perplexed local officials say they don't need it.
   ``If we had any homeless, we certainly wouldn't take them down
there and put them in an 80-foot tower, not if we had their best
interests at heart,'' he said Kent County commission president
Alexander P. Rasin III.
   ``Why would you want to stick them in the middle of the
boonies?'' he asked.
   The 1940s-era steel tower is a former observation platform that
was used by the U.S. Army at Aberdeen Proving Ground north of
Baltimore to monitor shelling across the Chesapeake Bay.
   Access to the top is up a formidable number of rickety wooden
stairs. It lacks heat, electricity or running water, and is located
along the waterfront in a hard-to-find corner of the rural county.
   The federal Department of Health and Human Services recently
notified Kent County officials that they could lease the abandoned
tower to house the homeless if they were interested.
   They weren't.
   On Thursday, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development in Washington said the notice to the county may
have been an error.
   ``We've been getting a lot of calls about things like this,'' HUD
spokesman William A. Glavin said. ``Either properties are too remote
or they somehow wouldn't work.''
</TEXT>
