<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     02-03 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Clash With Police In Kwangju</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people fought police with
firebombs in Kwangju today during a demonstration demanding an
thorough investigation into the government's suppression of a 1980
uprising in the southern city.
   A police officer was beaten by protesters and taken to a
hospital, but his condition was not immediately known, the Yonhap
News Agency reported.
   The protesters were among about 1,000 people who marched through
downtown after an outdoor rally denouncing the government of
President Roh Tae-woo and the United States, the news agency said.
   About 200 people, mostly students, dashed from the crowd hurling
rocks and dozens of firebombs when about 800 police halted the march
50 yards from the U.S. cultural center, Yonhap reported.
   It said the marchers dispersed voluntarily a short time later.
   The authoritarian government killed about 200 people when it put
down an uprising in Kwangju in 1980. The protesters accused the Roh
government of blocking efforts to investigate the suppression of the
revolt.
   Opposition and dissident figures say some military leaders
instigated the uprising as part of a plot to seize power in the
chaotic days that followed the death of then-President Park
Chung-hee in late 1979.
   They say the United States acquiesced in a military plan to
suppress the revolt ruthlessly and therefore is partly to blame for
the deaths.
   The United States has denied the charges and said it will
cooperate with a parliamentary committee investigating the revolt.
   Parliamentary officials said today that next week they will send
a questionnaire to two Americans, William Gleysteen and John
Wickham, and ask them to clarify any U.S. role in the case.
   Gleysteen was the U.S. ambassador and Wickham served as the top
U.S. military commander at the time of the uprising.
