<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Wiretaps     02-03 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Wiretaps,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Upholds Convictions Against Publisher, Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today upheld the
convictions of the publisher and editor of a tabloid that published
conversations obtained from an illegal wiretap of The New York
Times' Athens bureau telephone.
   Greece's highest court also ordered a reduction in the two-month
prison sentences given publisher George Bobolas and editor
Alexandros Filippopoulos of the left-wing daily Ethnos.
   A lower court will revise the sentences, which could be changed
to fines. A hearing date has not been set.
   Bobolas and Filippopoulos were sentenced in October 1987 for
publishing transcripts of the telephone conversations.
   Ethnos alleged the conversations proved Paul Anastasi, a
Greek-Cypriot journalist working for The New York Times and London's
Daily Telegraph, planned to bomb Ethnos, kill its employees and
destabilize democracy in Greece.
   Today's ruling was the latest in a series of court battles
between Ethnos and Anastasi.
   In 1983, Anastasi wrote a book that alleged Ethnos received
financial assistance from the KGB, the Soviet secret police and
intelligence agency, to begin publication in 1981.
   Anastasi was found guilty of libel in 1985 and sentenced to a
year in prison for his allegation, but the Supreme Court overturned
the conviction.
   He later filed a lawsuit charging Bobolas, Filippopoulos and
three other Ethnos editors with perjury and defamation. The suit is
pending.
</TEXT>
