<HEAD>Griffin O'Neal Released from County Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Griffin O'Neal was released from jail
today after serving 15 days for violating terms of probation he
received for his involvement in the 1986 boating death of a friend.
   Appearing tired and unshaven, he left the Anne Arundel County
Detention Center accompanied by his lawyer, T. Joseph Touhey.
   O'Neal, the 24-year-old son of actor Ryan O'Neal, said he made a
few friends and ``actually was pretty well liked'' during his time
in jail.
   ``I'm going home now,'' he said when asked about his immediate
plans, adding he wanted to ``hold on to my animals and my
girlfriend.''
   O'Neal was given an 18-day jail sentence for not performing 400
hours of community service ordered by the judge who found him guilty
of reckless boating in the accident that killed Gian-Carlo Coppola,
the son of film director Francis Ford Coppola.
   Sebastian Valenti, deputy superintendent of the Anne Arundel
County Detention Center, said O'Neal was released three days early
because he earned time off for good conduct.
   O'Neal has completed several other terms of the probation given
him Feb. 27, 1987, including making a boating safety video, paying a
fine and answering questions on a boating telephone hotline.
