<FIRST>r i PM-BlackAnglicans     02-03 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Anglicans,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church of England Rejects Expanded Role for Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England leaders have rejected a plan to
give black Anglicans more seats on the main policy-making body of
the church.
   After a two-hour debate, lay members of the Anglican state church
on Thursday blocked the proposal by a 96-80 vote, despite favorable
votes of 17-3 by bishops and 103-62 by clergy. The plan needed a
majority of each group to pass, as well as approval by the British
Parliament.
   Barbados-born Bishop of Croydon Wilfred Wood, the first black
bishop of the state church to serve in England, left Church House in
Westminster immediately after the vote. He looked upset and declined
comment.
   Although Wood's Committee for Black Anglican Concerns proposed
the plan, he and the seven other black members of the General Synod
did not speak during the body's debate.
   The proposal would have set aside a minimum of 24 seats for
blacks on the 574-member, policy-making synod in 1990. Proponents
said the arrangement would better reflect the estimated 2 million
blacks among England's 49 million people. Wales and Scotland have
separate churches.
   During the debate, senior synod member Oswald Clark said legal
advice had shown Parliament would reject the plan as ``inexpedient.''
   Businessman Timothy Royle said Parliament had never reserved
seats for any particular party or race. ``We won't make restitution
for our past to those who come from abroad, particularly from the
former colonies, by giving one group a special role,'' he said.
   Archbishop of York John Habgood urged the synod to approve the
plan and negotiate with the government on what it would accept.
   ``One generation of black people has already been lost and unless
we do something now, we shall lose the next generation and the
generation after that,'' Habgood said.
   Several speakers said they saw the plan as offensive to black
people because it implied they were incapable of helping themselves.
</TEXT>
