<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Stroessner 2ndLd-Writethru   02-03 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroessner, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0515,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stroessner Has Combined Patronage and Force During Long Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to ADD details on allegations of human rights
abuses. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The red-haired...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Paraguay, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Alfredo Stroessner relied on a canny blend of military
force, political patronage, and self-discipline to maintain control
over Paraguay for 34 years _ longer than any leader in the Western
Hemisphere.
   But a rebellion by army Gen. Andres Rodriguez, Stroessner's
second-in-command, today ended the dictatorship that began when
Stroessner seized power in a 1954 military coup.
   Stroessner, 76, won eight presidential elections despite
opposition charges the balloting was rigged. Even his critics admit
he helped stabilize a nation that before him had endured 22
presidents in 31 years.
   But at the same time, he was accused of brutal repression and
corruption, and his country became a haven for fugitive Nazis, drug
traffickers and former dictators. The list of refugees included
Josef Mengele, the Auschwitz death camp doctor, and Gen. Anastasio
Somoza Debayle, the ousted Nicaraguan dictator.
   The red-haired Stroessner, son of a Bavarian immigrant father and
Paraguayan mother of Spanish heritage, oversaw the country's
transformation from a neglected backwater, with open sewers and no
running water, to a relatively prosperous and modern nation.
   Scores of schools and buildings, in addition to Asuncion's
international airport, were named for the man who began his military
career at age 20 and quickly distinguished himself on the battle
field.
   In a central plaza in the capital, a huge neon sign blinked
incessantly with the slogan, ``Stroessner: Peace, Work and
Well-being.'' An important city is named Puerto Stroessner.
   In his innumberable speeches, which sometimes lasted hours, he
liked to list in detail the public works projects achieved by his
regime.
   Among the most important works was the $16 billion Itaipu dam,
the world's largest hydroelectrical project, built in partnership
with neighboring Brazil. It began producing power in early 1985.
   He attended hundreds of ground-breakings and other public
ceremonies each year, even in outlying towns, and served regularly
as a witness at weddings _ even when he didn't know the bride or
groom.
   Stroessner credited his longevity and energy to Spartan habits _
he did not smoke and drank little _ and a busy work schedule.
   Public dissatisfaction with the government became increasingly
evident in the mid-1980s, when protesters and police clashed in
street demonstrations.
   The nation's Roman Catholic Church and even a faction of
Stroessner's Colorado Party began criticizing the president,
accusing him of unjust repression and demanding democratic reforms.
   Human rights groups said many of Stroessner's foes were tortured
and killed during his early years in power. Others were simply
jailed indefinitely, convicted of political crimes or forced into
exile.
   A rabid anti-communist and staunch U.S. ally, Stroessner was
stung by the Reagan administration's labeling him as a dictatorship,
and relations between the countries declined.
   Stroessner attended the nation's military academy, graduating in
1929, and as a 20-year-old lieutenant led a mortar platoon in the
Chaco War against Bolivia. He distinguished himself for bravery in
the war, which lasted from 1932 to 1935, and rose quickly through
the ranks, being promoted to general at age 40. He became army chief
of staff in 1951.
   After taking power, Stroessner put down five attempted coups by
exiled politicians from 1954 to 1958 and began dismantling the
opposition.
   Employing special powers under a state of siege, renewed each 90
days until last year, civilian and military police arrested
thousands of opponents.
   Stroessner branded virtually all his opponents as subversives.
   Critics charge his government promoted a growing private sector
dominated by contraband. Many government and military officials,
including relatives and close assocites, became enriched through
their ties with Stroessner.
   Stroessner reportedly has been ill since a prostate operation
five months ago. His apparent slow recovery increased the demands by
opposition leaders that the army and Colorado Party consider a
transition to democratic rule.
</TEXT>
