<FIRST>u a PM-ChristicSuit     02-03 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christic Suit,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Awards $1 Million to Defendants in Contra Conspiracy Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today awarded $1 million in
attorneys fees to a Contra leader, a former CIA official and others
who had been accused in a civil lawsuit of mounting a guns-for-drugs
scheme to aid the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King in June threw out
the $24 million lawsuit filed by the Christic Institute on behalf of
journalists Tony Avirgan and Martha Honey. The judge said the
plaintiffs failed to prove their case, and defense attorneys
immediately filed a motion seeking to recover damages caused by the
lawsuit.
   Today the judge ruled again in their favor, saying the Christic
Institute and the plaintiffs would have to pay the defendants
$955,000 in attorneys fees and $79,500 in court costs.
   The judge said the lawsuit was ``based on unsubstantiated rumor
and speculation from unidentified sources with no first-hand
knowledge.''
   Among the defendants the plaintiffs accused of mounting the
extensive illegal operation were Contra director Adolfo Calero,
former CIA deputy director of operations Theodore Shackley,
Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord and Albert Hakim, and former Maj.
Gen. John K. Singlaub.
   Singlaub's attorney Thomas Spencer said he was elated by the
decision.
   The liberal, Washington-based Christic Institute, which has
appealed King's original decision to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, had no immediate reaction to today's ruling.
   Avirgan and Honey filed the lawsuit in May 1986, prior to many of
the revelations in the Iran-Contra affair.
   It grew from a 1984 bombing in Nicaragua apparently aimed at
maverick Contra leader Eden Pastora. Pastora escaped, but Avirgan
was injured and several other people were killed.
   The lawsuit accused the defendants of setting up the bombing, as
well as working with drug traffickers in a 30-year conspiracy that
covered activities in Southeast Asia, Central America and other
locations.
</TEXT>
