<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   02-03 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0458,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Soviet Convoy Departs Leaving Small Contingent Behind</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with huge Soviet convoy departing
Kabul; few Soviets remain behind. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Speaking of...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge column of Soviet tanks and
trucks rumbled out of Kabul early today, and Soviet and Afghan
sources said the departure left only about 1,500 Red Army soldiers
in the country.
   The convoy rolled out of the marshaling yard at the base of the
Salang Highway under cover of darkness and began the 260-mile
journey north to the Soviet border in a heavy snowstorm.
   Afghan soldiers manned the Soviet outposts along the highway and
Soviet flags were replaced with the red, green and black flags of
Afghanistan.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas, called mujahedeen, have pounded
departing Soviet convoys with artillery fire in recent days.
   The Afghan and Soviet sources said that no more than 1,500 Red
Army soldiers would remain in the country once the convoy reached
Soviet soil.
   They said they did not know how many vehicles or soldiers were in
the convoy, which took three hours to move out. Early this week,
Western and Soviet diplomats said about 15,000 Soviet soldiers were
still in the country.
   The Afghan and Soviet sources said the small contingent that
remained in Kabul today will guard the city's airport during an
airlift that will continue for at least a week.
   The Soviet Union, which once had about 100,000 troops in
Afghanistan is to complete its withdrawal by Feb. 15 under the terms
of a U.N.-brokered accord signed last year.
   On Thursday, President Najib said his army was ``mightier than
ever'' and ready for battle with the guerrillas, who predict an easy
time overthrowing the government once the Soviet pullout is
completed.
   The Afghan army ``can defend the country against any onslaught,
and we will prove it,'' Najib said at a two-hour news conference at
the Foreign Ministry, in a room unheated because of the fuel
shortage in the capital.
   As he spoke, another Soviet convoy of about 100 trucks, armored
vehicles and tanks headed for the Salang Highway.
   In Peshawar, Pakistan, border headquarters of a seven-party
insurgent alliance, a guerrilla leader predicted Najib's regime
``will fall in weeks, not months.'' Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, head of the
guerrilla group Hezb-i-Islami, said at a news conference that the
insurgents would not have to attack the cities.
   Speaking of a possible political settlement with the rebels,
Najib said his Communist Party must be part of any future
government. ``Any attempt to exclude'' the party ``and its allies
from a coalition goverment will be in vain,'' he said.
   The guerrillas have rejected offers of settlements based on that
assumption and say they are forming a council to choose an Islamic
government.
   Explosions and artillery fire could be heard in and around the
capital Thursday, where insurgent attacks have created severe food
and fuel shortages.
   Mountain guerrilla camps surround Kabul, and insurgent commander
Ahmed Shah Masoud controls the Panjshir Valley, through which the
Salang runs.
   Pakistan and Iran, the neighboring nations in which more than 5
million Afghan refugees live, urged the squabbling guerrilla
factions Thursday to patch up their differences and form a
broad-based government in Kabul as soon as the Soviets are gone.
   Najib, asked whether he would be willing to resign as part of a
settlement, said: ``The resignation of a person will not help to
solve any problem.''
   He expressed optimism that Eduard A. Shevardnadze, the Soviet
foreign minister, would work out a settlement at a meeting with
Pakistani leaders Saturday, but added that Pakistan must change its
position.
   ``Pakistan has not only refused to adhere to its commitment under
the Geneva agreements, but it has quantitatively and qualitatively
intensified and expanded its armed interferences and aggressions,''
he said.
   Najib's assurances about the ability of his conscript army,
estimated to number about 140,000, contrasted with uncertainty on
the part of others.
   Several governments, including the United States, are closing
their embassies and evacuating the staffs because of concern about
what will happen when the Soviets are gone. Bangladesh joined the
growing list Thursday.
</TEXT>
