<FIRST>r a PM-Landfill-Cancer     02-03 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landfill-Cancer,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Study Cites Above Normal Leukemia Rates Around No. 1 Superfund
Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITMAN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People living near the the nation's No. 1
Superfund toxic waste cleanup site had higher-than-average rates of
adult leukemia and of babies born underweight, a state study
concluded.
   The state Department of Environmental Protection's study was
released Thursday at a community meeting at a Pitman elementary
school, and was quickly criticized by many residents as being
incomplete.
   The 2{-year study, which covered residents of the Gloucester
County towns of Pitman, Mantua, Glassboro and Harrison, found normal
or below-normal rates of types of cancer other than adult leukemia
among residents within six-tenths of a mile of the defunct Lipari
landfill.
   ``It's superficial; the data base looks awful,'' said Joseph L.
Manganello, an assistant professor at Gloucester Community College
who has taught classes in statistics.
   ``If this is supposed to be a comprehensive study, I'd hate to
see one that isn't,'' Manganello said. ``The study should have gone
back more years and collected more data.''
   The cancer study looked at data from 1980 through 1984, and the
infant birth weight studies compared babies born in the 1960s, 1970s
and 1980s, according to today's editions of The Philadelphia
Inquirer.
   ``These findings suggest that the most adverse health effects
occurred during the 1970s, when exposures to hazardous substances
were probably the heaviest,'' the study concluded. But it stressed
that the limited information covered by the study could not prove
that the landfill caused the increased leukemia and low-birth-weight
rates.
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency has set aside $20
million to clean up the 15-acre landfill 12 miles south of Camden,
which is ranked at the top of the Superfund priority list of more
than 900 toxic-waste sites.
   The Lipari landfill began operations in 1958, taking wastes from
several nearby plants. It was closed by the state in 1971 after
residents complained of respiratory problems, nausea, dying
vegitation, and odors. Numerous carcinogens such as benzene,
methylene chloride and aresnmic have been found at the site.
   In 1983, the landfill was sealed off by a containing wall and
cover made of polyethylene. The next phase of the cleanup involves
flushing contaminants from the landfill, a process that could take
up to seven years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
