<FIRST>r a PM-DeadlyFumes 1stLd-Writethru a0560 02-03 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deadly Fumes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Dead, Three Hurt, From Fumes in Federal Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to Dirksen sted Dirken.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fumes from a solvent used to strip wax from a
bathroom floor overcame four people, killing one and injuring three
at the downtown federal building, authorities said today.
   Two cleaning company workers were stripping floor wax from a
washroom on the 21st floor of the Dirksen Federal Building about 9
p.m. Thursday when fumes from the thinner caused them to collapse,
said Michael Ahearn, a Fire Department deputy district chief.
   A security guard who pulled the men from the bathroom and a woman
who came into contact with the fumes also became ill.
   Randy White, 31, one of the bathroom workers, was dead on arrival
at Northwestern Memorial Hospital at 10:05 p.m., said Roxanne
Sanderson, a hospital spokeswoman.
   White's co-worker, Vincent Brewer, 32, was in critical condition
in Northwestern's intensive care unit today, Ms. Sanderson said.
   Adam Barnes, 37, the building security guard, became ill as the
men were being transported to ambulances, said police Capt. John
Clisham.
   Barnes was treated and released at the hospital, as was Cherie
Halsey, 24, Ms. Sanderson said. She did not know how Ms. Halsey came
into contact with the fumes.
   The bathroom where the men were working lacked adequate
ventilation, Ahearn said. The container holding the solvent stated
that the area must be well-ventilated when the product is in use,
said Karen Morgan, a nursing supervisor at the hospital.
</TEXT>
