<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett     02-03 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Lack of Cabinet Seat Won't Hamper Anti-Drug Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, who will lead
administration anti-drug efforts, said Friday his lack of a
permanent seat at President Bush's Cabinet table will not impair his
ability to deal effectively with other top officials.
   ``I have the confidence of the president,'' Bennett said in an
interview. ``I know that. He said it. I heard it. He said it to my
colleagues.''
   In a meeting of top-level appointees, Bush told everyone that
Bennett would be in charge of drug-control programs and said, ``You
are to work with him,'' Bennett recalled.
   ``He has since reiterated that,'' he said. ``He's told me, `I
want you to be able to do it (the new job) in a way that's
unencumbered.'''
   Bennett also said he's been assured by Bush that he will be
invited to Cabinet meetings when they pertain to the anti-drug
effort.
   Several members of Congress, including Senate Judiciary Committee
Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., who will preside over Bennett's
confirmation hearings starting March 1, have criticized Bush's
decision to leave the ``drug czar'' out of the Cabinet.
   ``I'm worried that the president has made a crucial mistake,
maybe in part by oversight, by not having the drug coordinator at
the table,'' Biden said Thursday.
   The director of national drug control policy ``has to do what
none of the others (in the Cabinet) has to do,'' said Biden. ``He
has to take them on, as a practical matter. He is entering the most
dangerous world in Washington, and that is the world of fiefdoms.''
   As soon as Bennett is confirmed, he will have 180 days to develop
a drug control strategy covering more than 30 agencies spread
throughout the federal government. Those agencies are under the more
direct control of individual department secretaries.
   ``I appreciate the concern of Senator Biden,'' said Bennett, who
met with him last week and was making courtesy calls on other
members of the Judiciary Committee on Friday afternoon.
   Bennett also said he had met with some department heads, such as
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   He said he has not been involved ``except in a very general way''
in developing the budget for fiscal 1990 that Bush is to present
Feb. 9. ``We're not going to get really involved in that until we've
finished our six-month plan,'' he said.
   The 180-day deadline for development of a drug strategy is the
reason his confirmation hearings were delayed until March 1,
according to both Bennett and Biden, who said he originally had
wanted the hearings to begin a month earlier.
   ``The clock is running the day I'm confirmed,'' Bennett said.
``Senator Biden and I discussed this and we decided to put off the
hearings a bit to give us time to set up our staff, figure out how
the office is going to run.''
   He said he still has not decided who will be his top two deputies
_ one to work on reduction of demand for drugs and the other on
cutting the supply.
   Bennett vowed the day he was named to the job by Bush, Jan. 12,
that he would quit smoking by the time he was confirmed. He said
Friday he hadn't yet, but ``I will be done by the time I take
office. I've set a date for that, but I'm not going to preach until
I've succeeded.''
</TEXT>
