<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hirohito-Amnesty     02-03 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito-Amnesty,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Plans to Pardon 30,000 For Hirohito's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will pardon about 30,000 people and reinstate
certain rights for about 11 million others as part of the funeral
for Emperor Hirohito, news reports said Friday.
   Chief government spokesman Keizo Obuchi said the government would
pardon people guilty of 17 minor offenses, including violations of
traffic laws and the Alien Registration Law, news reports said.
   The plan also includes reinstating certain rights for about 11
million people, such as the right to vote, to run for public office
or to obtain driver's licenses because of past offenses, the reports
quoted Obuchi as saying.
   The plan is to be approved at a Cabinet meeting next week after
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita returns from the United States, the
reports said.
   Thirty-one foreigners on trial for violating the controversial
Alien Registration Law have said they are opposed to pardons because
they would eliminate their ability to protest in court against the
law's requirement that all resident aliens be fingerprinted and
carry identification cards.
   The amnesty plan excludes people convicted of bribery, and
therefore will not apply to former Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka, who
was convicted in 1987 of receiving a bribe of $3.9 million from the
U.S. Lockheed Corp. to facilitate the sale of aircraft to a Japanese
airline.
   The government has pardoned criminals on previous occasions, such
as Japan's admission to the United Nations in 1956, the wedding of
then Crown Price Akihito in 1959 and the return of Okinawa from the
United States in 1972.
   The Foreign Ministry said Friday that 133 countries have notified
Japan they will send representatives to Hirohito's funeral on Feb.
24. Of the total, 54 nations have said they will send their head of
state, a ministry official said.
   A senior official in the National Police Agency said it plans to
mobilize 32,000 police to guard dignitaries and Japanese officials
at the funeral. At least six radical groups opposed to the imperial
system have threatened to disrupt the funeral.
</TEXT>
