<HEAD>Federal Marshals Capture Church of Love Convicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal marshals staking out a post office
box in Florida captured two fugitives who fled Illinois after their
federal fraud convictions in a mail-order sex fantasy scam.
   Marshals recognized Donald S. Lowry Thursday despite a new beard
when they pulled up next to him in a car in Lantana, Fla., said U.S.
Marshal James Fyke. Lowry also had a fake driver's license.
   Lowry, 60, surrendered and led authorities to a house in Lake
Worth where they found Pamala St. Charles, 25, who had dyed her hair
and was using her maiden name of Ortiz, Fyke said at a news
conference.
   A federal jury convicted Lowry and St. Charles of mail fraud,
conspiracy and money laundering charges on Dec. 16 after prosecutors
accused them of bilking $4.5 million from 31,000 men nationwide
using the Church of Love _ a lonely hearts club for older men.
   Prosecutors said the two, both of Bettendorf, Iowa, illegally
cheated men out of money by selling phony stories of nude ``angels''
at a retirement paradise called Chonda-Za using a mail order system
linked to Lowry's Moline-based Church of Love.
   Lowry and St. Charles were free on bond pending sentencing April
7, when they disappeared. Federal warrants for their arrests were
issued Jan. 19 when they failed to check in with probation officers.
Interviews with Church of Love members and others led marshals to
suspect the pair might be in Florida, Fyke said.
   The two were expected to appear in court in West Palm Beach this
afternoon and Fyke said they probably would be returned to Illinois
in the next 10 days.
</TEXT>
