<HEAD>Imprisoned Mandela Colleague Undergoes Eye Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imprisoned guerrilla leader Walter
Sisula, a close colleague of Nelson Mandela, has undergone eye
surgery to remove a cataract, his daughter said Friday.
   Sisulu, 76, was moved from Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town to
nearby Tygerburg Hospital on Jan. 23, according to his daughter,
Nonkweko Mavumbe.
   The African National Congress leader, who has been imprisoned for
25 years, underwent a successful operation the next day to remove a
cataract from his left eye and returned to prison Jan. 27, Ms.
Mavumbe said.
   She said he had a similar operation on his right eye last year
and had not suffered a loss of vision.
   Prison officials declined comment on the daughter's report.
   Sisulu and Mandela were sent to prison after the same trial for
sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-run government. The
banned ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, is the main black group
fighting the government.
   Officials have released several aging and ailing black activists
in recent years, prompting widespread speculation that Sisulu could
be freed soon. However, the government has said nothing.
