<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. relief officials plan to begin
airlifting food and medical supplies into the besieged capital of
Afghanistan within a few days, U.N. officials in Geneva and New York
said today.
   ``This is one of many actions of Operation Salaam,'' the U.N.
relief campaign for Afghanistan, said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes.
``It's all in the effort to assist in the reconstruction of
Afghanistan.''
   U.N. officials in Geneva, speaking by telephone on condition of
anonymity, confirmed that an agreement had been reached with Afghan
guerrillas in which they promised not to attack relief planes.
   In return, the United Nations has pledged to send more relief
supplies into regions controlled by the Islamic rebels, who call
themselves the mujahedeen.
   ``The airlifts have not started, but it is not the only action
that is being taken,'' Ms. Younes said.
   She said it was part of ``an overall action,'' implying that
Kabul, the Afghan capital, and the mujahedeen areas would both
receive relief supplies.
   ``There have been contacts all along with all the parties,'' she
added.
   The agreement comes as the last units of Soviet troops are
pulling out of Kabul, where food and fuel shortages have been
reported.
   Guerrilla leaders have predicted that Kabul and other cities
controlled by the Afghan army will fall when the Soviet pullout is
completed.
