<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ChemicalArms     02-03 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Chemical Arms,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Body to Seek Export Curbs on Chemicals for Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany has asked the European
Economic Community to adopt an export ban on chemicals that go into
chemical weapons, and such a plan will be considered this month, a
group spokesman said Friday.
   The plan was prompted by a letter this week to Jacques Delors,
president of the EEC Commission, from West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, said the spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   West Germany is embroiled in a scandal over the supply of
equipment to what the United States alleges is a chemical weapons
plant in Libya.
   The spokesman said the proposed EEC legislation would be
presented to a meeting of the body's foreign ministers in Brussels
on Feb. 20.
   The 12 EEC states now have an informal embargo on export of
chemicals that could be used to make weapons. It was declared in
1984 after it became known that chemical arms were used in the
Iran-Iraq war.
   The spokesman said the EEC Commission envisons a formal ban on
the export of ``certain chemicals to certain countries.'' He did not
elaborate.
</TEXT>
