<HEAD>Vietnamese to Visit Hong Kong to Process Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese officials will come to Hong Kong this
month to try to arrange this British colony's first major
repatriation of Vietnamese boat people, a government spokesman said
Friday.
   The four-member Vietnamese delegation will leave for Bangkok,
Thailand, on Feb. 10, and fly on to Hong Kong, said government
spokesman Akber Khan.
   They will issue travel documents to countrymen who wish to return
home after fleeing Vietnam by boat. About 300 have asked to go home,
and Hanoi has cleared 141 cases for consideration, officials say.
   More than 25,000 Vietnamese are detained in Hong Kong camps,
including about 15,000 eligible to resettle but not accepted by a
foreign government.
   About 10,000 arrived after a new policy took effect in June.
Under the new rules, they face forced repatriation unless they can
prove they fled their homeland for fear of persecution.
   Until now, only about two dozen of the Vietnamese who sailed to
Hong Kong since the end of the Vietnam War have voluntarily returned
to their homeland.
