<FIRST>r a AM-Homeless-Tower     02-03 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless-Tower,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Offers Abandoned Tower as Shelter For Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK HALL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kent County officials had no trouble
turning down an offer by the federal government to help house the
homeless _ the government was offering an old military observation
tower as a shelter.
   The federal Department of Health and Human Services recently
notified county officials that they could lease the abandoned tower
for the homeless. It's 80 feet tall, devoid of heat, electricity or
running water and situated in a remote part of the county.
   ``It's ludicrous,'' said county administrator William H. Landon.
``I can't believe anybody ever bothered to take a look at the
thing.'' The largely rural county has few problems with homeless
anyway, officials said.
   ``If we had any homeless, we certainly wouldn't take them down
there and put them in an 80-foot tower, not if we had their best
interests at heart,'' said county commission President Alexander P.
Rasin III.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development said Thursday that the notice to the county may have
been an error.
   ``We've been getting a lot of calls about things like this,''
said the spokesman, William A. Glavin. ``Either properties are too
remote or they somehow wouldn't work.''
   A federal judge in Washington ordered HUD to determine which of
more than 300 surplus government properties could be used to shelter
the homeless under the Stewart B. McKinney Homeless Assistance Act
of 1987. The ruling resulted from a lawsuit brought by homeless
advocates.
   HUD officials had only a month to determine which surplus sites
should be offered and gathered information by sending questionnaires
about the properties to other federal agencies. It is unlikely that
anyone from HUD actually visited the tower or contacted local
officials about it until now, Glavin said.
   The 1940s-era steel tower was used by the U.S. Army as an
observation platform during gun tests at Aberdeen Proving Ground.
</TEXT>
