<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceHoax     02-03 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Hoax,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Call Reporting Officer Shot Turns Out to Be Elaborate Hoax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone used accurate police jargon over a
restricted frequency to report an officer had been shot, sparking a
hunt involving 24 officers, two helicopters and police dogs,
authorities said.
   The tense, two-hour search ended when a radio roll call
determined that no officer was missing, said Wilshire Division Sgt.
Stan Freedman.
   The man claimed to be an investigator with the police Community
Resources Against Street Hoodlums unit. He issued a high-priority
call reporting that an officer had been wounded while pursuing a
drug dealer Wednesday night, Freedman said.
   Police quickly surrounded a midcity area to search for the
officer.
   The mysterious caller had initially asked dispatchers to run
license plate checks on a number of cars, but when asked for a radio
identification number, the caller went silent, police said.
   That number usually appears automatically on the dispatcher's
screen and among other things is used to pinpoint a patrol car's
location.
   Minutes later, the man radioed again, saying he was running after
a suspected drug dealer, Freedman said.
   ``He then broadcast: `Officer down,''' one of the department's
highest priority calls, reserved for times when officers appear to
be wounded, police Lt. Otis Dobine said. ``Because he was using
police jargon, it was believable.''
   Authorities were trying to determine how the caller was able to
tap into restricted frequencies used by police for emergency calls.
The man may have gotten his hands on a misplaced hand-held police
radio, Freedman said.
   ``We do have missing Rover hand-held radios that have been stolen
or lost,'' he said.
</TEXT>
