<FIRST>u i PM-UN-AfghanAirlift 1stLd-Writethru   02-03 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Afghan Airlift, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0608,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Plans Humanitarian Airlift Into Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout with details on relief project. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. relief officials plan to begin
airlifting food and medical supplies into Afghanistan's besieged
capital within a few days, U.N. officials said today.
   U.N. officials in Geneva, speaking by telephone and on condition
of anonymity, said Afghan guerrillas had agreed not to attack the
relief planes.
   In return, the United Nations has pledged to send more relief
supplies into regions controlled by the Islamic rebels, who call
themselves the mujahedeen.
   ``This is one of many actions of Operation Salaam (the U.N.
relief campaign for Afghanistan),'' said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia
Younes. ``It's all in the effort to assist in the reconstruction of
Afghanistan.''
   ``The airlifts have not started, but it is not the only action
that is being taken,'' Ms. Younes said.
   She said it was part of ``an overall action,'' implying that
Kabul, the Afghan capital, and the mujahedeen areas would both
receive relief supplies.
   ``There have been contacts all along with all the parties,'' she
added.
   The agreement comes as the last units of Soviet troops are
pulling out of Kabul, where food and fuel shortages have been
reported.
   Guerrilla leaders have predicted that Kabul and other cities
controlled by the Afghan army will fall when the Soviet pullout is
completed. The Red Army, which entered Afghanistan in December 1979,
is to be out by Feb. 15 under a U.N.-mediated accord.
   Operation Salaam plans to spend more than $1.1 billion over two
years in Afghanistan. The project includes clearing the nation of
mines, repatriating millions of Afghan refugees from neighboring
Pakistan and Iran, and reviving Afghanistan's agricultural economy.
   The Soviet Union has so far pledged $600 million for the
campaign, out of total pledges of $887.6 million. The United States
pledged $16.7 million.
