<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolMother     02-03 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Mother,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Of Truant Must Attend Classes, Too</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who allowed her daughter to skip
school was ordered to attend classes with the teen-ager, but she
said Friday would be her last day in school.
   Jeanetta Norvell, 45, was sentenced Monday to one day in jail and
the rest of the school year with her daughter, Diana, at West Junior
High School because Diana missed too many classes.
   But Mrs. Norvell, who skipped math class to speak in a telephone
interview Friday, said her school days are over because her daughter
turns 16 Saturday and is eligible to drop out.
   ``I'm withdrawing her Monday,'' Mrs. Norvell said. ``It's a
pretty sad thing that a 45-year-old adult has to go to a junior high
school, but it was more humiliating to be treated like a common
criminal.''
   Mrs. Norvell was convicted of permitting her daughter to skip
school five days between October and December of last year.
   ``Diana hates school,'' Mrs. Norvell said.
   Cabell County Circuit Judge Dan O'Hanlon ordered Mrs. Norvell to
accompany her daughter to school for the rest of the year and stay
with her throughout the school day. The judge also said she may not
leave the state without permission of the county probation office,
according to court records.
   It was believed to be the first time in West Virginia that a
parent has served time for allowing a child to be truant.
   West Junior High Principal Charles Buell said some of his
students have been required in the past to attend school past the
age of 16, but he said a final decision is up to O'Hanlon.
   ``I guess if this is the only way to make sure that children
attend school it's worth it,'' Buell said. ``But I'm really not in
favor of having parents follow their children around in school.''
</TEXT>
