<FIRST>u a PM-TurnpikeExplosives 1stLd-Writethru a0563 02-03 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turnpike Explosives, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0563,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorneys Deny Prosecutor Contention In Terrorist Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with prosecutor saying published report
incorrect and defense comment today. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government claims that a man described as
an international terrorist for carrying explosives on the New Jersey
Turnpike planned three bombings in New York, a defense attorney said
today.
   Ronald Kuby, Yu Kikumura's attorney, said that in a pre-sentence
report filed by the government, prosecutors claim his client
targeted the United Nations building, a Navy recruiting office and
an area of Manhattan's garment district.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito alleges Kikumura, 36, is a member
of the terrorist Japanese Red Army who was secretly planning attacks
in retaliation for the 1986 United States bombing of Libya. Alito
would neither confirm nor deny reports that Kikumura was acting at
the direction of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   Kikumura, convicted of illegally transporting explosives,
possession of firearms by an alien, possession of unregistered
firearms and carrying false travel documents, is to be sentenced
Monday.
   Alito said he would release the pre-sentence report later today.
   ``We are saying the attacks were planned by the Japanese Red Army
in retaliation for the bombing of Libya,'' Alito said. ``Any other
reports are probably coming from the defense attorneys, and they are
incorrect.''
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that Alito
identified Kikumura's targets as the three New York sites. Alito
said the reports were incorrect.
   Kuby said this morning, and government sources previously have
confirmed to The Associated Press, that a map of New York was found
in Kikumura's car when he was arrested April 12.
   Kikumura was arrested at a highway rest area with three 18-inch
pipe bombs in his car. The government says the bombs were capable of
destroying an average building.
   Kuby said the government claims the map had pinholes in them that
marked the three targets.
   ``The government says there was three pinholes in the map and
they were near a U.S. Navy recruiting office, the United Nations and
the garment district,'' Kuby said. ``They're are identifying the
targets and we're saying it's not true.''
   U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner convicted Kikumura Nov. 29
in a non-jury trial. He faces up to 100 years in prison.
</TEXT>
