<DOCNO> AP890203-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Prices Bjt   02-03 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Prices, Bjt,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Blasts Businesses For Raising Prices of Consumer Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced a crackdown Friday on
state-owned businesses that have raised prices and cut the
production of inexpensive products.
   The action, taking by the Council of Ministers, or cabinet, was
another attempt to ease chronic shortages of consumer goods.
   The council said it would require businesses to produce a minimum
amount of inexpensive consumer goods and would ban price increases
for items whose ``consumer properties change insignificantly,'' the
Tass news agency reported.
   Price increases for ``new and fashionable goods'' may not exceed
15 percent, the council decided.
   The decision was announced Friday, but had been approved in early
January, Council of Ministers spokesman Lev Voznesensky said in a
telephone interview. It did not affect the burgeoning cooperative
movement that has arisen under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev has said tackling the country's shortage of consumer
goods and food is a top priority of his economic restructuring
program.
   Because of Gorbachev's drive to make each factory pay its own
way, however, Soviet managers are in effect encouraged to seek the
highest markup they can on their products, and even to curtail
manufacture of cheap goods that bring little return.
   The consumer goods shortages _ known as ``deficits'' _ have
plagued the country for years, but Soviets complain that under
Gorbachev, new ones have appeared, including inexpensive items.
   One of the most talked about examples is soap. Soviets have
flooded the official press with angry letters and grumbled privately
that inexpensive soap has disappeared from shelves while expensive
bars are plentiful.
   ``I am writing this letter out of happiness that my husband
(according to a waiting list) received one bar of household soap and
a tube of `Zefir' toothpaste,'' one woman wrote sarcastically Dec.
28 in the labor daily Trud. ``I will take care of it to make sure it
lasts long, because it's unknown when such good fortune will visit
me again.''
   For state-owned Soviet factories and other businesses, the
problem is one of profits. They are required to be self-financing,
meaning they must not spend more money than they take in and will
not be bailed out by the government.
   As a result, many businesses have reduced production of
inexpensive goods that bring in little money, and increased output
of expensive items.
   Many Soviets complain they can't afford the costly alternatives
on their meager salaries, which average about $333 monthly. They
even charge that factory managers are withholding consumer goods
from the stores to try to sabotage Gorbachev's economic reforms.
   In October, Nikolai G. Belov, deputy director of the State
Committee on Statistics, called the substitution of cheap goods with
expensive alternatives ``hidden price hikes,'' and said that along
with increases in wages, inflation had developed. He did not give a
figure for inflation.
   Another decision of the Council of Ministers did pertain to
cooperatives, but its immediate effects were uncertain.
   Tass said cooperatives will be allowed to buy ``non-scarce foods
and non-edible commodities,'' presumably from the state, but that
any products made from them should be sold at prices fixed for
state-run retail shops.
   In the past, cooperative restaurants and other ventures could
only buy supplies from other cooperatives or independent sources
like the country's peasant markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay-Stroessner Bjt   02-03 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Stroessner, Bjt,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stroessner's Name, Picture Were Everywhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If his successors want to obliterate
the stamp Gen. Alfredo Stroessner put on Paraguay, they will have to
take down hundreds of pictures, rename towns and schools, and change
the thinking habits of two generations.
   One of the biggest towns in this landlocked nation is Ciudad
Presidente Stroessner. Asuncion's airport bears his name and he had
a huge neon sign erected in its central plaza to blink out the
declaration, ``Stroessner: Peace, Work and Well-being.''
   He seized power in 1954 and ruled for nearly 35 years _ longer
than any leader in the Western Hemisphere _ with a canny blend of
military force, political patronage and self-discipline.
   The red-haired son of a Bavarian immigrant, whose mother was of
Spanish heritage, began his military career at 20 and quickly
distinguished himself.
   During his long rule, Stroessner oversaw Paraguay's
transformation from a backwater with open sewers and no running
water to a relatively prosperous and modern nation.
   Then, on Friday, the 76-year-old general's era ended as it began,
with a coup by his second-in-command, Gen. Andres Rodriguez.
   Stroessner won eight presidential elections despite opposition
charges of fraud.
   Even his critics admit he helped stabilize Paraguay. In the 31
years before he took over, it had 22 presidents.
   Yet, he also was accused of brutal repression and corruption, and
his country became a haven for fugitive Nazis, drug traffickers and
former dictators.
   Among the refugees were Josef Mengele, the Auschwitz death camp
doctor who became a citizen of Paraguay in 1959 and was befriended
by Nazi sympathizers; Edward Rochmann, the Nazi ``Butcher of Riga'';
ousted President Anastasio Somoza of Nicaragua, who was assassinated
in Paraguay; drug trafficker Joseph August Ricorde; and Croation
militant and convicted assassin Miro Baresic.
   As convenient tools for keeping order, Stroessner had his
perpetual state of siege and Law 209 _ the Law for the Defense of
Democracy _ that gave his government the power to make sure there
was no democracy to defend.
   Stroessner's ubiquitous approach to governing included
innumerable speeches, sometimes lasting hours, in which he often
would list his public works projects in great detail.
   Among the most impressive of those was the $16 billion Itaipu
dam, the world's largest hydroelectrical project, built in
partnership with neighboring Brazil. It began producing power in
1985.
   He attended hundreds of ground-breakings and other public
ceremonies each year, even in outlying towns, and served regularly
as a witness at weddings even when he didn't know the bride or groom.
   Spartan habits and a busy schedule were the reasons for his
longevity and energy, he said. Stroessner does not smoke and drinks
little.
   Public dissatisfaction with the government became increasingly
evident in the mid-1980s, when protesters and police clashed in the
streets.
   The Roman Catholic Church and even a faction of Stroessner's
Colorado Party began criticizing the president, accusing him of
repression and demanding democratic reforms.
   Human rights groups said many of Stroessner's foes were tortured
and killed during his early years in power. Others were jailed
indefinitely, convicted of political crimes or forced into exile.
   He was a rabid anti-communist and staunch ally of the United
States, but the general's relations with Washington cooled when the
Reagan administration referred to his government as a dictatorship.
   Stroessner attended Paraguay's military academy, graduating in
1929, and as a 20-year-old lieutenant led a mortar platoon in the
Chaco War with Bolivia. He distinguished himself for bravery and
rose quickly through the ranks, reaching the rank of general at age
40. He became army chief of staff in 1951.
   In the first four years after seizing power, Stroessner put down
five attempted coups by exiled politicians and began dismantling the
political opposition.
   Using special powers under the state of siege, which was renewed
every 90 days until last year, civilian and military police arrested
thousands of opponents. Stroessner referred to virtually all his
opponents as subversives.
   Critics say his government promoted a side economy dominated by
contraband. Many government and military officials, including
relatives and close associates, became rich through ties with
Stroessner.
   The general is said to have been ill since a prostate operation
five months ago. His apparent slow recovery increased demands by
opposition leaders for a transition to democratic rule by the army
and Colorado Party.
   He and his wife, Eligia, have three children: Gustavo, an air
force colonel with many business interests; Hugo Alfredo, a
businessman, and Graciela Gonzalez Llamas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
