<FIRST>r a AM-Convicts-Tourism     02-03 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Convicts-Tourism,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Female Prisoners To Promote N.C. Vacation Spots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When residents of other states telephone
this spring to ask about vacation prospects in North Carolina, the
voice on the other end will belong to a state prisoner.
   Beginning in March, inmates at the North Carolina Correctional
Institution for Women will field inquiries for the Division of
Travel and Tourism, Gov. Jim Martin announced Thursday.
   The 16 or so women will be instructed about vacation
opportunities and on how to dispense advice, the governor said. The
program should provide valuable job training for the inmates while
improving the efficiency of the tourist-inquiry service, he said.
   Inmate labor has been used successfully for similar tasks in
other states, said Commerce Secretary Claude Pope.
   Martin drew criticism during his re-election campaign last year
because of slow responses to out-of-state inquiries about vacation
prospects in North Carolina. At one point in the summer, the backlog
of unfilled requests for information neared 100,000, and critics
said it was costing the state money in lost tourism dollars.
   The Division of Travel and Tourism has already used female
prisoners to package travel brochures, eventually eliminating the
backlog. Now, they will answer calls as well.
   David Guth, spokesman for the state corrections department, said
the inmates will earn $1 a day, the standard rate of pay for state
jobs done by prisoners.
   Male inmates can get jobs in printing, agriculture, and furniture
making for the state, but the state's only women's prison has few
similar jobs.
   ``There are just not a lot of opportunites for our women
prisoners to work and this seemed like an ideal one,'' Guth said.
   ``And from a psychological standpoint, women offenders are
generally better suited to this kind of work,'' Guth said. ``Male
offenders are often rougher and committed rougher crimes than women
offenders, and they are not the types you want answering questions
on the phone.
   ``Even women offenders who commit murder generally did so as a
result of abuse or some other factor and they better fit the
psychological profile we want for this type of job.''
</TEXT>
