<HEAD>Barbara Bush Carries Clothes to Community Center, Schedules Media
Interviews</HEAD>
<UNK>EDS: Will be topped after 2:30 p.m. EST interview.</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush visited a community
services organization Friday, carrying bags full of donated toys and
clothes and telling reporters ``we've got to help the working poor.''
   Mrs. Bush also scheduled her first media interviews since
becoming first lady as she kept up a busy schedule before she and
President Bush left for their first weekend at Camp David.
   Earlier Friday, Mrs. Bush visited the United Community Ministries
Inc. in the Washington suburb of Alexandria and praised the center's
staff of volunteers.
   ``It reinforces my belief that we have got to help the working
poor,'' she told reporters during her 40-minute visit.
   The first lady helped carry from the trunk of her limousine seven
plastic bags full of clothes and toys that she and members of the
White House staff donated.
   The center is a private, non-profit organization whose programs
include a thrift shop, food pantry, medical clinics, day care,
counseling and financial assistance.
   In the thrift shop, Mrs. Bush was joined by volunteers Eileen
Friedman, a member of the board of directors, and 78-year-old Jessie
Stark as she looked over secondhand clothes being offered for sale
at nominal prices.
   She posed for photographers with four children from the
facility's day care center. They included 4-year-old Amber Daniels,
who handed Mrs. Bush a ``mock voting tally'' from the preschool
class, showing President Bush with a clear margin over Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   ``That just makes me feel wonderful,'' the first lady said.
   Mrs. Bush also visited United Community Ministries in 1984, the
year she was honorary chairwoman of the organization's fund-raiser.
</TEXT>
