<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SolomonSentence     02-03 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Solomon Sentence,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gets 18-To-Life for Slaying Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who reported his wife missing and
led a search for her was sentenced Friday to 18 years to life in
prison for murdering her on Christmas Eve 1987.
   Matthew Solomon asked Suffolk County Court Judge Harvey Sherman
for leniency. Before being sentenced he also thanked his family for
its support and apologized to the family of his wife, Lisa.
   The prosecutor, Timothy Mazzei had asked Sherman to impose the
maximum, 25 years to life.
   Solomon, 24, will be eligible for parole when he is 42.
   Solomon was found guilty Nov. 18 of choking his 22-year-old wife
to death in their apartment in Huntington Station and dumping her
body, which was found more than a week later.
</TEXT>
