<FIRST>r a AM-CoveredBridgeFire     02-03 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Covered Bridge Fire,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Covered Bridge Burns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILIPPI, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 137-year-old covered bridge that
survived floods, tornadoes and an assault by Confederate troops was
done in by a gasoline leak and a car with a hot catalytic converter,
officials said Friday.
   The 312-foot Philippi Covered Bridge, the longest two-lane
covered bridge still in use on a federal highway, was destroyed by
fire Thursday night.
   Philippi City Manager Joe Mattaliano said he hoped the state can
repair the bridge, which carried U.S. 250 over the Tygart Valley
River.
   State Department of Highways officials were optimistic Friday
morning that the bridge's steel and concrete base was still
structurally sound. They planned a more thorough inspection later in
the day.
   A pool of gasoline that had trickled about 100 feet from a nozzle
being used to fill gas tanks at a service station was set off by a
car driving over the bridge, said firefighter Jeff Byrne.
   ``Apparently, the car's catalytic converter ignited the fuel,''
said Byrne. ``The women in the car said they heard a whoosing sound
and jumped out when they saw the road on fire.''
   No one was injured in the incident.
   Mattaliano, who was driving across the bridge when it caught
fire, said, ``I saw a wall of fire coming at me in my rear view
mirror. I got off the bridge in a hurry and called the Fire
Department.''
   The bridge, built in 1852 by Lemuel Chenoweth, was known for its
arched, all-poplar frame held together by iron bolts. It survived a
1910 flood and received minor damage in a 1985 blood. During the
Civil War, fleeing Confederate troops tried to burn the bridge to
prevent Union troops from following, but the attempt failed.
   ``This bridge is part of the history of West Virginia,'' said
Mattaliano. ``It survived floods and tornadoes.''
   With its loss, Philippi, a town of 3,700 people about 20 miles
southeast of Clarksburg, was left with only one other bridge, and
Mattaliano predicted traffic backups until the covered bridge could
be repaired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
