<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Soviet     02-03 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Soviet,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister to Try for Political Pact on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze enters talks this weekend in a bid to forge a political
settlement from nine years of futile intervention in Afghanistan's
civil war.
   His 17-hour visit, beginning Saturday night, caps a week of
hectic diplomatic efforts to avert more bloodshed as the Red Army
continues its troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Shevardnadze will be talking to officials of the Pakistani
government, which has backed and sheltered the most powerful
guerrilla forces fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed regime.
   ``We hope our talks with the Soviet leader will pave the way for
a peaceful settlement, although the situation on the ground in
Afghanistan is depressing,'' a Pakistani government spokesman said
this week.
   He was referring to bitter fighting between communist forces and
Moslem guerrillas. Some of the worst reported attacks have occurred
along the main Soviet withdrawal route from Kabul north to the
Soviet border.
   Moscow signed a U.N. accord last spring providing for removal of
the approximately 100,000 Soviet combat troops by Feb. 15.
   Although the last units are said to be en route home, there still
are no prospects for peace between Kabul's communist government and
tenacious Moslem insurgents armed by the United States, Pakistan and
other Islamic countries.
   All sides agree on the need for a settlement that will produce a
broad-based government to succeed the current regime, which seized
power in a bloody 1978 coup.
   President Najib of Afghanistan insists that such a new government
should retain some of his officials.
   However, the guerrillas consider the communists traitors for
inviting the Soviets to intervene in December 1979 and refuse to
negotiate with them.
   In addition, the guerrillas cannot agree among themselves on how
to form a transitional regime leading to a post-war Islamic republic
of Afghanistan.
   The insurgents' seven major parties, Sunni Moslem groups
headquartered in Pakistan, are at odds with Shiite Moslem insurgent
groups based in Iran over proportional repesentation in a grand
``consultative council'' that is to lay groundwork for a new
government.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran flew to Pakistan
earlier this week for two days of talks. When he departed Thursday,
he said only that the anti-government forces of Afghanistan should
work together to restore peace.
   In addition to backing the insurgents, Pakistan and Iran also
shelter more than 5 million Afghan refugees.
   Shevardnadze is the highest-ranking Soviet official to visit
Pakistan in more than 20 years. He initiated the trip himself, said
a Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman on condition of anonymity.
The spokesman did not disclose the agenda.
</TEXT>
