<DOCNO> AP890203-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   02-03 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Soviet Convoy Departs, Leaving Small Contingent Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge Soviet convoy rolled out of
Kabul in a snowstorm Friday, and Afghan and Soviet sources said no
more than 1,500 Red Army soldiers would remain in Afghanistan once
the convoy reached Soviet soil.
   The column of trucks and tanks began their 260-mile journey north
up the Salang Highway under cover of darkness, said the sources, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 1,000 to 1,500 Soviet soldiers still in Kabul will guard the
city's airport during food airlifts that are to continue for at
least a week, the sources said.
   Under an accord sponsored by the United Nations to end the
Soviets' nine-year intervention in Afghanistan, the Red Army has
until Feb. 15 to withdraw.
   Guerrillas fighting the pro-Marxist government since 1978 are not
a party to the agreement and say they will take over when the
Soviets are gone.
   President Najib, however, said Thursday that his conscript army,
believed to number 140,000, was prepared to repel the insurgents.
   A United Nations human rights report issued Friday said the
Soviet Union and Afghan army had violated international law during
the withdrawal by sowing mines, many of them in civilian areas.
   U.N. workers who visited Afghanistan in June found Soviet mines
in agricultural areas, rivers and villages, and said the number of
explosives ranged from 5 million to 30 million, according to the
report to the U.N. Economic and Social Council.
   ``Mines designed to cause unnecessary suffering have been widely
dispersed throughout Afghanistan,'' the report said. ``This is a
clear violation of customary and conventional international law.''
   Many diplomats say the Afghan civil war will become a bloodbath
when the Soviets are gone, and most major Western countries,
including the United States, closed their embassies in Kabul this
week.
   Heavy snow Friday delayed the departure of British diplomats and
their staff, who were to leave on a chartered plane for India,
government officials in London said. There was no immediate word on
when they would leave.
   Soviet flags Friday were replaced with the red, green and black
flags of Afghanistan, and Afghan soldiers took over the Soviet
outposts along the Salang Highway.
   Afghan soldiers said the Soviet convoy snaked through the Salang
Pass and the mountains where guerrillas have pounded departing
contingents with artillery fire in recent days.
   The sources said they did not know how many vehicles or soldiers
were in the latest convoy but that it took three hours for it to
depart.
   Early this week, Western and Soviet diplomats said about 15,000
Soviet soldiers remained.
   A Geneva-based U.N. office coordinating relief for Afghanistan
said Friday that it planned to airlift food and medicine to Kabul,
whose population has swollen to 2 million because of refugees
streaming into the city.
   U.N. officials in Geneva, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed an agreement in principle had been reached with Afghan
guerrillas not to shoot down incoming relief planes. In return, the
United Nations has pledged to send more relief supplies into regions
controlled by the guerrillas.
   Also on Friday, officials in neighboring Pakistan denied claims
by Kabul that Pakistani jet fighters shot down an Afghan passenger
plane.
   Official Radio Kabul, monitored in the Pakistan capital of
Islamabad Thursday night, said the plane was carrying food suppplies
from Kabul to Khost, 12 miles from the Pakistan border, when it
strayed off course Tuesday.
   It said Pakistan ignored the pilot's call for help and shot it
down, killing all five passengers and a crew of nine.
   Pakistani military spokesman Riaz Ullah said the Afghan plane
crashed inside Pakistani territory apparently after running out of
fuel during a possible attempt to defect.
   The United States and Pakistan back the guerrillas, who began
fighting after a communist coup in April 1978. The Soviet soldiers
entered the country in December 1979, and grew in number to an
estimated 115,000 by the time the pullout began May 15.
   Eduard A. Shevardnadze, the Soviet foreign minister, will meet
with Pakistani leaders Saturday to discuss ways to end the civil war.
</TEXT>
