<FIRST>r w AM-CourtStudy     02-03 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Court Study,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel to Develop Plan for Federal Court System's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee created by Congress to develop
within 15 months a long-range plan for the federal court system's
future held its first meeting Friday, and its chairman warned
against ``ideological warfare.''
   ``The assignment is breathtaking ... a pioneering effort,'' said
chairman Joseph F. Weis Jr., a federal appeals judge from Pittsburgh.
   Weis said the committee would work toward issuing by April 1990 a
report recommending, among other things, what role federal courts
should play in the 21st century.
   He said the committee plans to conduct public hearings in Los
Angeles, Chicago, Boston and Atlanta within the next 45 days so
legal groups, civic organizations and anyone else interested may
suggest what topics should come under review.
   Weis said the committee, whose 15 members include officials from
each of the federal government's three branches, will study the
federal judiciary's structure, its relationship to state courts and
the types of cases it should be handling.
   Rep. Robert Kastenmeier, D-Wis., told fellow committee members
they should avoid ideological discussions about the role of federal
courts so that their efforts are not perceived as
``court-stripping'' attempts.
   Past efforts in Congress to limit the purview of federal courts _
such as blocking Supreme Court review of all cases involving school
prayer or abortion _ have proved controversial.
   Weis agreed with Kastenmeier, saying, ``I didn't intend to get
into any ideological warfare.''
   Besides Weis and Kastenmeier, the committee's members are Sens.
Howell Heflin, D-Ala., and Charles Grassley, R-Iowa; Rep. Carlos
Moorhead, R-Calif.; J. Vincent Aprile II, general counsel of the
Kentucky Department of Public Advocacy; Keith Callow, chief justice
of the Washington state Supreme Court; Edward Dennis Jr., a Justice
Department lawyer.
   Also federal trial judges Jose A. Cabranes of New Haven, Conn.,
and Judith Keep of San Diego, Calif; federal appellate judges Levin
H. Campbell of Boston and Richard A. Posner of Chicago; private
lawyers Morris Harrell of Dallas and Diana Gribbon Motz of
Baltimore; and Rex Lee, professor of law at Brigham Young University.
</TEXT>
