<FIRST>u w PM-Quayle 3rdLd-Writethru a0668-a0580 02-03 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0668-a0580,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Pledges Continuing Relationship with El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle told
the Salvadoran government today that democracy, eocnomic growth and
respect for human rights ``go hand in hand'' as he pledged a
continuing relationship between the Bush administration and El
Salvador.
   In a toast during a luncheon for government officials at the home
of President Jose Napoleon Duarte, Quayle repeatedly mentioned
commitment to human rights as a guiding principle for democratic
government.
   Earlier today, Quayle was urged by Archbishop Arturo Rivera y
Damas, acting as a go-between for a peace proposal by
anti-government rebels, to consider the dissidents' point of view.
   Quayle said in his toast that under Duarte's five-year term El
Salvador's human rights record has improved but that ``there are
challenges yet to be met and hurdles that must be overcome.''
   ``And the anti-democratic forces of the extreme left and the
extreme right are ideologically exhausted and weakened,'' he said.
But, he added, ``they're still out there.''
   He assured the Salvadorans of the commitment of the United States
to a shared vision of a secure democratic future in El Salvador.
``This is a vision of democracy, economic growth and respect for
human rights. The three go hand in hand,'' Quayle said.
   He made the comments following morning meetings with
representatives of Duarte's Christian Democratic Party and the
rightist Republican National Alliance or ARENA, two of the parties
vying to win next month's presidential election.
   During his meeting with the archbishop, Quayle said he was in San
Salvador in the interest of helping Salvadorans move toward peace
and democracy, said David Beckwith, Quayle's press secretary.
   Strife-torn El Salvador relies heavily on U.S. aid of some $1.5
million per day.
   Flying to San Salvador from Caracas, Quayle was taken by
helicopter from the airport to a point near the residence of
Ambassador William Walker, which was surrounded by security
personnel. He then got into a motorcade where press vans were
equipped with one-inch-thick windows against possible attack.
   Quayle was expected to discuss with Duarte and other political
leaders a proposal in which the rebels offered for the first time to
participate in elections if certain conditions are agreed to.
   State Department officials view the proposal as significant
because it marks a departure from the rebels' demand for
power-sharing, but say a decision on whether to act on it is in the
hands of Duarte and his government.
   As part of their proposal, the rebels want the March 19 elections
postponed until September. While that would violate the
Constitution's election timetable, a State Department official,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said outright rejection of the
plan could be used by U.S. opponents of aid to argue that Duarte's
government is not serious about seeking peace.
   ``It would present some obstacles'' to winning continued aid, the
official said.
   Quayle's talks Thursday with presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras
and Guatemala were among the 10 bilateral sessions he held during a
hectic visit to Caracas for the inauguration of Venezuela's new
president, Carlos Andres Perez.
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, author of a regional peace
plan signed in August 1987 by the five Central American presidents,
said after meeting with Quayle that he was optimistic the Bush
administration would allow further regional diplomatic efforts to
proceed instead of moving to restock the Nicaraguan rebels with
weapons.
   ``Mr. Quayle told me they want to give us a chance,'' Arias said.
   Quayle told reporters there is now a ``hiatus'' with no U.S. move
to renew funding for the Contras battling Nicaragua's leftist
government.
   Although he contended that Nicaragua's record on civil liberties
has regressed since Congress cut off military aid to the Contras, he
said: ``We are going to give the diplomatic route a chance.''
   ``This is a testing period for us,'' to see if Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega is serious about holding free elections and
implementing democratic reforms he agreed to in the Arias plan.
   Asked how the Bush administration would differ from President
Reagan's hardline pro-Contra policies, Arias adviser Francisco
Aguilar-Urbina said Bush is more pragmatic and that Latins feel
positively about his presidency so far.
   Quayle criticized former President Jimmy Carter, who also
attended the Venezuelan inauguration, for meeting with Ortega on
Wednesday.
   ``Obviously when you have a former president meeting with heads
of state we don't meet with, it has a chance of complicating
matters,'' Quayle said at a news conference.
   The U.S. government has refused to hold talks with Nicaragua.
   Carter said Ortega had shared with him and Perez a new peace
proposal regarding the Contras.
   Carter did not release details, and U.S. officials said they had
heard only general components of the Ortega proposal. They said it
dealt with resettlement of the Contras into Nicaragua once peace is
declared.
   Carter also talked at length with Cuban President Fidel Castro at
the inauguration ceremony.
   Arias met at length with Castro, asking his support for the
regional peace initiative. President Mario Soares of Portugal also
met with Castro shortly before Soares' meeting with Quayle Thursday
night.
   Quayle said he was pleased with his own meetings.
   ``You can feel the good chemistry,'' he said, adding that the
Latin leaders appeared to be ``positive'' about dealing with the
Bush administration.
</TEXT>
