<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Given 24 Hours to Leave Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bulgarian human rights activist of
Turkish extraction and her family were given 24 hours to leave their
country on Friday, a Bulgarian emigre reported.
   Zeneb Yusseinov, 31, is a leader of the Society of the Protection
of Human rights. Her husband, Yussuf Yusseinov, also is an activist
of the group that has been persecuted for months.
   The family was expected to go to Turkey, said Eduard Genov, an
exiled member of the society living in Los Angeles.
   Genov and other members of the group were earlier forced to
emigrate. They include Tseko Tsekov, who said in Vienna on Thursday
he was given a choice of emigration or renewed imprisonment.
   Tsekov said he had been badly beaten in a Bulgarian prison and
was planning to settle in the United States. He also said there are
380 political prisoners in Bulgaria, many of them living under
humiliating prison conditions.
   Bulgaria is among the 35 countries who adopted a key document on
greater civil freedoms at the Helsinki review conference in Vienna.
</TEXT>
