<FIRST>r i AM-China-Pizza     02-03 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Pizza,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Offered Alternative To Cheesy New York Pizza</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New York law student said Friday he is
signing a contract to open a not entirely New York-style pizzeria in
the Chinese capital where customers can hold the cheese and instead
pile on the pork.
   ``Beijing residents should be able to afford to eat there four or
five times a month,'' said entrepreneur Richard Rosenzweig. ``I
think they will come No. 1 for the atmosphere, but No. 2 for the
food. Over time, they'll develop a taste for the food.''
   He said he plans to decorate the 600-seat restaurant, which will
also offer takeout service, with New York street signs and play
American pop music.
   The obstacles are formidable. Cheese is not part of the Chinese
diet, and many Chinese don't like it on first bite.
   However, they will be allowed to order cheese-less pizza with
tomato sauce, vegetables and pork, China's staple meat, Rosenzweig
said.
   ``We're not going to change the recipe of the pizza; it'll be
authentic, but when it comes to toppings, we'll take a lot of
Chinese input,'' Rosenzweig said. ``They may want sea-slug pizza.''
   The 26-year-old remembers craving pizza in vain when he was
studying law in Beijing in 1986.
   Foreigners now can buy local chefs' versions of pizza at several
Western-run hotels, but there is no restaurant selling mainly pizza
to Chinese.
   Rosenzweig said the company he founded, New York City Pizza
Corp., will sign a joint venture contract Saturday with the Beijing
Yanhai Development and Trade Corp., a subsidiary of the Ministry of
Agriculture.
   He said the Chinese are putting up $1.8 million, including the
site in central Beijing. His side will put up $1.2 million and train
the staff in the arcane craft of making thin-crust, New York-style
pizzas.
   Ground-breaking on the restaurant is scheduled for March 1, and
Rosenzweig said it will be open by May 1, 1990.
   About a mile away, managers at Beijing's first Western fast-food
restaurant, Kentucky Fried Chicken, have been licking their fingers
over the good business. They say they sell an average of 1,300
chickens a day, more than any other restaurant in the chain
worldwide.
   Rosenzweig said his pizza restaurant will be even larger.
   ``This has got to be the biggest pizza restaurant in the world.
Where else in the world would there be a need for such a big
restaurant?'' he asked.
   Beijing has 10 million residents.
   Rosenzweig said about $1.70 will buy a slice of pizza and glass
of soda.
</TEXT>
