<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Africa-Mothers     02-03 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa-Mothers,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Calls for Campaign to Save Lives of Pregnant Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from 22 African countries called
on the continent's nations Friday to do more to save the lives of
pregnant women, hundreds of thousands of whom die each year.
   More than 1,000 pregnant women die around the world each day from
complications during pregnancy or childbirth, or from illegal
abortions, according to a study by the United Nations Children's
Fund.
   The study was the focus of a five-day conference of
French-speaking African nations, which called the deaths the ``shame
of modern times.''
   ``What a woman loses life in giving life is as intolerable as it
is unjust,'' a conference declaration said.
   About 450 pregnant women per 100,000 die each year in
underdeveloped nations, including those in Africa, compared with 30
per 100,000 in the West.
   Health ministers, doctors and representatives of African women's
organizations were among the participants of the conference, which
ended Friday. The sponsors were UNICEF, the World Health
Organization and the World Bank.
   They said the conference was part of an effort to get Third World
countries to devote more time and resources to saving the lives of
pregnant women.
   A similar conference was held two years ago in Nairobi, Kenya,
for English-speaking African nations.
   Participants said Africa should try to reduce the number of women
dying in childbirth by 50 percent in the next 25 years.
   According to U.N. studies, African women furnish 80 percent of
the food their families eat.
   They gather firewood, carry water, plant gardens, prepare food,
care for animals and look after children and the elderly. The women
work at least 12 to 16 hours a day and experts on Third World
development say they hold the key to helping nations struggling out
of poverty.
   Yet African women also are the most vulnerable members of their
society, said Edward Jaycox, World Bank vice president for Africa.
   ``When food is in short supply, she is the one who goes without,
when there is no doctor, she is the one who must deal with the risks
associated with frequent pregnancies,'' he told the conference.
   At least 63 percent of pregnant women in Africa suffer from
anemia and vitamin deficiencies that affect the health of their
infant, according to a UNICEF report. More than 45 percent of the
women deliver their children without medical help or midwives, the
report said.
   Throughout Africa, women also marry young and often have their
first child before age 15.
   ``The major problem in Africa today is preventing children from
having children,'' said Dr. Frederick Sai, the World Bank's
population specialist. ``And women of 45 or 50 who are having their
eighth or ninth child are dying from it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SakharovVisit     02-03 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov Visit,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov and Bonner Planning Boston Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just two months after visiting the United States
for the first time, Soviet human rights activist Andrei Sakharov is
planning a return trip, this time with his wife, Yelena Bonner,
according to friends and family.
   The Sakharovs are to fly from Moscow to Rome next week. After
five days in Italy, they plan to visit Canada and then fly to Boston
to see Mrs. Bonner's children.
   Mrs. Bonner's daughter, Tatiana Yankelevich of Newton, said
Friday the dates are still uncertain.
   Although both Sakharov and Bonner have visited the United States
before, this will be their first trip together.
   Sakharov, 67, won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his defense
of human rights. After speaking out against the Soviet intervention
in Afghanistan in 1979, he was exiled to the closed industrial city
of Gorky.
   Mrs. Bonner was banished there as well in 1984, and the couple
remained in Gorky until Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev personally
called them back to Moscow in December 1986.
   Although Sakharov generally has supported Gorbachev's
perestroika, or political and economic restructuring, he has
continued to express concern about political prisoners, the
treatment of various ethnic groups and the steady accumulation of
power in Gorbachev's hands.
   He received permission to visit the West last year. During the
trip, Nov. 4 to Dec. 8, Sakharov underwent a heart examination, met
President Reagan in Washington and visited New York.
   Mrs. Bonner came to Boston in January 1986 for cardiac bypass
surgery. While in the area, she and Sakharov have stayed with her
daughter.
   In addition, they have visited with her son and daughter-in-law,
Alexei and Liza Semyonov, and their children. The Semyonovs live in
suburban Westwood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
