<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Priest     02-03 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Priest,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Funeral of Pro-Solidarity Priest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 Roman Catholic clergymen led
thousands of mourners Friday in a funeral for a pro-Solidarity
priest killed in a fire, and the union called for an independent
inquiry into his death and that of another priest.
   The Rev. Stanislaw Suchowolec, 31, was buried in a small square
near the Immaculate Heart of Mary Church in Bialystok, a provincial
capital about 120 miles northeast of Warsaw. The city was home to
Suchowolec.
   The service was celebrated by Bialystok Bishop Edward Kisiel with
assistance of 162 priests, according to the Rev. Jozef Koszewnik.
   Koszewnik estimated that more than 10,000 people gathered for the
service. He said many carried banners from different chapters of the
banned trade union Solidarity and the banned Independent Students'
Association.
   ``We are parting with a great spokesman of Solidarity _ a man who
was always closely linked to the working class and to those who
struggle for human dignity,'' he quoted Kisiel as saying.
   Kisiel and Cezary Potocki, chancellor of the church's Bialystok
Curia, acknowledged the death caused great concern among Polish
Catholics.
   ``We hope that the concern will disappear when all the
circumstances are cleared up,'' Koszewnik quoted Potocki as saying.
   A fire caused by an electric stove Monday unleashed a cloud of
smoke that claimed the life of Suchowolec, the second priest killed
within 10 days. The Rev. Stefan Niedzielak of Warsaw, a Solidarity
sympathizer who maintained a shrine to Poles killed in the Soviet
Union in World War II, died of a broken neck Jan. 21.
   The results of a prosecutor's investigation into what caused the
stove fire have not been made public. Another investigation into the
death of Niedzielak has not been finished.
   In a statement Friday, the Warsaw regional chapter of Solidarity
expressed sorrow for the deaths and demanded that independent
representatives be allowed to take part in the investigations. It
said the results should be made public.
   Suchowolec actively supported Solidarity and organized
pilgrimages to the Warsaw gravesite of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a
popular pro-Solidarity priest murdered by security police in 1984.
   The young priest was buried next to a cross dedicated to
Popieluszko that Suchowolec had erected when he began to serve in
the parish 2{ years ago, Koszewnik said.
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity member, brought a wreath and
represented the union at the funeral.
   ``That man meant a lot to us,'' said his wife, Zofia, who also
monitors human rights for Solidarity. She said Suchowolec had
informed them that he was assaulted and that his car had been
tampered with at least twice. He also said his parents' apartment
was burned.
   The United States urged the Polish government earlier this week
to conduct a ``thorough and rapid'' investigation into the two
deaths.
   The Polish government has said it had no evidence the deaths were
politically motivated killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
