<FIRST>r i AM-PanchenLama     02-03 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panchen Lama,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Monks, Faithful Pay Last Respects to Panchen Lama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Buddhist monks in Tibet paid last
respects to the Panchen Lama on Friday, with ancient chants and
prayers for reincarnation of the man who served as Tibet's top
religious leader in China.
   About 800 monks lined up in the early morning outside the Panchen
Lama's official residence in Xigaze, Tibet's second-largest city,
according to the official Xinhua News Agency. They filed by to view
the body of the government loyalist and presented white silk scarves
as a sign of respect.
   Other monks chanted ancient scriptures praising the Panchen Lama
and prayed for his early reincarnation, and tens of thousands of
faithful paid homage to a photograph of the Panchen Lama in an
adjoining hall.
   The Panchen Lama, who died of a heart attack Jan. 28 in Xigaze,
was revered as a reincarnation of the Buddhist god Amitabha. He
served as the main Tibetan spokesman for the Chinese government.
   Xinhua said his body would be preserved by being ``treated with
precious medicines and bound with fine silks and satins, which will
be changed regularly.'' It said ``golden powder'' will be painted on
his face.
   The body will then be placed in a special shrine to be built in
his honor at Xigaze's Tashi Lump Monastery, his religious seat.
   His predecessors also were preserved, but their funeral shrines
were destroyed and their bodies dismembered by leftists during
China's 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
   A memorial service for the Panchen Lama also was held in Tibet's
capital of Lhasa, Xinhua said. It said hundreds of monks, nuns and
local government attended.
   Tibet's Communist Party secretary, Hu Jintao, praised the Panchen
Lama for playing ``an enormous and incomparable role'' in putting
into effect party policies and managing Tibet's temples and
monasteries ``under a socialist mantle.''
   Xinhua also quoted Hu as urging Tibetans to honor the Panchen
Lama's appeals and ``strive for a united, prosperous and culturally
advanced new Tibet.''
   The Panchen Lama, who ranked second in Tibetan Buddhism after the
Dalai Lama, consistently supported Chinese rule in Tibet.
   By contrast, the Dalai Lama, who fled to India in 1959 after an
abortive Tibetan uprising against Chinese rule, has harshly
criticized Chinese repression and demanded freedom for his people.
The Chinese communists occupied the fabled mountain land in 1950 as
they consolidated national control after their revolution.
   The Panchen Lama, who was educated by communists from age 11,
criticized separatists without mentioning the Dalai Lama by name. He
denounced monks and lay Tibetans who held repeated anti-Chinese
protests in Lhasa over the past year and a half. Three of those
protests ended in violent clashes.
   However, the Panchen Lama spoke out against harsh treatment of
Tibetans and urged the government to promote Tibetans with talent,
``not simply lackeys.''
   The official media has given heavy coverage to his death,
recalling his support for Chinese rule in Tibet.
   Officials have refused to disclose funeral plans. It was not
clear if Friday's ceremonies in Tibet were meant to serve that
purpose.
   A ceremony is again likely when the body is placed in his shrine,
which will take months to build.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
