<DOCNO> AP890203-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MeatInspection     02-03 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meat Inspection,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups Urge More Public Review of Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two consumer watchdog groups said Friday the
Agriculture Department should allow more public review of a proposal
to overhaul federal inspection at meat and poultry processing plants.
   The Government Accountability Project and the Community Nutrition
Institute said in a statement filed with USDA's Food Safety and
Inspection Service that the changes should have an adequate
scientific basis and that ``swift and meaningful penalties'' should
be imposed on processors who violate the rules.
   USDA issued the proposal last November to carry out a 1986 law
that would get tougher on inspections of the most troublesome
processing plants but ease up on those with good records.
   The agency estimated that over time its inspection force would be
reduced by half by retirements and resignations. The program would
rely increasingly on ``good'' plants policing themselves.
   But the two organizations said the proposed rules fail meet the
1986 law's requirements and are ``unacceptably general and vague to
the point where they only propose a structure for relaxing
inspection, but not intensifying it where needed.''
   Also, they charged, the agency's own evaluation of pilot projects
using the proposed system showed serious deficiencies.
   ``The regulations were developed and drafted with no consultation
with consumer or other public interest groups or inspectors'' the
statement said.
   As proposed, the new rule would apply to plants that make
frankfurters, beef stew, chicken soup, luncheon meats and scores of
other processed items that include meat and poultry. The proposed
rule would not apply to slaughter plants, which would remain under
continuous federal inspection.
</TEXT>
