<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0619 02-03 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>^Woman Says When Mother Turns on News, `I Go to My Room and Lock
Door'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates in top 12 grafs with 32 panelists in, 13 to go, hearing
finished for week, picking up in 4th graf pvs, Those chosen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After four days of questioning prospective
jurors, the judge and lawyers in Oliver North's Iran-Contra trial
are learning that even in this news hub there are people who don't
give a darn about what's happening.
   By the end of Friday's session, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell had declared 24 women and eight men ignorant enough of
North's 1987 congressional testimony to earn them a shot at being on
the jury. Twenty didn't pass that muster.
   Gesell had wanted a panel of 50 from which the jury of 12 and six
alternates will be chosen, maybe next week. But Friday, he reduced
that target to 45. The panel will consist only of those who persuade
the judge and lawyers they did not watch North on television, hear
him on the radio or read about him in newspapers and magazines.
   ``Have you heard of Colonel North?'' Gesell asked a nurse's
assistant. ``No,'' she said.
   ``Have you read of Colonel North?'' he asked.
   She said, no, she only read her horoscope.
   ``Does `the Iran-Contra matter' carry any meaning for you?''
   No, she said.
   But Gesell dismissed the woman when she said she could not find
the defendant guilty because ``I wasn't there.''
   A supervisor of banquet cleanup at a posh White House-area hotel
said ``I'm the type of person who, once the news comes on, I switch
it off.'' And when she was asked if she heard North testify on
television, she said, ``with due respect to Colonel North, I found
the conversation boring and walked away.''
   To that, North lawyer Brendan Sullivan responded: ``He doesn't
mind at all.''
   North, at the defense table, smiled.
   Those chosen Friday included a woman who said she doesn't pay
attention to news because it is ``depressing.''
   ``I don't like the news,'' she said. And when her mother, who
does, turns it on, she said, ``I go to my room and lock my door.''
   Sullivan pressed her for her recollections of the six days in
which North testified before the Iran-Contra investigative
committees. At those joint hearings in the summer of 1987, the
former Marine lieutenant colonel detailed many of the activities
that are now charged to him as crimes.
   ``He was on TV all day long, on all morning, all afternoon and
rerun at night,'' Sullivan said.
   ``It made me mad, he was on all the channels,'' the woman said.
``I did not look at it at all. ... My mother probably did. I call
her the `news media,''' she said.
   One woman who publishes newsletters and the like said she was
trying to get her business going at that time and ``by the time the
day was over and the news came on I was out walking my dog.''
   But she did know that North had a blonde secretary, Fawn Hall, a
boss named (John) Poindexter, that he was a God-fearing man and that
he had something to do with money and arms on an international scale.
   ``I know people either are for him or against him,'' said the
woman whose office is on Capitol Hill. She was excused.
   A female military personnel clerk at the Pentagon qualified after
testifying ``I hate bad news.'' A legal secretary in the Federal
Trade Commission didn't qualify because she saw the first few
minutes of North's testimony before changing the channel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-TV     02-03 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-TV,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rupert Murdoch Takes Plunge In English Channels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Satellite television beams its way to Britain on
Sunday with much fanfare but few viewers.
   When media magnate Rupert Murdoch launches his four-channel Sky
Television network, the number of channels available to most Britons
will instantly double.
   But the equipment needed to receive the satellite signals in
British homes is in short supply and will be for several more weeks,
if not months.
   Only 5,000 to 20,000 homes will be equipped to tune in on Sunday,
giving just a fraction of the 56 million Britons a chance to watch
the 6 p.m. premiere.
   Watching television is Britain's most popular leisure activity,
even with only four regular channels: two commercial and two run by
the state-funded British Broadcasting Corp.
   Direct satellite-to-home television has been hailed as a
revolution in British broadcasting, and the beginning of a new
skirmish between Britain's two biggest newspaper publishers, who
both are trying to crack the satellite market.
   ``Time Out,'' the weekly guide to what's happening in London, has
billed it ``the biggest aerial dogfight since the Battle of
Britain'' and ``a no-holds barred Star Wars.''
   Critics, praising the high-quality shows now produced in Britain,
already have turned up their noses at Murdoch's programming, which
will rely heavily on imported American soap operas, situation
comedies and game shows.
   Michael Grade, chief executive of the highbrow commercial Channel
4, called it ``junk, fast-food takeaway telly.''
   Sky Television will be vying with a consortium involving rival
publisher Robert Maxwell, and a third international consortium,
British Satellite Broadcasting (BSB).
   Murdoch has managed to get Sky on the air seven months before
BSB's target date.
   He's using the Astra satellite, owned by a Luxembourg-based group
and put into orbit in December.
   BSB was awarded three of the five channels on another satellite
under international treaty. That satellite isn't scheduled to be
launched until August and programming is not expected until
September.
   Maxwell's two channels, Screen Sport and Lifestyle, also will be
bounced off the Astra satellite as soon as contractual snags are
ironed out, said spokesman Chris Howland. Maxwell's two channels and
one of Murdoch's now are available only to British cable subscribers.
   Cable subscribers have more channels than the regular four, but
very fewer Britons have cable. It is available in only three of
London's 32 boroughs, plus a handful of other cities. The Cable
Television Association says there are 265,645 subscribers.
   Sky Television and BSB will use incompatible technologies, so
those wanting to subscribe to both must buy two receiving dishes and
descramblers.
   Sky Television says it hopes its head start will persuade
television fans to buy its technology.
   All four Sky Television channels _ news, movies, light
entertainment and sports _ will initially be offered free.
   This summer, just before the BSB launch, Sky Television will add
the Disney Channel and an arts channel which, along with the movie
channel, will arrive scrambled. For a monthly subscription fee,
viewers will then receive a small credit card to plug into a
receiving box and decode the signal.
   Eurosport will kick off Sunday with Davis Cup tennis; Sky Channel
_ the light entertainment channel now available on cable _ with a
30-minute documentary on the birth of Sky Television; and Sky Movies
with ``Project X.''
   Sky News, Britain's first 24-hour news station, will premiere
with a newscast. The station will be heavily peppered with American
accents, receiving ``NBC Today'' 30 minutes after its broadcast in
New York, and ``NBC Nightly News'' simultaneously. It will also have
access to material from CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes'' and ``57th Street.''
</TEXT>
