<DOCNO> AP890203-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChristicSuit     02-03 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christic Suit,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blasts Contra Conspiracy Suit, Awards Defendants $1 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday criticized a
guns-for-drugs conspiracy lawsuit against Contra and ex-CIA figures,
calling it an abuse of the legal system and awarding the defendants
$1 million in fees and costs.
   Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King last June threw out
the $24 million lawsuit filed by the Christic Institute on behalf of
journalists Tony Avirgan and Martha Honey.
   On Friday, King issued a follow-up ruling requiring the
plaintiffs to pay the defendants $955,000 in attorney fees plus
$79,500 in court costs.
   Some of the 29 defendants _ who include Contra rebel leader
Adolfo Calero, ex-CIA deputy chief of operations Theodore Shackley,
Iran-Contra figures Albert Hakim and Richard Secord, conservative
activist former Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub and others _ promised
action against the liberal, Washington-based Christic Institute.
   ``This is the signal to begin the counterattack,'' Singlaub said
of King's action. ``I think this will put a damper on this kind of
courthouse terrorism against those who are fighting against the
radical left.''
   Singlaub said his attorneys would act quickly against the
Christics to seize any assets to fulfill the judgment.
   Avirgan and Honey filed the suit in May 1986, before many of the
revelations about the Iran-Contra affair. It grew from a 1984
bombing in Nicaragua apparently aimed at Contra leader Eden Pastora.
He escaped, but Avirgan was injured and eight people, including
three journalists, were killed.
   The suit accused the defendants of setting up the bombing, as
well as working with drug traffickers in a 30-year right-wing
conspiracy that included anti-communist activities in Southeast
Asia, Central America and other locations.
   In Washington, Shackley said he will ``try to keep the spotlight
of public scrutiny'' on the group and intends to continue his
campaign to drive the Christics out of business.
   The Christic Institute bitterly criticized the ruling by King,
noting that their appeal of his decision last June was still before
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. They also are
appealing Friday's ruling, seeking an immediate stay.
   ``Judge King's decision was a legal disgrace,'' said Christic
attorney Daniel Sheehan, who assembled much of the case. ``His
ruling will only strengthen our position in the appeals court that
Judge King is committing a consistent pattern of legal error.''
   Sheehan noted that while King criticized the suit as having no
legal merit, three of the defendants _ Hakim, Secord and Civilian
Materiel Assistance head Thomas Posey _ are under federal indictment
on related charges. Another defendant, John Hull, has been arrested
by Costa Rican authorities on drug- and gun-running charges.
   ``The Christic Institute's allegations ... were based on
unsubstantiated rumor and speculation from unidentified sources with
no first-hand knowledge,'' King said in the ruling.
   Theodore Klein, an attorney for three of the defendants, said the
case could now be ``consigned to the oblivion it richly deserves.''
   Asked what he planned to do with his share of the money, Klein
joked: ``Buy guns for the Contras.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
