<FIRST>r a AM-MardiGras     02-03 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mardi Gras,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cop Says Chill Won't Dampen Spirits, But May Cause People To Drink
Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Balmy southern breezes gave way Friday to
frigid north wind, but raucous Mardi Gras revelry continued building
to a fever pitch, including preparations for the nearly nude French
Quarter fashion show.
   With Mardi Gras less than five days away, maskers made ready to
roll on the elaborate floats of 40 metropolitan parades.
   Assistant Police Chief Ray Holman said the freezing temperatures
predicted for the weekend were unlikely to stop the fun.
   ``Snow, sleet, ice, or 80 mile an hour winds. Those are the only
things that would stop a parade,'' said Holman. ``Cold weather
doesn't dampen many spirits, but it may cause people to drink more
of them.''
   Each year on Mardi Gras, Wood Enterprises sponsors ``The Bourbon
Street Awards,'' a costume contest in which many of the participants
are male cross-dressers _ or undressers.
   Kenneth French of Wood Enterprises said hundreds of people turn
out each year in everything from elaborate creations of beads and
feathers to barely legal outfits. Thousands more are there to watch
and he doesn't expect this year to be any different, in spite of the
weather.
   ``People work all year on their costumes. They aren't about to
cover it up or not wear it just because it gets cold,'' he said.
   Holman agreed that the chill probably won't do much to tone down
the French Quarter celebration or cover up the celebrants.
   ``Mardi Gras day even if it's 30 degrees as predicted, you'll see
people, not nude, but pretty close to it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
