<FIRST>r w AM-Lujan-Drilling     02-03 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lujan-Drilling,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Says Interior Still Backs Alaska Refuge Oil Exploration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Department plans to stick with its
recommendation that a vast wildlife refuge in northeastern Alaska be
opened for gas and oil exploration, Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan
Jr., said Friday.
   Environmentalists have said the Bush administration's actions on
development of the 1.5 million acre coastal stretch of the Alaska
National Wildlife Refuge will be a test of the administration's
intentions toward environmental issues.
   Asked about the Alaska refuge during his first news conference
after being sworn in as interior secretary earlier in the day, Lujan
replied that President Bush ``has said we should explore (the
refuge) in an environmentally acceptable manner'' and the question
``is out of my domain.''
   Congress must approve any such oil exploration, and legislation
has been introduced in both the Senate and House that would open the
refuge for drilling. But other legislation also has been introduced
that would make the refuge a wilderness area protected from
exploration.
   The oil industry for years has been pushing for access to the
refuge's northern coastal plain where there are indications of large
oil and gas deposits.
   In the final days of the Reagan administration, outgoing Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel sent a recommendation to Congress endorsing
development. Earlier, Interior had sent Congress a formal assessment
that drilling would not cause undue harm to the environment.
   A dozen environmental groups, including some of the country's
largest, last month urged in letters to Bush and Lujan that Interior
review its findings, contending the conclusions were based on
incomplete or false research.
   Lujan told reporters Friday he was not aware of the petition from
the environmental groups and said of Interior's earlier
recommendation to Congress, ``I don't think I can pull it back.''
   He said that Bush has made it clear he favors oil and gas
exploration as long as it is acceptable environmentally. Lujan
declined to suggest how the refuge might be opened for exploration
and suggested he favors approaching that slowly.
   ``Should we open (the refuge) up in an environmentally acceptable
manner? That decision has been made,'' he said, alluding to the
president's previously proclaimed position. He emphasized that no
development in the refuge can proceed without congressional action.
   Environmentalists and conservationists including the Sierra Club
and the Wilderness Society have vowed to fight any drilling in the
refuge, which is home for the Porcupine caribou, polar bears and
millions of birds.
   On other subjects during his news conference, Lujan said:
   _ He has recommended abandonment of a proposal suggested by his
predecessor that firefighting on federal lands be paid for partly
from funds that now go to the states from lumber and mineral lease
receipts.
   _ He opposes selling oil shale development rights on public lands
for $2.50 an acre as Interior has proposed, saying that's too little.
   _ He plans in coming days to visit the Trust Territory islands in
the Pacific, over which Interior has jurisdiction, as well as tour a
number of schools run by the Bureau of Indian Affairs in the West.
   _ He intends to develop a strong anti-drug program aimed at
eradicating illegal marijuana growing on public lands, including
increased use of aircraft used by the National Park Service. A
federal court this week ordered a halt to random drug testing of
Interior Department employees.
</TEXT>
