<FIRST>r a AM-ColdTown     02-03 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold Town,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Residents Left Shivering After Gas Line Break</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PADUCAH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The single gas line into this tiny town
broke early Friday, cutting off heat to more than 800 homes and
businesses for most of the day in the coldest weather this winter.
   After an arctic cold front chilled most of the state,
temperatures dipped to below 4 degrees and the 4-inch steel pipe
that delivers natural gas to the town of 2,200 contracted and pulled
apart, said officials of Lone State Gas Co., owner of the pipeline.
   Almost two-thirds of the town's homes and businesses were without
gas for heating, hot water or cooking, and schools were closed for
the day.
   ``Boy, was it cold,'' said Kenny Bragg, a janitor at the Cottle
County Courthouse. ``I don't think I would have made it without my
electric blanket.''
   No injuries were reported either as a result of the break or the
cold, said officials.
   The pipeline broke about 3 a.m. in an isolated area of ranchland,
said LSG regional superintendent Bob Clark.
   Fire Chief Don Dillard sounded a fire alarm about 4:15 a.m. to
warn residents, and he and other volunteers began rounding up
electric space heaters to take to the elderly.
   ``I scared everbody to death blowing the whistle,'' he said.
``But we needed to warn 'em.''
   Space heaters were taken to the Wood Convalescent Home, where 44
people live. Nurses gathered ambulatory residents together in the
hall and draped bedspreads over windows for insulation, said nursing
home director Gwynna Stofel.
   ``Luckily it never got below 68 in here,'' she said. ``We used
hot plates to serve a warm breakfast.''
   The nursing home was the first place in town to have its service
restored, at about 11 a.m. after the break was repaired.
   Gas crews then went to work restoring heat to the homes of the
elderly, said Dillard. Others had to wait until late afternoon and
early evening.
   The cold sparked a run on $14 electric space heaters at West
Texas Utilities Co., said office manager Patsy Walling.
   ``We brought them in from all the offices around and we sold
those so they had to bring more all the way from Abilene,'' she
said, adding that more than 50 had been sold by early afternoon.
   Some people gathered on the town square at the senior citizens'
center, which has electric heat, stoves and ovens and served a warm
breakfast to about 125 residents, said center director Emma James.
   Restaurant owners Willa and Bill Isbell, lacking gas to fire
their stoves, took food from their steakhouse to feed the hungry and
cold.
   ``Isn't it wonderful how a little town just rises up and pitches
in when something like this happens,'' said Geneva Bragg, who
ventured out in the cold early to unlock the electric-heated Cottle
County courthouse so ``people would have someplace warm to go.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-AfghanAirlift     02-03 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghan Airlift,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Plans Humanitarian Airlift Into Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. airlift will begin flying food and
medical supplies in a few days to Kabul, the besieged capital of
Afghanistan, officials announced Friday.
   Kabul is surrounded by Moslem guerrillas who have attacked supply
convoys as the last Soviet soldiers withdraw from Afghanistan.
Soviet aircraft have been flying in emergency rations of flour and
fuel to relieve severe shortages.
   ``This is one of many actions of Operation Salaam,'' the U.N.
relief campaign for Afghanistan, U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes said.
``It's all in the effort to assist in the reconstruction of
Afghanistan.''
   U.N. officials could not give an exact date for the airlift to
begin. The Kabul airport was closed Monday because of heavy snow.
   Officials at the Geneva U.N. headquarters said by telephone, on
condition of anonymity, that Afghan guerrillas have agreed in
principle not to attack U.N. planes carrying relief supplies to the
2 million residents and refugees of Kabul.
   In return, they said, the United Nations would send more relief
aid into regions the insurgents control.
   Until last week, the guerrillas had threatened to attack U.N.
flights or truck convoys on grounds that providing aid to Kabul
would help the Soviet-sponsored government.
   Insurgent leaders have predicted Kabul and other cities will fall
quickly after the Red Army is gone, without the need for major
guerrilla assaults.
   Moslem guerrillas have fought since a Communist coup 11 years
ago. Soviet soldiers entered the country in December 1979,
increasing in number to an estimated 115,000 by last May 15, when
they began withdrawing under a U.N.-negotiated agreement. All are to
be gone by Feb. 15.
   ``Airlifts have not started, but it is not the only action that
is being taken,'' Ms. Younes said.
   Her comment that the airlift was part of ``an overall action''
tacitly confirmed supplies would be provided to both Kabul and
guerrilla areas. ``There have been contacts all along with all the
parties,'' she said.
   Government forces in Afghanistan generally are confined to the
cities, and insurgents control the countryside.
   Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan, director of Operation Salaam, was
beginning a week of consultations with the insurgents and other
parties to the conflict.
   Operation Salaam, which means ``peace'' in Arabic, plans to spend
more than $1.1 billion over two years in Afghanistan. Its objectives
include clearing the nation of mines, repatriating more than 5
million refugees from neighboring Pakistan and Iran, and reviving
the primarily agricultural economy.
   The Soviet Union has pledged $600 million of the $887.6 million
promised so far. The United States, principal arms supplier to the
guerrillas, pledged $16.7 million.
   Much of the Soviet aid will consist of food, clothing, bedding,
medical supplies and cloth, with no restrictions on where it may be
distributed, the Operation Salaam office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-49ers     02-03 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-49ers,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets With 49ers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush congratulated the San Francisco
49ers on Friday and said they ``rewrote the record books'' with
their Super Bowl victory. In turn he was presented with two
autographed balls and a jogging outfit.
   ``Let me congratulate you also on your victory,'' quarterback Joe
Montana told Bush at a East Room reception. Montana said being
invited to the White House ``means a lot to all of us'' and joked:
``Not very often do I get to see these guys in ties.''
   Bush, surrounded by 49ers, told the team, ``With this, your third
Super Bowl title in eight years, you rewrote the record books and
raised the game of football to a new level of excellence.''
   And, to Montana, who drove the team to the winning touchdown on a
92-yard drive late in the fourth quarter, Bush said: ``Joe, you once
again showed your grace under pressure. I guess we all wonder why it
took so long.''
   Bush was presented autographed balls by both Montana and wide
receiver Jerry Rice, who won the game's Most Valuable Player award.
   ``That's the real thing from the Super Bowl,'' Rice said of the
ball he gave the president.
   Bush joked that he heard, ``there is a new TV series coming out
based on your Super Bowl performance _ Miami Rice. Available in
every city in the country except one. Cininnnati, that is.''
   The 49ers beat the Cincinnati Bengals, 20-16, two weeks ago in
Miami.
   Team owner Danny DeBartolo told Bush that he would be presented
with a Super Bowl ring, size 11, ``because we want to make you an
honorary member of our team.''
   And outgoing coach Bill Walsh gave Bush a 49ers jogging outfit,
but cautioned, ``I'm not sure we suggest running in the streets of
Washington, D.C., in this suit....Remember the Redskin fans are all
around us.''
   Super Bowl winners are traditionally invited to the White House.
</TEXT>
