<FIRST>r w AM-Nixon-PayRaise     02-03 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon-Pay Raise,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide Says Nixon Would Use Extra Pension Money to Pay for Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a pay raise that would increase pensions of
former presidents becomes law, former President Nixon will use the
additional money to pay for security for himself and his wife, a
spokesman said Friday.
   John H. Taylor, assistant to the former president, wrote on
Nixon's behalf to David Keating, executive vice president of the
National Taxpayers Union, who had written to Nixon urging him to
publicly oppose the pay increase.
   The pay raise proposal, approved by former President Reagan,
calls for increasing the salaries of members of the Cabinet to
$155,000 from $99,500.
   Since a 1971 law links presidential pensions to Cabinet salaries,
the pensions of all former presidents would be increased by the same
amount.
   Keating wrote Nixon on Jan. 17: ``In view of your recent public
statements urging the new administration and the new Congress to
control the federal budget deficit, I hope that you will publicly
issue a statement urging Congress to reject the increase and saying
that you will refuse to accept a 56 percent pension increase.''
   Taylor noted in his reply that former first lady Pat Nixon
relinquished her right to Secret Service protection in 1983 and the
former president did so the following year.
   ``The Nixons are now paying for their own security, an expense of
over $500,000 since 1985,'' he said. ``It is RN's intention to apply
whatever increase may be enacted in his pension entirely toward
defraying the cost of his and Mrs. Nixon's security.''
   Taylor also told Keating that the Richard Nixon Library and
Birthplace, now under construction at Yorba Linda, Calif., would be
the first such facility to be both built and operated without
expenditure of public funds.
   ``In sum, I am sure you will agree that by his decisions
regarding Secret Service protection and private funding for the
operation of his library and birthplace, President Nixon has already
demonstrated extraordinary leadership on the deficit issue,'' Taylor
said.
   The pay raises automatically go into effect unless they are
disapproved by both houses of Congress before Wednesday.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, however, has proposed that the
House vote Thursday on a proposal that would scale the increases
back, both for members of Congress and for Cabinet officers and
other executive branch officials.
   Taylor released the correspondence from Nixon's office in
Woodcliff Lake, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
