<DOCNO> AP890203-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>x w AM-AT&amp;T-PriceCaps     02-03 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T-Price Caps,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Seeks Reasons for Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee on
Friday asked FCC Commissioner Dennis R. Patrick to explain the
``rationale and justification'' for his proposal to change the
two-decades-old system that regulates American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
Co.'s long-distance rates.
   A letter from committee chairman John D. Dingell, D-Mich, and
telecommunications and finance subcommittee chairman Edward J.
Markey, D-Mass., urged Patrick to submit a detailed description of
the plan, which Patrick revised after failing to sell it on Capitol
Hill last year.
   Patrick acknowledged congressional concern about the price cap
proposal last week when he postponed a commission vote on the plan
until March 16.
   ``We are pleased that you have agreed to a procedure that will
permit the public and Congress to review the details of the price
cap plan,'' said the letter, which also was signed by Rep. Norman F.
Lent of New York and Matthew J. Rinaldo of New Jersey, the ranking
Republicans on the committee and subcommittee, respectively.
   It added: ``We also would appreciate your explanation of the
rationale and justification for adopting this price cap plan.''
   FCC spokeswoman Maureen Peratino said the commission would have
no immediate comment on the letter.
   A committee aide who asked that her name not be used said Patrick
would be invited to testify at a Feb. 28 subcommittee hearing.
   Since the early 1960s, the government has allowed AT&amp;T a certain
profit beyond its costs. But the FCC proposed replacing this
so-called rate-of-return regulation for dominant carriers such as
AT&amp;T and the regional Bell companies with ceilings on prices.
   The commission proposed to let AT&amp;T raise rates 3 percent less
than annual inflation _ a move it said would would encourage greater
efficiency and innovation and save customers $1.6 billion over four
years if all the dominant companies participated. AT&amp;T officials
have applauded the plan as being a long-overdue concession to
changing economies in the telephone industry.
   But lawmakers said the plan didn't guarantee that AT&amp;T's rates
would remain in a ``zone of reasonableness.''
   The letter Friday asked Patrick to ``outline how the price cap
plan will benefit residential consumers, business users and rural
telephone subscribers. Please specify both the safeguards proposed
to prevent the dominant carriers from engaging in anti-competitive
practices and assess the role of competition in determining the
applicability of the price cap plan in each segment of the market.''
   It asked for computer models and analyses used to derive the
proposal, including ``any analyses of the impact of price caps on
residential and business consumers, and a comparison of how
consumers would fare under prices caps and under the current
rate-of-return regulation. Please include the origin of the starting
rate that you propose to adopt for each element of service, and the
method of adjustment proposed for each (element).''
</TEXT>
