<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-Unification     02-03 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Unification,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Secret Meetings on Korean Reunification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of North and South
Korea have held secret talks about improving relations and discussed
the possibility of a meeting between their leaders, newspaper
reports said Friday.
   Two days before the reports, an unprecedented trade agreement was
announced between the South Korean conglomerate Hyundai and
communist North Korea. The South Koreans said Friday the agreement
could open the way to reunification after 44 years.
   Seoul newspaper reports quoted a government source, who was not
identified, as saying the secret talks were held abroad and covered
most major issues between the rival Koreas.
   They said the most recent meetings were in Singapore during the
past week between Park Chul-un, a special secretary to President Roh
Tae-woo, and a senior North Korean official who was not identified.
   Park met with the North Korean several times to discuss major
issues, including a proposed summit, the reports said. The
government source was quoted as saying the summit could be held this
year.
   Last month, Roh renewed a proposal that he and North Korean
leader Kim Il Sung discuss the future of the Korean peninsula, which
was divided in 1945.
   The reported talks coincided with the historic visit to North
Korea of a leading South Korean industrialist to discuss direct
investment and joint venture projects.
   Chung Ju-yung, founder and honorary chairman of Hyundai, was in
North Korea from Jan. 23 to Feb. 1 as a guest of the communist
government.
   He said Thursday he had agreed with North Korean officials to
undertake several joint ventures in the North, including a shipyard,
railroad plant and tourist resort.
   Newspapers quoted unidentified government officials as saying
tours would be available later this year to the resort area, a
rugged scenic region 20 miles north of the eastern boundary of the
demilitarized zone that divides the peninsula.
   Roh's government said it would propose special legislation to
facilitate the projects.
   Contact with North Korea is a violation of South Korea's national
security laws. The two nations are technically still at war because
no peace treaty was signed when the three-year Korean war ended 1953.
   In a statement Friday, the government said it ``in principle
takes a favorable view of the proposed projects, regarding them as
possible pilot projects that could contribute to efforts to achieve
national unification.''
   Chung was believed to be the first South Korean business leader
approved by both governments to visit the North.
   North Korea's participation in the deal is seen as an attempt to
revive its economy. It is reported to owe $5 billion to Soviet bloc
and Western nations.
   Figures published Friday and attributed to the South Korean
government said North Korea had a trade deficit of $720 million in
1987. Exports were given as $1.67 billion and imports as $2.39
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
