<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     02-03 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Meets Without Botha; No New Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament opened on Friday
without President P.W. Botha, but his temporary replacement echoed
the ailing leader's commitment to segregation and cautious social
reforms.
   Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis, appointed
acting president after Botha suffered a stroke Jan. 18, promised
``full civil rights for all South Africans'' in a speech to
lawmakers. But he said racial segregation laws would remain in place
and announced no major new initiatives.
   Heunis also reiterated the government's call for political
negotiations with black leaders, although virtually all prominent
blacks have refused to talk without signs of additional race reforms.
   Zach de Beer, leader of the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal
Party, said afterward that Heunis ``merely repeated platitudes and
generalities offered in the past.'' Another liberal leader, Denis
Worrall, said Heunis should have condemned a recent series of racist
incidents nationwide.
   The opening ceremony took place one day after Botha announced he
was resigning as leader of the long-governing National Party.
   Education Minister F.W. de Klerk was elected as the new party
leader by a 69-61 vote, defeating a slightly more liberal candidate.
   Botha is recuperating at his home in Cape Town from a stroke that
weakened his left arm and left leg. Doctors said he has recovered
rapidly and is taking daily walks but needs at least one more month
of rest before returning to work.
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe said Friday that Botha
is not taking part in daily management of government while he
recuperates.
</TEXT>
