<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LockheedFraud     02-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lockheed Fraud,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Dept Won't Join Lockheed Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department declined Friday to
intervene in a suit charging that Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Co.
billed the Pentagon for more than $10 million in fraudulent charges.
   The department's decision not to intervene in the case at this
point indicated it had legal reservations about the complaint by
current and former workers at the company's Sunnyvale, Calif.,
aerospace plant.
   The complaint, filed last year in federal court in San Jose,
Calif., alleged that employees, among other things, charged the
government for using computers to operate private businesses while
awaiting security clearances and to run a football pool.
   The suit also charged that a senior plant manager had Lockheed
machinists build him a private airplane at government expense.
Employees were also allegedly told to charge their time to contracts
on which they did no work, the complaint said.
   The suit was filed under the False Claims Acts, a Civil War-era
statute that was amended in 1986 to allow whistle-blowers to collect
a percentage of judgments against companies that cheat the
government.
   The Justice Department said it had elected not to join the
lawsuit ``after a review and investigation'' of the case.
   The department added, however, that it would continue to monitor
the case, brought by a former software manager and a technician
currently employed at the plant.
   The statute allows the government to intervene at a later time
``upon a showing of good cause,'' the department noted.
   The plant employs 23,700 workers to develop space craft,
satellite systems and submarine-launched missiles. Lockheed Missles
&amp; Space, a subsidiary of Lockheed Corp., has vigorously denied the
allegations in the complaint.
   But the lawsuit said the Defense Contract Audit Agency
substantiated the allegations made by Margaret Newsham, the former
software manager who was fired in 1984 for allegedly padding her
time card. Copies of the agency's reports were appended to the
lawsuit.
   Ms. Newsham's dismissal is the subject of a separate lawsuit
against the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
