<FIRST>r a AM-DelayedArrest     02-03 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delayed Arrest,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested On Murder Charge 21 Years After Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two decades after a grand jury
charged Bernice Van Heise in the shooting death of her married
boyfriend, the woman pleaded innocent Friday.
   The woman _ who disappeared after the slaying _ was found living
quietly in rural Elburn, married and going by the name Greta
Knickerbocker.
   Mrs. Knickerbocker, 62, was re-indicted Wednesday on charges of
murder and involuntary manslaughter in the Jan. 31, 1968, shooting
death of Eugene Douglas in this prosperous suburb north of Chicago.
   ``She was sad and nervous, it seemed,'' in her court appearance
Friday before Lake County Judge Harry Hartel, said Joe Collina,
chief of investigations for the Lake County state's attorney's
office.
   She was accompanied in court by her husband of 20 years, Conrad
Knickerbocker, Collina said. Bond was set at $100,000, he said,
adding police do not believe Mrs. Knickerbocker is likely to flee.
She remained in jail Friday afternoon.
   Mrs. Knickerbocker was arrested Thursday in St. Charles, west of
Chicago, where ``she was having lunch at a restaurant with her
son,'' he said.
   ``This is a touchy situation,'' Conrad Knickerbocker told the
Chicago Tribune on Thursday. ``We thought it was over years ago.''
He said his wife worked occasionally in part-time retail jobs but
was primarily a homemaker.
   He declined to comment further, and no one answered the phone
Friday at the Knickerbocker home.
   The case was reopened in November, when police received a tip on
Mrs. Van Heise's whereabouts. ``She was found through a friend of
her daughter's,'' Collina said.
   Investigators said Douglas' survivors lobbied hard to have
charges renewed after it was learned where she was that month.
   At the time of the shooting 21 years ago, Mrs. Knickerbocker _
then Mrs. Van Heise _ was a divorcee involved with Douglas, a
married, 49-year-old artist who lived in the north Chicago suburb of
Glenview, Collina said.
   ``Witnesses said Eugene Douglas ... had decided to go back to his
wife and children,'' Collina said. ``He was breaking off the
relationship.''
   The shooting occurred at Mrs. Van Heise's coach-house apartment,
Collina said. She told police at the time that she had been showing
Douglas a gun, and that it fired accidentally when she was handing
it to him.
   ``The physical evidence doesn't support that, according to the
police,'' Collina said.
   Mrs. Van Heise was a suspect just after the shooting, but a judge
at the time rejected a murder charge, ruling there was insufficient
evidence. A grand jury later indicted her on a murder charge, but
she had disappeared, authorities said.
   That indictment was withdrawn about 1975, said Deputy Chief
Robert Boone of the Lake Forest police. He did not know why the
charge was dropped, but said the case had been inactive for many
years.
   The Knickerbockers have lived near Elburn _ about 40 miles west
of Chicago _ since 1976, when they moved from the suburb of Hinsdale.
</TEXT>
