<FIRST>r w AM-US-Somalia 1stLd-Writethru   02-03 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Somalia, 1st Ld-Writethru,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS last graf to show that coup was in 1969 sted 1960.
^Somali Premier Heckled as He Accuses Ethiopia of Arming Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somalia's Prime Minister Mohamed Ali Samantar
was heckled by dissidents Friday as he accused Ethiopia of arming
Somali rebels and promised to free all political prisoners in his
country.
   ``Stop the killing, stop the genocide,'' shouted several Somalis
as Samantar was answering reporters' questions at the National Press
Club. Outside, about 15 protesters shouted ``Samantar is a killer.''
   Samantar, who has met with Vice President Dan Quayle and members
of Congress to respond to accusations of human rights violations,
said Somalia would allow representatives of Amnesty International to
visit and investigate ``without restrictions.''
   The government has ``decided to release all political prisoners
in Somalia without exception, including those interned during the
last year in connection with the troubles in the north,'' Samantar
said.
   Amnesty International issued a report last September saying the
government had executed as many as 1,000 unarmed civilians last year
while trying to put down an insurgency in the northern part of the
country on Africa's eastern coast.
   U.S. officials and congressional aides noted that an Amnesty
visit had been postponed from January to April.
   In response to reports of torture and killings, Congress last
summer froze some $55 million of U.S. aid to the impoverished
African nation. After Somalia freed about 100 political prisoners
recently, there were indications that lawmakers might be willing to
release $17 million of the aid for payment of arrears to the
International Monetary Fund, said congressional sources who spoke
only on condition of anonymity.
   But Samantar's talks this week failed to convince some lawmakers
that his government was making much progress on human rights, the
sources said.
   ``For the time being, it's promises,'' said one source. He said
Somalia is still rejecting a U.S. condition for peace talks between
the government and the rebels.
   Samantar said the rebels were being armed by Ethiopia, in
violation of a 1987 pact between the two countries that ended their
11-year war and stipulated that they would not arm each other's
insurgents.
   Samantar said his government had brought the matter up with
Ethiopia's Marxist leaders and was told they had not authorized such
aid although it may have been approved at a lower level of
government.
   U.S. officials say that although some 200,000 to 300,000 Somalis
had found refuge in Ethiopia from last year's fighting in their
country, there is no evidence to support Somalia's accusations that
Ethiopia is arming the rebels who have been seeking to topple the
government for seven years.
   Samantar denied rebels' claims that his government had received
chemical weapons from Libya, but said the two countries had
normalized their relations in recent years.
   Asked whether Somalia had received shipments of conventional
weapons from Libya to help combat the insurgency, Samantar said:
``It's possible.''
   U.S. officials say they have evidence that Libya sent light
weapons and ammunition to Somalia last summer. But when asked about
this in Congress, Samantar denied any Libyan help, the congressional
sources said.
   Somalia has been ruled by army general Siad Barre since he took
power in a 1969 coup. The country of 5.3 million was originally
allied with the Soviet Union, but switched allegiance to the West in
1977.
</TEXT>
