<FIRST>u w AM-Sullivan-HHS     02-03 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-HHS,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Vice Chair Doubts Sullivan Tried To Buy Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran Georgia county commissioner has told
the FBI he doubts that Health and Human Services Secretary-designate
Louis Sullivan was trying to buy influence when his medical school
put another county commissioner on its payroll.
   Lee J. Roach, vice chairman of the Fulton County Commission, said
Friday the FBI, which is conducting a background investigation on
Sullivan, questioned him about the nominee's connection with
Reginald Eaves, a commissioner who was suspended upon conviction of
extortion last May.
   Roach and other Atlanta public figures interviewed by the FBI say
agents have concentrated on Sullivan's links to Eaves.
   It is this continuing inquiry that prompted the White House
earlier this week to get Congress to indefinitely postpone
Sullivan's confirmation hearing.
   Eaves was paid more than $34,000 over four years as a guest
lecturer at Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta while he
promoted school issues before the commission. Sullivan is president
of Morehouse. Published reports has said Eaves gave only two
lectures.
   Roach dismissed the idea that Sullivan hired Eaves to increase
Morehouse's influence on commission votes.
   ``I was not aware of whether Dr. Sullivan knew or did not know
about Eaves' being hired. I guessed that he did not,'' Roach told
The Associated Press in recounting his interview with FBI agents,
which he said lasted 10-15 minutes.
   Eaves, who knew Sullivan from their undergraduate days at
Morehouse College, was an active supporter of the medical school
which Sullivan founded, but Roach said the rest of the commissioners
also strongly backed the school.
   ``The support for Morehouse was solid. We were committed to do
what we had to do for Morehouse,'' Roach said. ``There was nothing
Eaves could do to make that more solid.''
   Roach said commissioners were unaware Eaves was on the school's
payroll during the four years, but the link between Eaves and the
school became public last July after Eaves was convicted.
   Roach said he did not know how much direct contact Eaves had with
Sullivan.
   ``An old-time seasoned politician might have looked at that and
might have asked, `What's going on?' But Sullivan is not a
politician. He's an administrator,'' Roach said. ``If there's any
sin on Dr. Sullivan's part, it's that he's not a seasoned
politician,'' Roach said.
   Few issues involving Morehouse came before the board, though the
ones that did were important and usually involved large
appropriations to the school, Roach said.
   Earlier, Eaves told the FBI he was unsure whether Sullivan, his
friend and associate, knew he was being paid as a lecturer at the
school and that the nominee had never tried to influence him
improperly, according to Eaves' lawyer, Charles R. Floyd Jr.
   Eaves was questioned by the FBI earlier this week at a federal
prison in Montgomery, Ala., where he is serving a six-year sentence,
Floyd said.
   Eaves was convicted of accepting $35,000 from an FBI undercover
agent in exchange for votes on zoning issues.
   Reached by telephone at the prison Friday, Eaves declined to
discuss his relationship with Sullivan, whom he said he has known
since 1952. He said he is not granting any interviews because his
case is on appeal.
   The FBI has refused to discuss its background investigation.
   On Capitol Hill, the questions about Sullivan's link to Eaves do
not appear to threaten his nomination to head the largest federal
department.
   ``We don't read anything into this at all,'' said a Senate
source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
