<HEAD>Shuttle Discovery Moved to Pad for March Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 14th graf, `Engineers believe' on possible
cause of corrosion being chlorine cleaner not thoroughly wiped off, picks
up 15th graf, `The pumps...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CSB2, KSC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Discovery moved to the
launch pad Friday but it may have to be taken back to a hangar if
technicians on a tight schedule can't replace three engine pumps in
time for a mid-March liftoff.
   The five astronauts who will fly the mission rode partway to the
launch pad with their spaceship, and later swooped low over the pad
in three T-38 jets as they headed back to their training base in
Houston. The shuttle arrived at the pad about 1 p.m.
   Tip Talone, Discovery's processing director, said March 10 is the
earliest possible launch for the planned five-day mission.
   Officials had said earlier that if Discovery could not be
launched by March 18, it would have to yield the pad to Atlantis,
set for liftoff on April 28. But on Friday, NASA officials said they
might extend that March 18 deadline a few days by trimming the
potential number of launch days available to Atlantis.
   Only one shuttle launch pad is currently available while a second
is being refurbished.
   Atlantis has priority over Discovery for use of that launch pad
because it is to send the Magellan probe to Venus. If Atlantis is
not launched April 28 to May 23, Venus will not be in the proper
alignment with Earth for the Magellan project again until 1991. By
contrast, the Discovery flight could be rescheduled relatively
quickly if it has to be postponed.
   ``If we can get (Discovery) out of here in mid-March, we will
protect the Magellan `window,''' Talone said, referring to the
period available for the Atlantis launch. ``We're going to make it.''
   NASA would like to have the entire launch period available for
Atlantis in case problems develop. But it might be willing to
shorten that window slightly if Discovery is nearly ready March 18.
   If Discovery's three suspect turbopumps can't be replaced in
time, its mission with a communications satellite would be put off
until later this year.
   Talone acknowledged there is a lot of work to be done and some
uncertainty about how long the pump replacement will take, because
technicians have never made such a changeout with a shuttle in the
vertical position.
   He said he expects all three of the old pumps to be out by next
Friday. The new units will arrive here the week of Feb. 12 and the
plan is to have all installed and checked out by the end of February.
   ``We don't feel any pressure on this,'' he said.
   After Atlantis flew in December, an inspection of the shuttle's
engines disclosed two tiny cracks in a bearing housing in one of
three high-speed turbopumps that convert liquid oxygen to a gas.
   Engineers believe the cracks were caused by stress corrosion
resulting from moisture trapped inside the housing during the
manufacturing process. Because two of Discovery's turbopumps
underwent the same processing, NASA decided to replace all three
pumps with new, carefully inspected units, and to delay a planned
Feb. 23 launch.
   Shuttle engineers said Friday they think the corrosion resulted
when the trapped moisture mixed with chlorine from a common
household cleaner. They said the cleaning material probably was not
thoroughly wiped off after a scrub-down.
   The pumps are critical because the shuttle could explode if one
failed during liftoff.
   Attached to its two solid fuel booster rockets and external fuel
tank, Discovery moved out of an assembly building into the darkness
at 6 a.m. to begin a four-mile trip that ended seven hours later at
Launch Pad 39B. The transporter, a giant tracked vehicle called a
crawler, traveled at a maximum speed of 1 mph.
   The astronauts rode part of the way on the crawler. They are
commander Michael Coats, John Blaha, James Buchli, Bob Springer and
James Bagian. As they left for Houston, they swung their jets in a
wide circle over Discovery, then about half a mile from the pad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
