<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Ambassador     02-03 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Ambassador,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Envoy Choice Draws Criticism In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders said Friday that the man
who may be the next U.S. ambassador to Mexico helped orchestrate the
civil war in Nicaragua and is a master of meddling in other nations'
affairs.
   Right-wing and leftist groups said relations with Washington
would worsen if President Bush selects John Negroponte as the next
ambassador.
   Sources in Washington said this week that Negroponte, a deputy
national security adviser, will be picked to replace Ambassador
Charles Pilliod.
   When he served as U.S. ambassador to Honduras from 1982 to 1985,
Negroponte had a major role in assisting the U.S.-backed rebels
seeking to overthrow the leftist government in Nicaragua. Honduras
was a major base of operations for the rebels, known as Contras.
   Critics also said Negroponte also sought unduly to influence the
Honduran government.
   The Foreign Ministry said it would not comment publicly on the
selection until it had advised the U.S. government of its views. But
leftist and conservative parties suggested Mexico investigate
allegations about Negroponte and consider rejecting him.
   ``National authorities have the right to keep officials who are
highly discredited and who have violated human rights from assuming
posts in Mexican territory,'' Diego Fernandez, a leader of the
conservative National Action Party, was quoted as saying by the
liberal daily La Jornada on Friday.
   Amalia Garcia of the Mexican Socialist Party, the largest leftist
party, urged the government not to accept the appointment, the
newspaper said.
   She was quoted as saying it ``will make problems more complex and
deepen differences between the two nations.''
   Oscar Mauro Ramirez Ayala, leader of the congressional delegation
of the center-left Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, also
called for a thorough analysis of Negroponte's background, saying,
``according to reports about him, he's an expert in combating the
libertarian forces of the Latin American countries.''
   Jorge Bustamante of the Colegio del Norte, a northern think tank
in Tijuana, said in a television interview on Friday that the choice
was ``bad news for bilateral relations'' and worked against Mexico's
efforts to achieve peace in Central America.
   Mexico opposes U.S. support for the Contras.
   The independent but pro-government daily Excelsior ran a lengthy
front-page story on Thursday describing Negroponte as a diplomat who
``has earned the reputation of being more astute and calculating
than Machiavelli.''
   La Jornada, in a front-page editorial on Thursday, called the
appointment ``an ominous decision'' and began a three-part series
called ``The Path of an Ultra-Hawk.''
   The government newspaper El Nacional said Negroponte ``simply
complied, like a good ambassador, with orders from Washington'' in
the rebel effort.
   Negroponte had a close relationship with Gen. Gustavo Alvarez
Martinez, who was head of the Honduran military from 1982 until his
overthrow in 1984 and for a time was considered for a time the most
powerful figure in the country.
   As head of the national police in 1981, Alvarez told CIA director
William Casey the Nicaraguan rebels could operate from Honduran
territory, allowing the movement to take root.
   Alvarez was assassinated in Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital, in
January. A leftist group claimed responsibility for the killing.
</TEXT>
