<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Cocaine     02-03 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Cocaine,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize 1,500 Pounds Of Cocaine Base in Jungle Gunfight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of narcotics police seized more than
1,500 pounds of partially processed cocaine after a jungle shootout
in which two traffickers were killed and four wounded, officials
reported Friday.
   The U.S. Embassy said U.S. helicopters ferried Peruvian police,
but neither the aircraft nor U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
agents were present during the fight.
   Police said the 1,570 pounds of cocaine base, which can be
refined into an an approximately equal quantity of pure cocaine, was
one of the largest single seizures of the drug in Peru.
   They said the raid took place Thursday at an airfield on the
outskirts of Uchiza in the cocaine-producing Huallaga Valley, about
265 miles northeast of Lima.
   Officials said police moved in while traffickers were loading the
drugs on a plane. They said 15 were arrested after the gunfight, and
no police were injured.
   About 60 percent of the world's coca leaf, the raw material of
cocaine, is grown in Peru. It usually is processed into cocaine base
and flown to Colombia, to be refined and delivered to the United
States and Europe.
   Washington is providing increased support for Peru's
anti-narcotics effort. The embassy said nine helicopters, operated
by U.S. civilian pilots, have been loaned to Peruvian authorities
and more than a dozen DEA agents are stationed in the jungle to
advise and train police.
   U.S. officials say cocaine trafficking generates at least $700
million annually in Peru. Police said the drugs seized Thursday were
worth $14 million locally but several times more when refined and
sold abroad.
</TEXT>
