<FIRST>r w AM-FSLICDirector     02-03 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSLIC Director,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>FSLIC Director Quits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators Friday announced the
resignation of Stuart D. Root, the executive director of the fund
that insures saving and loan deposits.
   Root, appointed to head the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corp. in October 1987, submitted his resignation on Monday. It will
be effective Feb. 10.
   Replacing Root as acting director will be Mary A. Creedon,
currently principal deputy director of operations, according to a
statement released Friday evening by the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, the FSLIC's parent agency.
   The statement said Root, an attorney, would ``return to the
private sector.'' The telephone at Root's office was not answered
Friday evening.
   A bank board official, who declined to be identified, said Root
had decided earlier that he would step down after regulators'
completed their year-end rush to sell insolvent S&amp;Ls before
lucrative tax breaks were halved on Jan. 1.
   The official noted that top FSLIC officials maintained a brutal
work pace, including a 16-hour day on Chistmas. ``He just thought it
was time to go back to the private sector,'' the official said.
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the bank board, praised Root for his
``substantial personal sacrifice'' and ``invaluable service.''
   Root, previously a lawyer at the New York firm of Cadwalader,
Wickersham &amp; Taft, presided over roughly the first half of what will
be the largest government rescue of an industry ever. He had been a
top officer of Bowery Savings Bank in New York from 1981 to 1983.
   Under Root's direction, the FSLIC last year pledged $38 billion
to merge or close 205 insolvent institutions and keep 18 others
afloat. Seventy-five of the resolutions came in a final frenzy
during December. About 350 insolvent institutions remain.
   Creedon has been a bank board career employee since 1973, with
intervening service in what was then the Department of Health,
Education and Welfare and the Department of Commerce. She had
previously served as acting FSLIC director from December 1983 until
March 1987.
   She plans to return to her career position as deputy director
when the bank board finds a permanent FSLIC director, which is a
politically-appointed post, the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
