<FIRST>u i AM-Koreas-Shooting     02-03 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koreas-Shooting,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Claims South Korea Shot Over Demilitarized Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen in South Korea fired at a North Korean
military post in the demilitarized zone and ``committed a grave
military provocation,'' the North Korean Central News Agency
reported Saturday.
   The government-controlled news agency, monitored in Tokyo, said
``some 10 armed bandits'' fired several rounds of machine-gun fire
toward the post on the North Korean side on Friday.
   Radio Pyongyang also reported the alleged incident, saying it
``seriously threatened'' the North Korean security guards on duty,
and destroyed some facilities at the military post.
   ``The South Korean puppets committed a grave military provocation
by firing large-caliber machine-gun bullets at a post of our side in
the DMZ,'' southeast of Mount Sobang in the central part of the DMZ
that divides South Korea from its communist neighbor to the north,
the North Korean news agency said.
   The ``military provocation'' of the South Koreans ``fully shows
that they seek confrontation and war, not detente and dialogue,''
the news agency said.
   The North Korean news agency also reported North Korea seized two
South Korean ships that allegedly trespassed into North Korean
waters northwest of Changsan Cape on Jan. 29.
   The news agency said the alleged intrusion into North Korean
territorial waters was a ``deliberate plot,'' and that North Korea
captured the ships in ``self-defense.''
   South Korea has protested the apprehension of the two ships, and
an investigation of the incident was in progress, the news agency
said.
   It did not say how many crew members were aboard the Taeyang No.
37 and Taeyang No. 39, owned by the Taeyang Fisheries Association in
Inchon, South Korea.
   South Korea and North Korea reportedly have held a series of
secret talks on measures to ease tensions on the Korean peninsula,
including a possible summit meeting.
   The two countries technically remain at war since no peace treaty
was signed at the end of the three-year Korean War in 1953. Each
claims to be the sole legitimate government of Korea.
   The shooting came on the same day the Seoul government announced
that an unprecedented economic agreement between a South Korean
business tycoon and North Korea ``could contribute to efforts to
acheive national unification.''
   The Seoul government Friday said it would propose special
legislation to facilitate the agreement between the nation's largest
business group and a state-run North Korean corporation to jointly
develop a tourist resort, shipyard and railroad plant in the
communist North.
   Chung Ju-Yung, founder and honorary chairman of the giant Hyndai
group, visited North Korea last month to discuss economic
cooperation between the two Koreas.
</TEXT>
