<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Salvador     02-03 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Salvador,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Charge CIA Plot To Link Nicaragua With Salvadoran Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interior Ministry on Friday accused
the CIA and Salvadoran navy officers of plotting to falsely portray
the Nicaraguan government as an arms supplier to leftist Salvadoran
guerrillas.
   Officials said four Nicaraguan criminals were hired to steal
weapons from the Nicaraguan army and smuggle them into El Salvador,
where the arms were to be ``intercepted'' and shown as proof that
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government was aiding the rebels.
   The Nicaraguan government has long denied that it has shipped
weapons to the guerrillas fighting El Salvador's U.S.-backed
government.
   The U.S. Embassy had no immediate comment on the Interior
Ministry charges and no spokesmen were immediately available at the
U.S. Embassy in San Salvador, because of Vice President Dan Quayle's
visit.
   A Salvadoran navy spokesman, Lt. Jose Castellanos, said he knew
nothing about the accusations.
   Oscar Loza, operations chief for Nicaragua's State Security
Agency, said the alleged plot came to light after the four
Nicaraguans were arrested in December and January during an
investigation of a crime streak in Chinandega and Leon, two
provinces close to El Salvador.
   Loza said the men never got a chance to actually steal any
weapons.
   ``This is a group of delinquents used by the CIA and Salvadoran
naval intelligence in subversive acts against Nicaragua,'' Loza
said. ``That's the only type of people they can hire now.''
   Loza spoke at a news conference at the Interior Ministry, which
includes the security agency.
   He said the men were robbery suspects who fled to El Salvador in
November. El Salvador is across the Gulf of Fonseca from Nicaragua,
on the Pacific coast.
   After being arrested in El Salvador, the men allegedly were
approached by CIA agents and Salvadoran officials who offered them
$10,000 and told to return to Nicaragua and steal weapons from a
military installation on Los Castanones, a small island off the
northwestern port of Corinto.
   He said the men also were promised $5,000 for each Redeye
surface-to-air heat-seeking missile they stole and about $200 for
each AK-47 assault rifle.
</TEXT>
