<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay-Mood 1stLd-Writethru   02-03 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Mood, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0763,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stroessner Coup Stirs Joy, Hopes for Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 11th graf, ``I think...' to CORRECT name of paper to ABC
Color.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Paraguay, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some danced, some sang, some merely
gaped at the pools of blood in the street. Thousands cheered the end
of a 34-year-old dictatorship, and others wondered whether a new one
had begun.
   Thousands of people poured out of the homes on Friday, the
morning after the night that Gen. Alfredo Stroessner was overthrown
by his second-in-command, Gen. Andres Rodriguez.
   For many, Stroessner was the only leader they have ever had, a
man who snatched power in a 1954 coup, then lost it more than three
decades later to another military leader.
   But Paraguayans of all ages and political persuasions left their
homes to celebrate, to satisfy curiousity and to simply stare at the
damage left by nearly five hours of heavy fighting between rebels
and loyalist troops.
   An estimated 5,000 people gathered in downtown Asuncion. Two
blocks from the rallying crowd, wreckers towed away bullet-riddled
cars that were caught when rebel tanks and troops attacked police
loyal to Stroessner.
   Five hundred yards away, about 100 troops guarded the gray, 19th
century presidential palace overlooking the Paraguay River where
Stroessner ruled and where Rodriguez was sworn in.
   Two miles from downtown, small groups of citizens gathered in
front of the presidential escort battalion which remained loyal to
Stroessner and was the scene of some of the heaviest fighting
throughout the night.
   The roof of one of the four buildings had collapsed, and there
were gaping holes in the brick walls.
   Caravans of cars, many flying the red, white and blue Paraguayan
flag _ or the crimson banner of the ruling Colorado Party, or the
blue banner of the opposition Liberal Party _ drove through
downtown, horns honking.
   The nation's principal radio stations and their mobile units
carried on a marathon of interviews with politicians and citizens,
many of whom suffered at the hands of the Stroessner regime.
   ``I think that the era of terrorism and corruption that affected
our country for so long has come to an end, thanks to the armed
forces,'' said Aldo Zuccolillo, publisher of ABC Color, the
country's biggest newspaper at the time it was shut down by the
Stroessner government in 1984 for, among other reasons, ``preaching
hatred among Paraguayans.''
   Zuccolillo said he will reopen the paper as soon as he can obtain
printing paper and ink.
   ``I'm happy that this man (Stroessner) is gone for good, but I'm
sad about the dead,'' said a young waitress who spent the night
huddled in a restaurant near the police headquarters. Estimates of
the dead ranged up to 200.
   ``I don't know if we're going too have democracy and liberty now,
but we've taken the first step,'' said Humberto Rubin, owner of
Radio Nanduti, forced to close in 1987 for its criticism of the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
