<FIRST>r p AM-Kirk     02-03 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kirk,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Chief Reportedly Considering Massachusetts Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul G. Kirk Jr., the outgoing Democratic national
party chairman, is considering a run for governor of Massachusetts
next year, two newspapers reported Friday.
   Kirk, who is well known in national political circles but not a
household name in his home state, was described as weighing a run
for governor in stories that appeared on Friday's front pages of The
Boston Globe and The Wall Street Journal.
   Kirk, who has never held elected office, is stepping down next
week as DNC chairman. He was traveling in Hawaii on Friday and could
not be reached.
   In Massachusetts, Democratic professionals said Kirk could be a
formidable candidate.
   The apparently orchestrated effort to float his name as a
contender took some Democratic political veterans by surprise, but
nearly all agreed that he would be a serious candidate.
   ``I'm surprised. My own sense of Paul's decision was he wanted to
return to private life,'' said political pollster and consultant
John Marttila. But he added, ``He's a capable, talented human
being.''
   Kirk, 51, was born in the Boston suburb of Newton and owns a home
in Marston Mills on Cape Cod. He had worked for a Boston law firm
and was expected to return there.
   Kirk, who turned down a chance for another four years as
committee chairman, would be seeking the post of Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis, the former Democratic presidential nominee who has said he
will not seek re-election next year.
   Likely Democratic candidates for governor include Lt. Gov. Evelyn
Murphy and former Massachusetts Attorney General Francis X.
Bellotti. In addition, there is great suspense surrounding the plans
of U.S. Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II.
   Kirk was a longtime aide to Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and
served as political director in the senator's 1980 presidential
race. According to Marttila and others, it is highly unlikely that
Kirk would enter a Democratic primary for governor if the race
included Joseph Kennedy, the senator's nephew.
   The younger Kennedy has topped the list of preliminary polls of
likely candidates for governor, but he has not revealed his plans.
</TEXT>
