<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-GreatEscape ADV07   02-03 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Great Escape, ADV 07,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, Feb. 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Great Escape' Offers Video Travel Around World</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The syndicated travel show ``The Great
Escape'' takes you to wonderful places around the world, but co-host
Bob Chandler admits that everything is not quite what it seems.
   ``This show is geared for the consumer,'' said Chandler, a former
pro football player who is co-host with Michelle Russell. ``We don't
offer vicarious travel, like `The Lifestyles of the Rich and
Famous.' We occasionally do an upscale place, but mostly we tell
people about places they can afford to visit. A part of any
successful show is knowing what your direction is. Our direction is
to go to places that are easily accessible and that are good.''
   So, you will rarely hear a discouraging word.
   ``We don't go out of our way tosay something is bad or to be
critical,'' said Chandler. ``If we run into a situation we don't
like, we'll handle it by omission. We're not selling out, and it's
not because we're afraid of losing our tradeoff. It's just that our
goal is that we're looking only for the great places to visit.
   ``We get tradeoffs in the form of free travel and accommodations.
We're up-front about that. We've got two hosts and four camera crews
going all over the world and it's the only way we could afford it.''
   It's common practice for television shows to accept free travel
and accommodations, but federal regulations require that such
arrangements be acknowledged on the air.
   Each weekly half-hour show visits three places: a feature
destination that's usually foreign, a Discover America segment and a
weekend escape.
   Chandler has spent a large part of the past few years on the
road. First as co-host of ``Two on the Town,'' a magazine show for
KCBS-TV in Los Angeles, and for ``The Great Escape.''
   He had been a been a sportscaster after his football career. He
was a wide receiver for the Buffalo Bills and played in Super Bowl
XV for the Oakland Raiders. He earned a law degree while playing
professional football.
   ``For this show we're on the road 10 to 15 days, then we're home
for about the same time,'' he said. ``It's tough to complain about
this job. People say, `You kidding? You get to travel everywhere.'
They don't see us packing 18 trunks of equipment, checking into a
different hotel every night. I was out once last year for 27 days.
We were in seven different locations.''
   Chandler said ``The Great Escape'' uses only original footage,
taped around the world. The only exception was one minute of the
Follies Bergere at Las Vegas.
   ``We get offered a lot of footage,'' said Chandler, ``but one of
our strengths is our cameramen. We have four crews and they
frequently work without a host or correspondent. Besides Michelle
and myself, we have used correspondents in Australia and Europe.''
   Chandler and Russell go to different places so they can cover
more places.
   ``I've been just about everywhere,'' he said, ``but when we start
traveling again in March I hope we go to the Orient. The funny thing
is, before this I'd only been out of the United States once.
   ``The great thing is you learn a lot about the areas. You have to
do research. And when you get there you get involved with the
people. You get to see a lot more than tourists do.
   ``I do have some favorite places,'' he said. ``The Northern
Island of New Zealand, at the Huka Lodge. It's like an old-fashioned
hunting club. There's a wonderful lake for trout fishing and you can
go skiing only a few hours away. I also love the eastern coast of
Australia, from Sydney to the Great Barrier Reef. The third place is
the South of France, from the Burgundy region and the Loire Valley
to the Mediterranean.''
   Where does Chandler go on vacations? ``I usually stay home,'' he
said. He has two children and he and his wife, Marilyn, are
expecting another child.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BOYS WILL BE BOYS _ The Showtime cable channel has ordered eight
episodes of ``The Boys,'' a new comedy series starring Norm Crosby,
Norman Fell, Jackie Gayle, Michael Lerner and Lionel Stander. They
portray members of a fading New York City men's club. The show will
go into production in May for a summer premiere. ...
   PASSES GO _ Merv Griffin has agreed to develop and produce a
television game show based on the popular board game ``Monopoly.''
The agreement is with King World Productions, which also distributes
``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy!'' for Griffin. ``Monopoly''
will be produced for ABC and for syndication.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, Feb. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
