<DOCNO> AP890203-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-S&amp;LCrisis-Sharks Adv06   02-03 1071</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-S&amp;L Crisis-Sharks, Adv06,1101</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Feb. 6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Money Sharpies Take Control of S&amp;L Flops</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting to change cycle designator to BC.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When George Bailey's savings and loan verged on
collapse, it escaped a conniving financier's takeover plot with help
from depositors who donated cash to help the thrift account for
thousands of missing dollars.
   That happens only in the movies.
   The script from the 1940s Hollywood classic ``It's A Wonderful
Life,'' starring Jimmy Stewart as the virtuous smalltown banker,
would have to be revamped today to dramatize the frightening world
of failing thrifts.
   While Washington may eventually require depositors or taxpayers
to help rescue the country's most beleaguered savings institutions,
few George Baileys have emerged to rally the little people.
   Instead, the government has embraced some of Wall Street's
biggest dealmakers _ people known for multibillion-dollar buyouts
and takeovers, not low-risk lending and Christmas clubs.
   They include such names as Texas tycoon Robert M. Bass and Revlon
Group Inc. Chairman Ronald O. Perelman, both ranked among Forbes
magazine's richest 400 Americans.
   In exchange for passing off the rescue effort to these
financiers, the government has offered them guarantees against
losses and in some cases magnanimous tax benefits. But the tradeoff
is raising questions about the buyers' motives and their impact on
the industry's long-term survival.
   ``It's very unclear whether many of these investors want to be in
the S&amp;L business on an on-going basis,'' said John J. Kriz, a thrift
and banking analyst at Moody's Investors Service. ``A number of
them, no doubt, have exit strategies which call for flipping the
businesses to others.''
   Critics of the bailouts have implied that the low-paid
bureaucrats who rushed to seal many of these deals at the end of
1988 were no match for the shrewd investors who entered bids.
   Some of those critics now worry that sickly thrifts could be used
by their new owners as government-backed vehicles to engage in the
kind of business adventurism that originally sucked the institutions
into insolvency.
   Others believe the buyers simply saw short-term opportunities to
exploit the grandiose tax benefits, which in some cases are worth
more than the government's sale price of an institution.
   John Buchanan, a First Boston Corp. thrift analyst and former
chief of staff at the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the government's
S&amp;L regulator, said takeover artists look at failed S&amp;Ls ``as an
opportunity to make money, quite frankly. Given the nature of the
transactions they struck, I'm certain they're not going to do it for
free.''
   By far the two deals that best symbolize these concerns were the
board's biggest sale, the American Savings &amp; Loan Association of
Stockton, Calif., to a group run by Bass; and the sale of five
bankrupt Texas thrifts to a concern run by Perelman.
   In the American Savings arrangement, the Bass group is putting up
$500 million, receiving $1.7 billion in government aid and obtaining
control of a vast network of assets worth more than $30 billion.
   Perelman's group is putting up $315 million and getting $5.1
billion of government aid in exchange for savings units with assets
of more than $12 billion.
   Bass, 40, is one of four Texas billionaire brothers, known as
``the boys,'' in their hometown Fort Worth, who control an empire of
businesses that include oil wells, real estate and stocks.
   Over the last few years, Bass has dabbled in broadcasting and
publishing, with strategic investments in Taft Broadcasting Co.,
Macmillan Inc. and, most recently, Houghton Mifflin Co.
   Perelman, 45, is known as a ruthless negotiator and Manhattan
party-circuit celebrity, whose sprawling MacAndrews &amp; Forbes
Holdings Inc. has interests ranging from jewelry to licorice extract.
   By far Perelman's most flamboyant acquisition has been Revlon,
the cosmetics maker. He's also made unsuccessful, but lucrative,
runs at Gillette Co., the men's toiletry maker.
   Both men rarely grant interviews and have said little about their
reasons for buying S&amp;Ls, an area in which they've had no experience.
   But the financiers have hired highly respected, conservative
thrift managers to run the businesses, an outward indication they
want them to pursue the historic strength of the thrift industry:
low-risk home mortgages.
   That would be a welcome change from the ambitious commercial real
estate lending and generous rates of interest on deposits offered by
hundreds of now-insolvent thrifts, primarily in the Southwest, that
resulted from deregulation in the early 1980s.
   Perelman and his aides declined to respond to three telephone
requests for comment. Bass likewise failed to respond to requests,
but people familiar with his S&amp;L venture said Bass was in it for the
long term.
   The Bass negotiations weren't without controversy. In September
he proposed creating a thrift subsidiary that would use $1.5 billion
in assets to engage in merchant banking activities such as
takeovers. The proposal created such a stir it was hastily scrapped
and the merchant banking plans were scaled way back at the behest of
government regulators.
   The Bass and Perelman deals differ in a number of key ways; those
differences may determine how well the two S&amp;L ventures perform and
how long they survive. For one thing, Bass will get relatively few
tax advantages, while Perelman can apply previous losses from the
thrifts as tax deductions for his other businesses.
   Those deductions are considered so valuable that a rival takeover
strategist, Saul Steinberg, sued the government and Perelman,
claiming his offer for the same S&amp;Ls was unfairly rejected from
consideration.
   On the other hand, some analysts have said, Bass's acquisition
has a greater chance of success over the long haul, partly because
of government-imposed restrictions on the types of investments it
can make.
   American Savings' 187 branches also provide a well-established
lending network, and the government itself has a 30 percent
profit-participation interest.
   ``American Savings is somewhat tarnished but it's not a bad one.
Assuming the deal holds together from the government end, Bass
should do fairly well,'' said Bert Ely, a thrift industry consultant.
   Ely dismissed much of the criticism leveled at the financiers who
have purchased thrifts, saying any blame must be shared by
regulators and Congress.
   ``We can beat up on the Perelmans of the world; these guys are
getting rich, and maybe they are, but only because a federal agency
went into these deals and did them the way they did,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Feb. 6</NOTE>
