<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w BC-S&amp;LCrisis-Players Adv05   02-03 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-S&amp;L Crisis-Players, Adv05,0860</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release, Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>You Need A Scorecard to Follow the Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While a dozen congressional committees grope
publicly for ways to raise an estimated $85 billion to end the
savings and loan crisis, the most important decisions will likely be
made by a handful of players far from the television lights.
   Foremost, according to others involved in the process, are likely
to be President Bush himself; Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., and
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   Rostenkowski and Bentsen chair, respectively, the tax-writing
House Ways and Means Committee and the Senate Finance Committee.
These two men will be Capitol Hill's brokers with the Bush White
House on who will pay for the cleanup of the ailing industry.
   ``We'll hold our hearings and other committees will hold theirs,
but Ways and Means will grab it in the end,'' says Rep. Henry
Gonzalez, D-Texas, who heads the House Banking Committee. That
panel, along with the Senate Banking Committee, chaired by Sen.
Donald Riegle, D-Mich., have jurisdiction over the savings and loan
industry.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady already is Bush's point man in
the dealings with Congress, requesting weekly meetings with the four
committee chairmen, the senior Republicans on those panels and the
speaker of the House, Jim Wright.
   Brady's credibility was badly damaged in floating one of the
major ingredients of the rescue package as a ``user fee'' on bank
and S&amp;L depositors instead of as higher federal insurance premiums
on the institutions themselves.
   One source close to the back-and-forth floating of ideas said
Rostenkowski expects to bargain any compromise directly with Bush,
who as a Texas congressman two decades ago served on the Ways and
Means panel with Rostenkowski.
   The Illinois Democrat, after meeting with Brady, Gonzalez and
Wright recently, described Brady's proposed 25-cent user fee on each
$100 of deposit as ``flat as a pancake.'' He said he is concerned
that whatever agreement is reached, the administration will say it
was Congress' doing.
   Briefly, here are sketches of some of the central figures in
resolving the S&amp;L crisis:
   _M. Danny Wall, the chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
who said when he took the job 18 months ago that he was confident of
resolving the industry's problems. Now he has lost the confidence of
key House Republicans because of the manner in which the bank board
rescued 75 institutions in December at a cost of nearly $20 billion
to the government over the next decade.
   _L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., the relatively flush fund that insures deposits in commercial
banks carrying an FDIC sticker on their windows. He supports the
separation of the Federal Savings and Loans Insurance Corp. from the
bank board and opposes charging banks higher insurance fees to raise
money to resolve the S&amp;L problems. Some industry and government
officials say Siedman wants to take over the government's deposit
insurance programs covering savings and loans and credit unions as
well as banks.
   _Wright, criticized by Wall's predecessor, Edwin Gray, for
intervening in 1986 on behalf of savings and loan institutions in
his home state. It was that action, Gray says, that delayed for
nearly two years legislation that gave FSLIC an infusion of $10.8
billion in new money to close insolvent S&amp;Ls.
   Wright contends he was seeking only a hearing on behalf of his
constituents. His intervention is one of six allegations of
wrongdoing under investigation by the House Ethics Committee.
   _Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, a former banking committee chairman and
now its senior Republican. He was the prime author _ along with
ex-Rep. Fernand St Germain, D-R.I. and one-time chairman of the
House Banking Committee _ of the 1982 law deregulating the thrift
industry.
   Critics blame part of the current crisis on that legislation,
which allowed S&amp;Ls to expand their lending activities away from home
mortgages into more risky commercial ventures.
   _Gonzalez, a 72-year-old outspoken maverick who succeeded St
Germain as the banking committee chairman after St Germain was
defeated last November. Gonzalez wants to separate FSLIC, which
insures accounts in thrift institutions, from the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board, the government's umbrella agency for S&amp;L regulation. He
is sympathetic, however, to the plight of S&amp;Ls in Texas, the center
of the industry's insolvency.
   _Riegle, a one-time Republican with one of the most liberal
records in Congress. He is a relative neophyte on savings and loan
issues despite 12 years on the banking committee. While he has been
unsympathetic to allowing banks and S&amp;Ls to venture into new areas
of investment, he says it would be ``an enormous shift backwards''
to require thrift institutions to return to what was once their
prime line of business _ home mortgages.
   _Bentsen, whose home state is at the heart of the S&amp;L crisis, has
called the depositor fee proposal ``really very foolish.'' As
chairman of the Finance Committee, Bentsen will wield considerable
influence over any eventual solution to the S&amp;L crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
