<DOCNO> AP890203-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0618EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w BC-S&amp;LCrisis Adv05-2Takes   02-03 1177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-S&amp;L Crisis, Adv05-2 Takes,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Savings and Loans: An Industry Under Siege</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a bank examiner's nightmare: an
electronic run at American Savings and Loan Association of Stockton,
Calif., the nation's largest insolvent S&amp;L a year ago.
   Big depositors, worried that the long-troubled institution was on
the verge of toppling, sent wire orders yanking out nearly half a
billion dollars in the first two months of 1988 alone.
   Regulators ended the nightmare with a few soothing words. They
waved a magic wand called deposit insurance.
   The episode symbolizes both the great strength and the underlying
weakness of the U.S. system of insuring bank and S&amp;L deposits, a
system created half a century ago as part of Franklin D. Roosevelt's
New Deal.
   Bank run. The very words make financial regulators queasy and
evoke Depression-era memories of long lines of depositors anxiously
clutching savings passbooks.
   But the run at American Savings and Loan was straight from the
high-tech '80s. There were no mobs pressing at the institution's
doors; only clacking computer terminal keys and whirring magnetic
discs as money brokers withdrew their wealthy clients' cash.
   Officials at the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, the agency that
regulates nearly 3,000 federally insured S&amp;Ls, stopped the run in
mid-March with the simple announcement that they would protect all
depositors, even those with accounts exceeding the Federal Savings
and Loan Insurance Corp.'s $100,000 limit.
   Ironically, the deposit insurance that saved the California S&amp;L
also helped create the industry's mess. The insurance allows savings
and loan owners to put up a little of their own money, take in a lot
of deposits and gamble on risky loans, potentially at the taxpayers'
expense.
   That's what occurred with American Savings and Loan. Once a
conservative mortgage lender, new management took over in 1983 and
embarked on a program of rapid growth and aggressive real estate
lending. Bad loans grew and last December the FSLIC had to pay $1.7
billion to have the institution taken over by a new owner.
   If deposit insurance is part of the problem, it has also been a
source of security for millions and the only thing that has staved
off disaster for people who found that the repositories of their
life savings had gone under.
   `People have an almost mystical degree of confidence in the
federal sticker on the wall,'' says Robert Litan, a banking expert
at the Brookings Institution, a liberal Washington think tank.
   ``Even though the FSLIC is insolvent, they believe the government
can come up with the money somehow. George Bush just told them
that.''
   One week into his term, Bush made a point in his nationally
televised news conference of reassuring S&amp;L customers. Deposits in
the nation's S&amp;Ls ``are sound, they are good ... nothing is going to
change in that regard,'' the president said.
   How, then, did a once sleepy, seemingly secure industry come to
the point that it needed presidential pronouncements to steady its
customers' nerves? How did it sink so low that regulators would
pledge $31 billion to rescue 205 institutions in 1988 and still have
350 insolvent, but still open, institutions to babysit?
   The seeds of the ailment have been buried deep within from the
start. They lay in the inherent instability of borrowing short (from
depositors) and lending long (to home buyers for 20 or 30 years).
   That was fine during the long economic boom and stable interest
rates that followed World War II. S&amp;L executives lived by the 3-6-3
rule: Take in deposits at 3 percent interest, lend the money to home
buyers at 6 percent and hit the golf course by 3 p.m.
   By the late 1970s and early 1980s, however, the industry's
underpinnings had become wobbly. Inflation was soaring into double
digits and the Federal Reserve Board responded by pushing interest
rates past 20 percent. Money poured out of the thrifts, with their
low interest rates, and into high-yield money market mutual funds
offered by brokerage firms.
   By 1980, Congress felt it had little choice but to lift the 5.5
percent cap on interest paid to S&amp;L depositors or watch thrift
institutions shrivel. At the same time, the limit on federal
insurance was raised from $40,000 to $100,000 per account.
   Then, two year later, new laws gave thrift owners fresh
investment opportunities: commercial and consumer loans,
construction lending and direct investments in development projects.
   The idea was that diversification would give S&amp;Ls a chance to
enter more lucrative fields and grow less dependent on the roller
coaster housing market.
   Regulators also lifted rules limiting brokered deposits to 5
percent of the total. Brokers divy up the money of wealthy clients
and institutions into $100,000 chunks, parceling them out to
institutions paying the highest rates.
   Some thrifts thrived in the new climate, but many didn't have the
experience to succeed and saw their portfolios grow ever more shaky.
   Even more bedeviling were laws lying dormant in states such as
Texas, California and Florida giving thrifts power to make risky
investments. As long as the federal interest rate cap and the limit
on brokered deposits remained in place, institutions couldn't
attract enough deposits to get into risky areas in a big way.
   After 1982, that changed. Enter a new breed of player: the high
flier.
   Men like Don Dixon and Ed McBirney, who purchased small, staid
institutions such as Dixon's Vernon Savings and Loan and McBirney's
Sunbelt Savings, both in Texas and both later bailed out for
billions of dollars. These new owners opened up the phone lines,
scooped up brokered deposits and shoveled the money into risky
construction and development projects.
   Along the way they lived well and made powerful political friends
such as House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. McBirney threw lavish
parties at his North Dallas home, serving exotic game and dressing
servants in costume. He flew important customers on a Las Vegas
junket in a borrowed jet.
   Dixon lent his yacht, High Spirits, to California Rep. Tony
Coehlo, chief of the Democrats' congressional campaign committee,
for lucrative Democratic fund-raisers.
   The party lasted until 1986, when oil prices collapsed. Across
Texas, real estate projects begun on projections of $70-a-barrel oil
fell apart. Borrowers defaulted but the collateral they turned over
was now worth only a fraction of what they owed. Regulators estimate
that about half of the nation's S&amp;L problem is centered in Texas and
other oil states.
   As the comptroller of the currency, Robert Clarke, says of bank
failures, ``When the economic tide goes out, you find out who is
swimming naked.''
   And while more and more S&amp;Ls were becoming financially shaky, the
government had fewer cops _ S&amp;L examiners _ on the beat.
   The Reagan administration's budget office rebuffed Edwin Gray,
then chairman of the bank board, when he pleaded for money to hire
more and better-qualified examiners.
   In 1985, he did some administrative maneuvering, freeing the
examination force from White House budget controls. He raised
examiners' salaries and by last year the force had doubled.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w BC-S&amp;LCrisis Adv05-1stAdd   02-03 1134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-S&amp;L Crisis, Adv05-1st Add,1168</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: had doubled.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gray also began the process of requiring S&amp;L owners to put more
of their own money into their institutions. By 1991, the capital
requirement will be 6 percent.
   Previous regulators had relaxed the requirement from 5 percent to
3 percent, seeing the move as a way to give struggling thrifts
greater latitude to work out their problems. In the end, it just
created an incentive to gamble because S&amp;L owners had less of their
own money at risk. Economists call it ``moral hazard.''
   In fact, owners of the 350 insolvent institutions still open have
nothing left to lose, a situation ripe for fraud.
   Bank board Chairman M. Danny Wall says fraud contributes
significantly to 20 percent of all S&amp;L failures and plays some part
in 70 percent as managers swing for the bleachers in an attempt to
hit a financial home run and prevent bankruptcy.
   While the bank board's push for tougher capital rules and
supervision will help prevent future problems, it came too late to
head off today's crisis. By 1986, the FSLIC was broke.
   Early that year, the Reagan administration proposed selling bonds
to raise $15 billion and then assessing S&amp;Ls to pay off the bonds.
   The industry's biggest trade association, the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions, one of the most effective lobbies in
Washington, balked and found a good deal of sympathy on Captiol Hill.
   When Congress thought of thrift executives, the image was not of
Dixon and McBirney, but of George Bailey, the small town, idealistic
building and loan officer played by Jimmy Stewart in the 1946 movie
classic ``It's A Wonderful Life.''
   Congress dithered and finally, in August 1987, authorized $10.8
billion in industry-funded borrowing. By then, almost everyone knew
that would be only a down payment.
   Today, the General Accounting Office, the congressional auditing
agency, estimates it will cost $85 billion to close or merge all the
insolvent S&amp;Ls _ roughly $500 for every taxpayer in the nation.
   ``If you roll back the clock (to) five years ago, this was a $10
billion to $20 billion problem,'' said Litan of the Brookings
Institution. ``If we had shut them down then, we wouldn't have a
$100 billion problem today.''
   In the meantime, the bank board has been selling insolvent S&amp;Ls
to new owners, using as little government cash as possible. It
handled 205 last year _ a post-Depression record.
   Bank board members say they don't have the money to simply shut
down S&amp;Ls and pay off the depositors and that it's better to arrange
a rescue than to let an insolvent institution hemorrhage further.
   But private analysts say such deals, some of which offer large
tax benefits to the new owners, may come back to haunt the
government by requiring a second and more expensive generation of
rescues.
   Typically, a large part of the bank board's assistance is in the
form of a promissory note, on which it pays the acquiring
institution interest.
   At year's end, the FSLIC had $20.3 billion in such notes
outstanding. In 1988 alone, the agency issued $14.5 billion in the
bonds. The government is also guaranteeing owners of rescued S&amp;Ls
against loss on the existing loan portfolio.
   ``The risks to the government are unlimited,'' said Lowell L.
Bryan, an analyst for McKinsey &amp; Company Inc.
   Now, Congress and the White House are struggling to raise $85
billion to $100 billion to deal with the remaining 350 insolvent
thrifts, to pay off the promissory notes and make good on the loss
guarantees.
   Treasury Department officials have told members of Congress they
will propose another bond issue. The difficulty comes in deciding
where to get the $7 billion to $9 billion a year to pay off the
bonds.
   There are basically three choices, all painful:
   _Depositors could pay through a fee, but that could send money
pouring out of federally insured institutions and into money market
funds.
   _The institutions themselves could pay, but that means either
further erosion of fragile profit margins or depositors end up
paying through a lower return on their savings, which in turn could
also send them to money market funds.
   _The taxpayer could pay, but that would either cut President
Bush's already slim chances of keeping his ``no new taxes'' pledge
or mean deep cuts in other government programs.
   Meanwhile, troubles aren't over for S&amp;Ls, which lost a
post-Depression record of $9.4 billion in the first nine months of
1988.
   For one thing, the once-hot Northeast real estate market is
cooling, a potentially ominous sign for that region.
   For another, interest rates have been heading higher since last
spring, threatening to recreate on a smaller scale the interest rate
spread problems of a decade ago that got thrifts into trouble in the
first place.
   Moreover, the debate in Washington over how to solve the problem
of insolvent S&amp;Ls may in itself be making the situation worse as the
public becomes increasingly aware of the problem.
   ``The fear and uncertainty are growing with each succeeding
article. ... It's a real land mine,'' said Mark Riedy, president of
the National Council of Savings Institutions.
   ``If consumers get it in their heads that `I'm going to play it
safe and put my money under my pillow,' you have a real problem that
you're not going to stop very easily,'' he said.
   Public officials, including the president, need to drive home
again and again that the debate in Washington is over the best way
to raise the money to end the crisis, not over whether to protect
the deposits, he said.
   Along with finding the money, Congress must also look at some
sort of ``never again'' reforms guaranteeing that the government
will not be asked again to bail out the S&amp;L industry.
   There is some sentiment for turning back the clock, returning
thrifts to their traditional role of home mortgage lending and
steering them out of speculative commercial ventures.
   However, that ignores that overspecialization in housing is at
the root of the industry's trouble. Private analysts say it's both
too late and unwise to return to the days of George Bailey and the
Bedford Falls Building and Loan.
   ``Thrift viability in the long run is threatened by a return to
traditional mortgage lending, which according to my research has not
shown a profit in five years,'' said Andrew S. Carron, an analyst
with First Boston Corp.
   The bank board has already moved toward a number of key reforms _
bigger capital cushions and more vigorous regulatory supervision _
and Congress likely will reinforce that in some way.
   As to administrative changes, the bank board is almost sure to
lose some of its independence and may lose control over its
insurance fund.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
