<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv05   02-03 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 05,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun Feb. 05 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush and Administration Both Finding Voices</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a long-running serial with no final
installment, every president tries to find a formula that will
produce a smooth, mutually satisfactory system for dealing with the
White House press.
   President Bush and his advisers have been working on it, and
there already is some sniping from an institution that probably is
impossible to satisfy. Reporters always will have another question
and presidents won't always answer.
   That conflict is built into their jobs. It can be controlled but
it can't be eliminated.
   Before laryngitis temporarily stilled his voice, Bush held an
informal press conference his first day in office, then a pooled
interview, then a 43-minute televised news conference.
   Critics in the media promptly complained that reporters hadn't
been tough enough in their questions and that Bush hadn't been
specific enough in his answers.
   Vice President Dan Quayle held a briefing for reporters the other
day and stirred a micro-controversy because he wouldn't be quoted by
name.
   Bush asked White House reporters to advise him on press
conference ground rules but got no clear answer.
   There's a message in all this: Accessibility does not guarantee
satisfaction.
   Access was an issue, and a valid complaint, when Bush was waging
his winning campaign. There was virtually none because his managers
were determined to keep control of the news agenda.
   But during the transition, and in his first weeks as president,
Bush has proven far more accessible than Ronald Reagan ever was.
   There is a tradeoff. The Bush formula precludes questions shouted
on the White House lawn, or at picture-taking sessions or, as of
Wednesday night, by pool reporters representing the rest of the
press at White House social events.
   Reagan took questions at such events but seldom provided
meaningful information. Nevertheless, that made him appear
accessible to questioning newsmen.
   Bush has said he'd provide opportunities for meaningful questions
in place of the shouted ones. The news, of course, is not in the
questions anyhow. It is in the answers.
   The willingness of presidents to meet with reporters and answer
their questions varies with circumstances. In the best of times,
most presidents are very accessible. In the worst, they usually
avoid questions.
   Lyndon B. Johnson sometimes seemed bent on non-stop news
conferences, indoors and out, until Vietnam policy became an
overriding and tormenting issue. Richard M. Nixon clammed up during
the scandal that ended his presidency, save for periodic news
conferences he convened to protest his innocence and say that one,
then two years of Watergate was enough. Reagan's low access became
just about no access while the Iran-Contra scandal was unfolding.
   Bush openness will face its real trial when something goes badly
wrong.
   That latest Quayle controversy, hardly a blip compared with those
that hit him during the campaign, came when he took part in a
background briefing for reporters who covered his three-day trip to
Latin America.
   Such briefings are traditional prior to presidential and vice
presidential travels. They usually are conducted by members of the
National Security Council staff and by State Department experts on
the areas involved. They speak on condition that they be identified
only as administration officials. The briefings cover logistics and
explain U.S. policy in the areas involved.
   Quayle appeared at the briefing on his own trip, but couldn't be
identified by the reporters who attended. He could and was by
reporters who did not attend, and the background rules drew
criticism.
   But Quayle isn't the first top-level traveler to take a hand in a
trip briefing. Presidents sometimes have done so themselves.
   At the same time, the incident teaches one of the lessons of
politics at the top. If it's said, it might as well be said on the
record, because background rules, even off-the-record strictures are
must about impossible to keep.
   Spiro T. Agnew learned that the hard way in 1971, after a
midnight conversation in a Williamsburg, Va., hotel suite. He
invited a handful of reporters there for a nightcap, conversed off
the record for an hour or so _ and expressed misgivings about U.S.
overtures toward China. Nixon was just beginning the process that
restored U.S. ties to the Communist mainland. The vice president's
comments didn't stay off the record for long _ they found a way into
print the next day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington for more than 25
years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Sun Feb. 05 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
