<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-03 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0839</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales edged up a meager 0.9 percent
last year, the government said in a report analysts cited as
evidence that higher mortgage interest rates continue to dampen
activity in the housing market.
   Sales for all of 1988 totaled 677,000 dwellings, up from 671,000
sold during the previous year, the Commerce Department reported
Thursday. Home sales had plunged 10.5 percent in 1987, with the drop
blamed on rising interest rates and a slowdown in demand after five
strong sales years.
   Fixed-rate mortgages last week stood at 10.6 percent, up from
10.16 percent a year earlier, according to a survey by the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan says he
would prefer a gasoline tax increase to an oil import fee in the
event Congress cannot meet its deficit-reduction targets through
spending cuts alone.
   Greenspan told the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee
Thursday he would most prefer Congress cut spending to meet the
fiscal 1990 deficit target of $100 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has ignored a congressional request for
details about its sweeping probe of fraud in Chicago's commodities
markets, delaying reauthorization of the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission, the chairman of the House Agriculture Committee said.
   Lawmakers expected to act quickly this year to reauthorize the
CFTC, which regulates the nation's commodity markets, through 1994,
Rep. E ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, the House Agriculture
Committee chairman, said Thursday.
   But plans were altered by disclosure of a two-year, FBI
undercover investigation of alleged widespread fraud and illegal
trading practices in the Chicago futures markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu rebuked
bankers over ``irresponsible'' newspaper advertisements encouraging
savings and loan customers to withdraw their deposits, industry
officials said.
   Sununu raised the issue during a private, hour-long meeting
attended by President Bush, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady,
Budget Director Richard Darman and representatives of five bank and
S&amp;L groups, Frederick Webber, president of the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions, who attended the meeting, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance ministers of the world's largest
industrial economies gathered for a get-acquainted session with the
Bush administration with Third World debt the main topic on the
agenda.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady was host for the two days of
talks as the new administration got its first chance to explain its
economic policies to major allies.
   The finance ministers and central bank presidents of Japan, West
Germany, Great Britain, France, Canada and Italy were taking part in
the discussions, which began Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is promising continued good
U.S.-Japanese relations, telling Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita any
disputes between the nations are ``the differences of friends.''
   Takeshita was equally upbeat Thursday. Standing alongside Bush in
a departure ceremony at the White House, Takeshita said their
session ``marked a new start for U.S.-Japan cooperation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. posted a 23.8 percent
fourth-quarter earnings increase, although annual profits declined.
It also announced Thursday an estimated $500 million deal with
France's Renault to build a four-wheel drive vehicle code-named
``JJ.''
   The venture with Renault was the second the nation's No. 3
automaker disclosed with a foreign company during the past week.
Chrysler earlier this week announced it would market autos made in
Canada by South Korea's Hyundai Motor Corp., beginning in 1991.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department's chief safety official
is casting new doubt on whether a South Carolina reactor complex can
be restarted in time to avoid a squeeze on supplies of a material
vital to producing nuclear warheads.
   Richard Starostecki told a Senate Armed Services subcommittee
Thursday it was not likely that even one of the three reactors at
the Savannah River Plant near Aiken, S.C., would be able to operate
by the department's official target date of late 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popeyes Fried Chicken and Biscuits owner Al
Copeland has extended his $8-a-share offer to Church's Fried Chicken
shareholders, this time pushing the expiration date to Feb. 19.
   The move Thursday comes two days after Copeland's latest court
victory. On Tuesday, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals refused
to reconsider an earlier decision allowing Copeland to go ahead with
the bid.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market bounced back and forth aimlessly Thursday as
traders awaited the first statistical gauge of how the economy
started off 1989, the January unemployment rate. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials dropped 4.46 to 2,333.75.
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies in
listless trading. Gold prices slipped.
   Bond prices were little changed in slow activity.
   Orange juice futures prices turned decisively lower; precious
metals futures resumed their slide; grains and soybeans moved lower;
energy futures and livestock futures were mixed.
