<DOCNO> AP890203-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GMPlant     02-03 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Plant,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Take Wait-And-See Attitude Toward GM Plant Shutdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grniet in 3rd graf is cq; Will be topped with Dukakis remarks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than 10 years, General Motors
Corp.'s sprawling assembly plant here has been lurching and stalling
like an old duster.
   So frequent have been the layoffs and start-ups, union officials
said Thursday, that many of the 2,100 workers are skeptical about
GM's announcement that the plant will shut down indefinitely in
August.
   ``They're still in a wait-and-see mode,'' said Arthur T. Grniet,
a 24-year veteran of the plant. ``Because there have been so many
layoffs, the perception in everyone's mind is that, `I'll get called
back.'''
   But GM officials and industry analysts threw cold water on that
perception Thursday.
   ``I'd say the chances of that plant reopening are very low,
because GM still has too much production capacity,'' said Douglas
Laughlin, who follows the automaker for the Wall Street investment
firm Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   The plant, built in 1948, assembles two of GM's A-body cars, the
Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera and Buick Century. It was hit by temporary
shutdowns, ranging from a few weeks to several months, in 1977,
1981, 1982 and 1987.
   Adding to workers' optimism that this shutdown, too, will prove
to be temporary was the wording of GM's announcement. The automaker
said it would ``idle the plant for an indefinite period,'' rather
than shut it down permanently.
   But that wording in fact was dictated largely by the company's
contract with the United Auto Workers, which prevents it from
permanently shutting most factories.
   GM spokesman Dee Allen sought Thursday to underline that the
coming shutdown differs fundamentally from earlier ones.
   ``The real difference is that in the past, when the plant has had
to be shut down or a shift taken off, it's been because of a
temporary volume related adjustment,'' he said.
   This time, Allen said, GM has decided to reduce its productive
overcapacity and bring down costs by building A-cars only at its
plants in St. Therese, Quebec; Oklahoma City, Okla.; and Ramos
Aripze, Mexico.
   Those plants, which already build A-cars, can easily meet the
demand for the Olds Cutlass, Buick Century and other models in 1990
and beyond, he said.
   ``What that means is, we don't have a product to build in
Framingham anymore. That's very different from the simple volume
adjustments that we've had to make in the past,'' Allen said.
   Philip B. Ernst, chairman of Framingham's board of selectmen,
said Thursday he was optimistic GM would eventually decide to build
some other models in Framingham. But Allen was skeptical about that,
too.
   ``It isn't as if there is a shelf with a lot of products and all
you have to do is get someone to give you one,'' he said. ``There
aren't those products out there.''
   The plant's high point in recent years came in August 1987, when
GM invested $240 million in a new paint shop.
   Until this week's announcement, the low point was in November
1987, when the plant shut down indefinitely, laying off 3,700
workers. It reopened last May with the current 2,100 employees, more
than half of whom have 20 years or more of service.
   Allen refused to explain why GM chose to close the Framingham
operation rather than one of the other three A-car plants.
   ``Each facility has certain advantages and disadvantages _ some
are material, some are physical, some have to do with human factors.
You have to weigh all of those things when you make one of these
decisions,'' he said. ``GM is not going to discuss the specific
reasons behind its evaluation of a facility.''
</TEXT>
