<FIRST>r f BC-Europe-Airlines     02-03 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe-Airlines,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Airlines Say Traffic Growth, Delays Up in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nineteen percent of European airline
flights suffered delays of at least 15 minutes during 1988, up from
14.9 percent the previous year, a trade association reported Friday.
   The Association of European Airlines said the delays affected 13
million passengers, compared with 9.5 million in 1987.
   In its annual report, the group also said its 21-member airlines
posted a 6.1 percent growth in passenger traffic worldwide in 1988.
Growth was strongest on the European and Far Eastern routes, where
traffic rose 8.5 and 7.2 percent respectively, the report said.
   The annual report said the AEA airlines posted a 9.4 percent rise
in freight traffic ``with all regions except the Near and Middle
East contributing to the increase.''
