<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   02-03 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jobs Surge In January; Factory Orders Up; Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with factory orders; stock, bond
and dollar prices; central bank intervention to restrain dollar; picks
up 5th graf, The 408,000 ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment rose slightly in January to 5.4 percent, but the
number of jobs created last month shot up to 408,000, the government
said today in a report that indicated strong economic growth.
   The Labor Department said the civilian unemployment rate rose by
0.1 percentage point from the December rate of 5.3 percent.
   But the first major report of the economy's 1989 performance
showed continued strong growth, something analysts have predicted
would feed inflationary fears and perhaps convince the Federal
Reserve Board to tighten its reins on credit.
   In another report signaling vibrant economic growth, the Commerce
Department said orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods
surged 4.1 percent in December, the biggest rise in six months.
   Bond prices were modestly lower after the reports, indicating
investors' concerns about inflation caused by overheating. The yield
on the Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond, which rises when the price
falls, climbed to 8.84 percent from 8.80 percent late Thursday.
   The dollar rose on speculation that the Federal Reserve would
push up short-term rates to hold down inflation, making short-term
dollar-denominated securities more attractive to global investors.
   Not willing to let the dollar climb too high, central banks of
the United States, West Germany, France, Switzerland, Austria and
Belgium all reportedly intervened in the market to sell dollars.
   At midmorning in New York, the central banks' sales managed to
hold the dollar below the psychologically important level of 1.89
West German marks. The dollar rose, nevertheless, against the mark
and the British pound, while declining slightly against the Japanese
yen.
   Stock prices were mixed. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 8.93 to 2,342.68 in the first hour of trading.
   The 408,000 new nonfarm jobs created last month followed a gain
of 279,000 in December and nearly matched November's robust gain of
440,000 new jobs.
   Analysts had predicted that January job growth would be in the
250,000 range and that any growth of more than 300,000 could trouble
the markets.
   The Labor Department said the unemployment rate rose because the
number of people in the labor force grew even faster than the number
of people with jobs. The labor force expanded by nearly 900,000
people, with about 700,000 of them finding jobs. A record 62.9
percent of the working-age population had jobs.
   On Thursday, reports indicated that higher interest rates are
hurting the housing market but haven't dissuaded consumers from a
generous spending spree at the nation's big department stores.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday new home sales rose a
meager 0.9 percent last year to 677,000 dwellings, vs. 671,000 sold
in 1987. Housing industry analysts said they expected continued
increases in interest rates and a slowdown in the economy to result
in decreased new home sales this year.
   ``The bottom's not falling out of the market by any means but we
do expect a modest slowing,'' said economist Richard Peach of the
Mortgage Bankers Association.
   Fixed-rate mortgages last week stood at 10.6 percent, up from
10.16 percent a year earlier, according to a survey by the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Many economists are predicting interest
rates could hit 11.5 percent by the middle of this year.
   Tighter credit evidently isn't hurting the nation's biggest
retailers, however. Most said Thursday in reporting January sales
that they benefited from light inventories and an unusually warm
winter.
   The low inventory levels, due to unexpectedly brisk Christmas
business and tight control of stocks, saved general merchandise and
apparel retailers from having to slash prices to move out the excess
goods.
   Patterns of retail purchases are closely watched for indications
of overall consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of the
country's overall economic activity.
   In other economic news Thursday, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said he would prefer a gasoline tax increase to an oil
import fee in the event Congress cannot meet its deficit-reduction
targets through spending cuts alone.
   Greenspan told the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee in
Washington he would most prefer that Congress cut spending to meet
the fiscal 1990 deficit target of $100 billion.
   None of the Thursday developments had much effect on the
financial markets. Stocks meandered and the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 4.46 to 2,333.75; bond prices barely budged; and the
dollar ended mixed in slow trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
