<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed early today on the Chicago Board of Trade with bullish fears
of cold-weather damage to the winter wheat crop offset by slack
foreign demand for U.S. grains.
   The winter wheat crop appeared to be most vulnerable in Kansas
and Nebraska, where temperatures have plunged after rising in the
past week to levels high enough to cause some seed germination.
   ``The biggest threat is heaving of the ground where you have
alternate hot and cold,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``We've certainly had the warm part of it and now it looks like
we'll have the cold,'' he said.
   Export sales of U.S. grains and soybeans have slowed to a crawl,
and there was little news to influence corn and soybean prices.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to 1} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.27 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.71} a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.16 a bushel; soybeans were
2{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with March at $7.62{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .13 cent higher with February at
75.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with March at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to
.50 cent higher with February at 43.90 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent to .25 cent higher with February at 39.80
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
