<HEAD>North Korea's Economy Facing Range Of Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Korea-Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea's economy is facing
difficulties with its growing foreign debt, sluggish exports and
deteriorating productivity resulting from tight government controls,
reports say.
   Figures published Friday and attributed to the South Korean
government showed North Korea had a trade deficit of $720 million in
1987. Exports were listed at $1.67 billion and imports at $2.39
billion.
   No figures for 1988 were available.
   The Joong-ang Daily News quoted government officials in Seoul as
saying North Korea's economy is nearly bankrupt, forcing the
communist North to seek economic cooperation with other nations
including capitalist South Korea, its archrival since the Korea
peninsula was divided at the end of World War II.
   North Korea's trade has been highly dependent on its communist
allies, especialth Korea's trade volume was estimated at
$88.3 billion, compared with North Korea's $4 billion.
