<HEAD>London Shares Close With Broad Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed broadly higher in active
trading Friday on the London Stock Exchange, as the market resumed
its steep climb after a brief pause earlier this week.
   At the close of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 26.5 points, or 1.3 percent, at 2,069.9.
   The 100-share index was up as much as 34.6 points at midday. At
its lowest, the index was up 3.8 points at the opening.
   Stock was still in short supply, and that accentuated the gains,
dealers said. In addition, shares were led higher by a brisk run in
the stock futures market, which dealers said ignited a sharp jump in
equity prices shortly after the opening.
   ``Once again the futures did seem to lead the market up,'' a
dealer said. ``There was no way (the market) was going to stay
down.''
   Volume expanded to 768.7 million shares from 571.2 million on
Thursday.
   Wall Street's resilience to apparently negative U.S. economic
figures also encouraged the London market to advance, dealers said.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials opened lower following news
that U.S. employment gained at a faster-than-expected rate in
January. But a turnaround by the Dow Jones index into positive
territory spurred the London market to hold on to most of its early
gains.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 21.2 points at 1,689.0
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 16.46 points
to close at 1,167.78.
</TEXT>
