<SECOND>BC-Polaroid-Shamrock,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Nominees Announced for Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc., which is waging a
proxy fight for control of Polaroid Corp., on Friday announced a
slate of 14 candidates for the board of the instant-camera company.
   Shamrock, the investment vehicle for Roy E. Disney, nephew of the
late animator Walt Disney, has been pressing an unsolicited $3.2
billion buyout of Polaroid, and last month buttressed that strategy
by launching the proxy war.
   Disney's nominees will stand for election to the Polaroid board
at the Cambridge, Mass., company's annual shareholders' meeting May
9.
   Polaroid's board has 13 members; a 14th management candidate is
to be nominated before the meeting.
   Disney is offering Polaroid shareholders $45 a share for their
stock.
   In July, the California investor made an unsolicited friendly
offer of $40 a share to buy Polaroid with the consent of management.
When that offer was spurned, he made a tender offer to shareholders
in September of $42 a share. That price was sweetened to $45 a share
on Jan. 19.
   Among those on Shamrock's slate of nominees are Disney, Stanley
P. Gold, president and chief executive of Shamrock, and Frank G.
Wells, president and chief operating officer of The Walt Disney Co.,
in which Shamrock holds stock.
</TEXT>
