<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-03 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed little changed Friday after
central banks choked off a rally in the currency brought on by
bullish news on the U.S. economy.
   After a strong surge after the release of the economic reports,
the dollar ended narrowly higher against the West German mark and
British pound but lower against the Japanese yen and Canadian dollar.
   Gold prices, after dipping as low as $387 a troy ounce, ended up
slightly higher. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
bullion was bid at $391.50 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from
$391.10 late Thursday.
   The Labor Department said non-farm payrolls rose by 408,000 jobs
in January, well above market expectations. The strong job growth
overshadowed the announcement that the unemployment rate rose 0.1
percentage point to 5.4 percent in January.
   Also, the Commerce Department said factory orders shot up 4.1
percent in December, the biggest monthly gain since June.
   The twin reports indicated to investors that the Federal Reserve
would have to keep short-term interest rates high to prevent the
economy from overheating. ``There's still very strong short-term
rates here, and that's what's bringing money into the country,''
said Dan Brooks, chief dealer of Westpac Banking Corp. in New York.
   Traders in Europe and the United States said the dollar's upward
move was countered by coordinated dollar sales by the central banks
of the United States, West Germany, the Netherlands, France, Italy,
Belgium, Switzerland and Austria.
   In Tokyo, where trading ended before the release of the U.S.
economic reports, the dollar fell 0.48 yen to a closing 129.27 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 129.40 yen. In New York, the
dollar dipped to 129.40 from 129.58 late Thursday.
   In London, the dollar rose against the pound, which cost $1.7410,
cheaper than $1.7515 on Thursday. In New York the dollar also
strengthened. The pound fell to $1.7420 from $1.7452 Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8790 West German marks, up from
1.8775; 1.5949 Swiss francs, up from 1.5945; 1.1833 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1894; 6.3880 French francs, unchanged; and
1,371.8 Italian lire, up from 1,371.3.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8805 West German marks, up from 1.8700; 1.5983
Swiss francs, up from 1.5923; 6.3950 French francs, up from 6.3735;
2.1240 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1135; 1,374.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,368.50; and 1.1885 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1882.
   Gold prices were lower in Europe but rose by the end of trading
in New York.
   In London, gold traded at a late bid price of $388.25 a troy
ounce, down from $392.25 bid late Thursday. In Zurich, the bid price
for gold was $389.90, down from $391.50 bid late Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $393.10 a troy ounce, up from $392.30 late
Thursday.
   Silver was quoted in London on Friday at a bid price of $5.83 a
troy ounce, down from Thursday's $5.86. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $5.835 an ounce from $5.823.
</TEXT>
