<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe Bjt   02-03 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe, Bjt,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Mix Threats, Promises In Quest For Traders' Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities are increasing their pressure
on traders and brokers in an effort to win cooperation in their
investigation of fraud in the world's two largest commodities
exchanges, sources said Friday.
   The U.S. attorney's office in Chicago has shown some futures
traders evidence of at least one type of trading offense and has
invited them to share information in exchange for immunity from
prosecution, reduced charges or a recommendation for a lenient
sentence, say attorneys for some of those subpoenaed over the past
two weeks.
   The pressure increasingly applied being to selected traders and
brokers is helping to sharpen the focus of the government's two-year
undercover investigation of the Chicago Board of the Trade and the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, the lawyers said.
   ``It tells me they need cooperation,'' said John Troelstrup, an
attorney with a number of clients who have been contacted by the
U.S. attorney's office.
   ``It tells me that the eerie feeling that they're not focusing on
anything more than a routine trade-practices investigation may be on
the mark,'' he said.
   Anton Valukas, the U.S. attorney for the northern district of
Illinois, has refused to confirm the existence of the investigation,
which was disclosed by the Chicago Tribune on Jan. 19. Speculation
about the purpose of the probe has ranged from rooting out trading
fraud to documenting the laundering of drug money.
   Defense lawyers said federal prosecutors have shown some traders
evidence of ``bag trading.'' In the illegal technique, a floor
broker conspires with another trader _ the ``bag man'' _ to sell a
customer's futures contract at the low end of an official price
range and to buy it back for a different customer at the high end of
the range.
   The transaction produces a profit for the bag man, which he
splits with his trading.
   Futures are binding contracts for delivery of a commodity at a
specified price on a specified date. Producers and consumers of
commodities use the futures markets to lock in prices in advance,
while speculators use them to bet on price movements.
   Prosecutors also have told some brokers or their attorneys they
were prepared to accept ``proffer letters,'' from people under
investigation, defense attorneys said.
   In a proffer letter, a potential defendant lays out the
information he is willing to provide in exchange for immunity, a
lesser charge or prosecutor's recommendation for leniency. If no
such deal is struck, prosecutors agree not to use the information to
prosecute the individual.
   One lawyer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said proffer
letters were fairly routine in criminal investigations.
   But Troelstrup said it was unusual for federal authorities to let
it be known publicly, albeit through unofficial channels, that they
were willing to negotiate plea bargains.
   The government also is seeking handwriting samples from some of
those subpoenaed by asking them to write down the trading-badge
numbers of certain other traders at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
defense lawyers said.
   Troelstrup said federal authorities may want to compare the
handwriting samples with the handwriting on trading cards obtained
by subpoena. Futures traders record on trading cards the price,
quantity, time and badge number of the opposing buyer or seller for
each trade they make.
   Meanwhile, the Chicago Tribune reported Friday that Chicago Board
of Trade officials were drafting a document that would prohibit
floor brokers from trading both for their own accounts and on behalf
of customers. Dual trading, which is unique to futures markets, has
been criticized as inviting trading abuse.
   Board of Trade spokesman Michael O'Connell would not confirm the
report, saying only that dual trading was one of the issues being
examined by an internal committee formed earlier this week to make
recommendations to the exchange's board of directors.
   In a statement unrelated to the investigation, the Chicago Merc
said Friday it had fined Timothy S. Fox, a trader in the Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 stock-index futures pit, $50,000 for making pre-arranged
trades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SeabrookFinances     02-03 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Finances,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>PSNH to Pay $2 Million To Former Seabrook Owners So They Won't Sue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Co. of New Hampshire
disclosed Friday it has agreed to pay $2 million to four former
owners of the Seabrook nuclear power plant so that they won't sue
the utility over its management of the stalled project.
   The agreement is part of a deal under which Public Service, which
sought bankruptcy protection a year ago because of its 36 percent
Seabrook share, would assume $30 million in plant payments being
skipped by the owner of the fourth-largest share, Massachusetts
Municipal Wholesale Electric Co.
   In return for making MMWEC's payments _ which would keep the
project afloat through May 1990 _ Public Service wanted all present
and former Seabrook owners to agree not to sue it. Public Service
denies mismanaging the project but says it wants to avoid expensive
litigation over it.
   Central Maine Power Co., which formerly owned 6 percent of
Seabrook and initially refused to waive its right to sue Public
Service, now has signed on.
   But Vermont Electric Cooperative, New Hampshire Electric
Cooperative and Hudson Power &amp; Light Co. of Massachusetts _ which
own a total of about 4 percent of Seabrook _ won't go along, Public
Service spokesman Nicholas Ashooh confirmed Friday.
   Public Service's bankruptcy judge, James Yacos, must approve the
agreement for assuming the MMWEC payments, and the utility on Friday
told him how it got Central Maine and the other former owners to
sign on.
   Public Service said it would pay $1.2 million in cash to Central
Maine, Maine Public Service Co., Bangor Hydro-Electric Co. of Maine
and Central Vermont Public Service Co. Ashooh said Public Service
also would waive $800,000 in debt from Central Maine.
   Those companies sold their Seabrook shares, totaling 12 percent
of the project, to a subsidiary of Eastern Utilities Associates of
Massachusetts in 1986.
   Public Service disclosed some details of its Seabrook funding
deal as it asked Yacos for another extension of the deadline for the
project's past and present owners to file claims against it in
bankruptcy court.
   Yacos previously had granted three extensions of the deadline for
claims against Public Service, and said last month there would be
``no further extensions'' beyond Feb. 9. But on Friday he granted
one more extension, to Feb. 24.
   Seabrook, its pricetag now $5.8 billion, was completed in July
1986 but remains idle because of problems with finances and
evacuation planning.
   MMWEC, which owns 12 percent of Seabrook, stopped making payments
of about $1.5 million a month to the project last summer. Plant
officials initially said they hoped to complete arrangements for
assuming $30 million of MMWEC's payments by Sept. 15.
   An interim funding arrangment expired Nov. 30; plant officials
say some owners have been making the payments since, but they won't
give specifics.
   The federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission ruled in December that
Seabrook's financial problems do not pose a safety concern for
low-power atomic tests, but appeared to leave the issue open for
commercial licensing. Seabrook officials hope to start low-power
tests within the next month and gain a commercial license by year
end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890203-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   02-03 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late January Sales Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks rose 5.6
percent in late January, bolstered by a strong performance by Ford
Motor Co. and continued solid truck sales, the manufacturers
reported Friday.
   One analyst suggested that Ford's 14.8 percent increase in sales
of domestically made cars may stem from late-January fleet sales.
Fleet customers include all those who buy more than 10 vehicles a
year, such as rental car companies, police forces and firms that
provide employees with cars.
   The automakers reported they sold cars and light trucks at a
daily rate of 41,798 vehicles during the Jan. 21-31 period this
year, compared with a rate of 39,571 during the same period a year
ago.
   Car sales were up 5.3 percent, based on Ford's performance, and
truck sales rose 6.3 percent during the period, in which there were
nine selling days both years. General Motors Corp.'s U.S.-made car
sales rose 2.1 percent while Chrysler Corp.'s fell 11.9 percent in
late January compared with the same period last year.
   ``I think there might have been a little blip in their number
from fleets,'' said analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman
Hutton in New York. ``You normally see that in the latter part of
the year.''
   Sales in December of last year were very strong while the
car-selling market softened somewhat in the first part of January.
   ``There is still a great deal of concern that strong fleet sales
throughout the fourth quarter may have been masking some possible
deterioration in the retail marketplace,'' Phillippi said.
   Another analyst, David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in
New York, said Ford's share of the domestic car market _ about 30.7
percent _ is nearly the same as it has been lately.
   ``I think if you take the month as a whole, the weak early
January and the late strength, I think if you smooth out the last
few months, car sales are a little weaker,'' he said. ``But there's
so much noise in these numbers that it's hard to tell.''
   Industry-wide, car and truck sales in the United States dropped 5
percent during January. Sales of imported vehicles dropped 18.2
percent while sales of vehicles made in the United States fell 0.4
percent.
   Ford said its car sales rose 14.8 percent during the period to a
daily rate of 8,426 during late January this year, compared with a
daily rate of 7,339 during the same time last year. Meantime, sales
of U.S.-made trucks by Ford rose 4.9 percent to a daily rate of
5,115 this year from a rate of 4,873 during late January last year.
   For the entire month, Ford's car sales have risen 3.6 percent
while its truck sales increased 4.9 percent.
   Chrysler showed the biggest decline in late-January car sales,
dipping 11.9 percent to a daily rate of 3,180 this year compared
with a rate of 3,607 last year.
   But truck sales for Chrysler led the Big Three, going up 8.1
percent in late January 1989 to a rate of 3,452 compared with a rate
of 3,193 last year.
   For all of January this year, Chrysler's car sales were 6.7
percent lower than January last year, while truck sales were up 12
percent.
   GM said its car sales rose 2.1 percent in late January, to a
daily rate of 12,899 this year from a rate of 12,631 last year.
Truck sales rose 4.1 percent to a daily rate of 5,213 this year from
5,009 last year.
   For the month, GM sold 11.1 percent fewer cars this year compared
with last year and 1.7 percent more trucks.
</TEXT>
