<FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     02-03 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices fell slightly in active trading
Friday as the market shrugged off inflationary fears triggered by a
government unemployment report indicating robust economic expansion.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell \ point, or about
$2.50 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from its price, rose to 8.83 percent from 8.80 percent
late Thursday.
   Analysts said the bond market climbed in afternoon trading after
an early sell-off in response to the Labor Department's report that
408,000 new nonfarm jobs were created last month, well above
expectations of about 300,000.
   The report was viewed as a sign of rapid economic expansion,
triggering some inflationary fears, analysts said. But many traders
attributed the increase to unseasonably warm January weather that
created more construction jobs.
   ``The market seems to want to be fairly strong,'' said Robert
Chandross, chief economist with Lloyds Bank PLC in New York. ``Part
of the rise of employment was excused away because of the weather
and its impact on construction.''
   He said the market also was buoyed by rumors that the weekly
nationwide survey of purchasing managers, a key economic indicator
released on Mondays, would show a lower reading, implying an
economic slowdown.
   But William Sullivan, director of money market research at Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said the employment data were strong enough to
force the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates to slow
the economy as a hedge against higher inflation.
   ``Even if you exclude (construction) you see a very buoyant set
of labor data and it does suggest the economy is taking a strong
tick in the new year,'' he said. ``Against that data I would look
for some tightening in credit policy.''
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell 3-16 point, intermediate maturities fell 3-16 point
and long-term issues also were down 3-16 point, according to
Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.90 to 1,137.90.
   In corporate trading, industrials inched up. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.04
to 299.77.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds was down 3-32 point at 92 5-32. The average
yield to maturity rose to 7.57 percent from 7.56 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.76 percent as the
discount rose nine basis points to 8.47 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 9.01 percent as the discount rose 11 basis points to
8.52 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.14 percent as the
discount rose 11 basis points to 8.47 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was unchanged at 9 percent.
</TEXT>
