<FIRST>u f AM-ColaWars     02-03 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cola Wars,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Fires Back, Coca-Cola Says Pepsi Panicking in Cola Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybe somebody should send Coke and Pepsi to
their rooms until they cool off.
   In the latest volley of the cola wars, Pepsi-Cola Co. is running
a new commercial tweaking Diet Coke's recent 3-D ads and disputing
claims about how many Pepsi drinkers are switching to Diet Coke.
   Coca-Cola Co. fired back, saying its campaign to position
third-ranked Diet Coke as a challenger to regular Pepsi's spot as
the nation's No. 2 soft drink ``apparently has set off a panic at
Pepsi.''
   ``We've struck a sensitive chord,'' said Michael A. Beindorff,
vice president for Atlanta-based Coca-Cola.
   That's not the way Pepsi sees it. Spokesman Tod MacKenzie said
late Friday it appeared that Pepsi's new ads scored ``a solid right
to the corporate chin'' with its ads attacking the credibility of
Coke's claims.
   Pepsi has complained about Coke's ad claims to the three major
television networks, which are reviewing them. Coca-Cola says it
plans to complain to the networks about Pepsi's new ad, which began
running Thursday night.
   Jesse Meyers, publisher of the trade newsletter Beverage Digest,
said the attention that the two soft drink giants are paying to
their diet colas illustrates the growing importance of the diet
segment of the $43 billion retail soda market as the population ages
and becomes more weight conscious.
   Diet Coke started the latest exchange with commercials on last
month's broadcast of the Super Bowl football game that took the
unusual approach of going against regular Pepsi rather than Diet
Pepsi.
   ``Last year, nearly two million families stopped buying Pepsi and
more of them moved to Diet Coke than any other major soft drink,''
the ads say.
   The campaign theme is ``The move is on to Diet Coke'' and the ads
employ ``Miami Vice'' star Don Johnson, an ex-Pepsi pitchman, to
reinforce the point.
   The ads attracted heightened attention because they first aired
in connection with Coke's sponsorship of the Super Bowl halftime
show, the first live network broadcast in three-dimensions.
Coca-Cola bottlers distributed about 20 million pairs of special
glasses so viewers could get the 3-D effect in both the show and an
ad for Diet Coke.
   Pepsi said Coca-Cola's claim was misleading because millions of
families switch to other brands every year, and asked the networks
to pull the ads or demand modifications.
   According to the trade newsletter Beverage Digest, Pepsi's market
share fell 0.1 percentage point to 18.7 percent in 1988, while Diet
Coke and its caffeine-free version rose to 10.2 percent from 9.4
percent in 1987 and Diet Pepsi and its caffeine-free version rose to
6.6 percent from 6.1 percent.
   Pepsi also developed an ad that it began airing Thursday on
network TV.
   It shows a man making a presentation in a boardroom, his back to
the camera as he gestures at a chart that shows Diet Coke sales
rising.
   As the presentation proceeds, a narrator says, ``Last year, two
million families stopped buying Diet Coke and over a million new
families started buying Diet Pepsi. So what's giving Diet Coke such
a distorted view?''
   The answer becomes obvious, as the man turns toward the camera,
wearing 3-D glasses. ``Gentlemen, I trust we are all seeing this the
same way,'' he said as viewers see the other executives are also
wearing the 3-D glasses.
   Meyers said there are elements of truth in both campaigns. Diet
Coke's market share closed the lead on regular Pepsi last year, he
said. But by some measures, he said Diet Pepsi has grown more
rapidly than Diet Coke.
   But, he added, ``You can't have `cola wars' without skirmishes.''
</TEXT>
