<FIRST>r f AM-NewspaperSale     02-03 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper Sale,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scripps Announces Sale of Hollywood Sun-Tattler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.W. Scripps Co. on Friday announced an
agreement to sell The Sun-Tattler to a media organization affiliated
with the Dallas Times Herald. Terms were not disclosed.
   The buyer is DTH Media Inc., which bought the Dallas newspaper in
June 1988.
   Scripps, which is based in Cincinnati, has owned the Sun-Tattler,
a morning newspaper published Monday-through-Saturday, since 1965
and will continue to publish it as usual until the transfer of
ownership is complete.
   Scripps had announced its intention to sell the paper on Oct. 26,
saying its newspaper operations had been unprofitable.
   The Sun-Tattler, with 164 employees and a circulation of 31,000,
was founded as the Weekly Sun in 1935, and merged with the South
Broward Tattler in 1942. It expanded to five days a week in 1959 and
six days in 1963.
   Scripps is a diversified media company which operates 19 daily
newspapers, nine television stations, 5 radio stations and cable
television systens in 10 states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
